<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Soviets     08-22 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Soviets,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Up To 710 Soviets Killed In Afghan Rocket Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British newspaper said Tuesday up to 710 Soviet
soldiers and civilians were killed in a rocket attack by Afghan
rebels on a military base north of Kabul, the capital of
Afghanistan.
   The Daily Telegraph said its account of the rocket assault, that
occurred either Aug. 10 or 11, was based on reports received in
Peshawar, Pakistan, from Afghan guerrillas.
   Earlier reports had surfaced from diplomatic and guerrilla
sources of the attack on the Kalagay military base 100 miles north
of Kabul, but they had few details and a lower death toll.
   Daily Telegraph correspondent James Bone in Peshawar reported a
spokesman for a guerrilla group said the rockets devastated the
Kalagay ammunition depot and turned the Soviet compound into an
inferno.
   Bone quoted the spokesman, who was not identified, as saying,
``Maybe it was lucky but it was a good hit and our greatest day.''
   Western diplomatic sources in Islamabad had said at least 109
Soviet soldiers died at Kalagay.
   Bone said the casualties were much higher according to a report
written on cloth by Muhibullah Khan, a guerrilla commander in the
Kalagay district, and received in Peshawar.
   Bone said Muhibullah Khan's report quoted a leader of the
government militia as saying 598 Soviet soldiers and 112 Soviet
civilians were killed and 284 Soviets were wounded. He wrote that
the report said the guerrillas fired eight 107mm rockets into the
supply base.
   Western reporters generally are barred from Afghanistan and
there was no independent confirmation of conflicting claims by the
government and guerrillas.
   If the report attributed to Muhibullah Khan was accurate, it
would be possibly the worst single loss by Soviet forces since they
entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help the Marxist government
battle the rebels.
   Under an accord signed by Afghanistan and Pakistan with Soviet
participation last April, all Soviet military personnesl are to be
withdrawn from Afghanistan by Feb. 15. The Soviet Union had up to
115,000 troopers in the country but announced that half of the
force had been removed as of Aug. 15 according to the withdrawal
schedule.
   The anti-communist guerrillas did not participate in the peace
negotiations and have vowed to continue their fight.
</TEXT>
