<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 6thLd-Writethru a0749 08-22 1022</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0749,1000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Reagan Aides Coach Quayle For Solo Trip, Bush Defends Him To
Vets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 6th pvs, Presidential nominee...to
end, to update with reports on national guard situation in 1969;
SUBS 10th graf, Thompson is ... to appear, to CORRECT to Quayle
sted Bush being invited; edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle told a veterans group Monday
``absolutely no influence was used'' to get him into the Indiana
National Guard during the height of the Vietnam War.
   In brief remarks to a convention of the Veterans of Foreign Wars
in Chicago, the Republican vice presidential nominee: ``Influence
was not even necessary if I had chosen to use it, which I never
would have.
   ``The reason is because my Indiana National Guard unit had
openings before I applied, they had openings when I applied, and
they had openings after I applied. So there was absolutedly no
influence used.''
   The crowd of about 2,500 veterans cheered and whistled turing
the hastily called appearance, in which the Indiana senator joked:
   ``My national guard unit was never called up to active duty, but
let me say that after these last 72 hours no one can say I've never
faced combat.''
   Presidential nominee George Bush and his aides have sought to
play down suggestions that Quayle's candidacy needed shoring up
after a rocky week dominated by the controversy over whether
Quayle, a pro-military conservative on Capitol Hill, pulled strings
to enter the National Guard in 1969 as his college draft deferment
was about to end.
   In a report in Tuesday's editions of The Washington Post, the
guard official who swore in Quayle said he received no special
treatment. Retired major general Alfred F. Ahner said in a
telephone interview that ``there had to have been a vacancy before
he enlisted.''
   The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer reported, however, that records
show the guard under a virtual freeze on recruitment imposed 49
days before Quayle's enlistment on May 19, 1969.
   The documents also appear to contradict assertions from some
former Indiana Guard officers that the Guard had more than 200
vacancies and therefore was open to Quayle without special
treatment or favoritism, the story said.
   At the VFW conference, where Bush had appeared earlier Monday,
Quayle also said he hoped to put the issue of his military record
behind him so attention could be focused on ``the real issues'' of
the campaign.
   ``The question before all of us is: Not what Dan Quayle did 20
years in the past _ but what either President Bush or President
Dukakis will do in the future to secure world peace,'' Quayle said.
   The circumstances surrounding Quayle's unplanned, last-minute
appearance before the veterans group were in dispute. Wade LaDue,
the spokesman for the organization, said Quayle was invited Monday
after Illinois Gov. James Thompson intervened with Commander in
Chief Earl Stock.
   Thompson is a key Bush supporter in Illinois. Quayle press
secretary David Prosperi said Stock made the invitation. Kevin
Morris, communications director for the Bush campaign in Illinois,
said members of the VFW encouraged Thompson to persuade Quayle to
appear.
   Quayle flew back to the nation's capital Sunday, accompanied by
James A. Baker III, Bush's campaign chairman and top strategist, to
meet with the new campaign staff assembled for him by Bush aides.
   Bush departed from his prepared remarks to a Veterans of Foreign
Wars convention in Chicago on Monday to defend his running mate:
   ``Dan Quayle served in the National Guard, signing up in a unit
that had vacancies at the time and now he is under shrill partisan
attack,'' Bush said, his voice rising. ``So let his attackers cast
the first stone. He served honorably. True, he didn't go to
Vietnam, but his unit wasn't sent.
   ``But there's another truth _ he did not go to Canada, he did
not burn his draft card and he damned sure didn't burn the American
flag,'' Bush said, drawing cheers and a standing ovation from the
veterans.
   Quayle is scheduled to return to the campaign trail Wednesday,
certain to face more questions about the Guard issue and how he got
into law school when he did not meet admission requirements.
   He is to attend legislative conferences in Cincinnati and
Lexington, Ky., before traveling to St. Louis, where aides say he
will deliver a major address to the Enlisted Association of the
National Guard, composed of current and former enlisted personnel.
   Meanwhile, Newsweek magazine reported that during his 1980
Senate campaign, Quayle referred to himself in political pamphlets
as a ``Vietnam-era veteran.'' Quayle dropped the reference after
objections by some Vietnam combat veterans. Although the reference
was technically correct, Newsweek said that his National Guard duty
was not the type of service implied in the leaflet.
   In the interview, Quayle also said his influential family didn't
pull strings to get him admitted to Indiana University Law School.
   The staff that the Bush campaign has assembled for Quayle is a
group with substantial experience in the White House and
presidential politics.
   Stuart Spencer, a longtime Reagan adviser and member of the
president's ``kitchen cabinet,'' is chairing Quayle's campaign. His
deputy is Joseph Canzeri, known as an expert detail man during his
years in the Reagan White House.
   Spencer, long a Reagan intimate, is a savvy strategist who has
been at Reagan's side in most of his political decisions.
   Canzeri served Nelson Rockefeller, titan of the Republican
Party's moderate wing, for nearly 20 years. A presidential
assistant and deputy to Reagan aide Michael Deaver, Canzeri was
known as a Mr. Fixit in the White House for his quick humor and
ability to get things done.
   Canzeri resigned in 1982 under a cloud after accepting mortgages
from friends at favorable interest rates and double-billing the
White House and the Republican National Committee for ``$700 and
change'' for two dinners he gave while out of the country preparing
for presidential trips. The Justice Department later concluded that
Canzeri did not violate federal law.
   Quayle's press secretary, Prosperi, was Interior Secretary
Donald Hodel's spokesman and also worked at the Reagan White House.
</TEXT>
