<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0000EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WickesBuyout     08-21 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wickes Buyout,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wickes `White Knight' Sigoloff Makes Leveraged Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sanford C. Sigoloff, the corporate
``White Knight'' who rescued Wickes Cos. Inc. from bankruptcy five
years ago, on Sunday announced a management-led leveraged buyout
offer of $12 a share.
   The retail giant, including the Builder's Emporium and Wickes
Furniture stores, also announced a net loss of $12.4 million for
the second quarter ended July 30, said company spokesman Michael
Sitrick.
   Sigoloff disclosed that WII Holdings Corp., a firm he
established with members of his Wickes management team, will offer
to purchase nearly 40 million shares of outstanding common stock,
Sitrick said. He said WII stands for W-2 or Wickes 2.
   The offer is nearly $3 higher than Wickes' closing stock price
of 9] on the New York Stock Exchange last Friday.
   ``While I have strong confidence in the long-term viability and
prospects of our continuing businesses,'' Sigoloff said in a
prepared statement, ``it has become increasingly clear to me, as
well as the other directors of the company, that our stockholders
want to maximize the value of their investment in the company in
the immediate near-term.''
   The 39,846,600 shares sought in the merger deal represent about
83 percent of Wickes' outstanding shares, Sitrick said.
   The offer is scheduled to be in effect from Aug. 26 to Oct. 20,
he said.
   It is expected that the principal investors in WII Holdings will
be institutional investors, including Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
which promised no problems in arranging financing for the buyout,
Sitrick said.
   The offer is void if fewer than 50 percent of outstanding shares
are sold, he said.
   The company's net loss for the second quarter amounted to 28
cents a share, with reported earnings of $10.4 million, or 19 cents
a share, on sales of $937.9 million and losses from discontinued
operation of $22.8 million, or 47 cents a share.
   In April 1982, Wickes, with assets estimated at about $3
billion, became the largest U.S. company to file for bankruptcy
protection. But less than two years later, creditors approved a
plan allowing Wickes to emerge from Chapter 11 proceedings.
   Analysts had predicted it would take Wickes at least five years
to erase the accumulated red ink.
   The force behind the comeback was Sigoloff, who earned the
nickname ``Ming the Merciless'' for the tough-minded business moves
and hard-nosed cost cutting he employed to resuscitate two other
Los Angeles companies in the 1970s: Republic Corp. and Daylin Inc.
   Sigoloff reorganized Wickes by selling off seasonal divisions
such as MacGregor Golf and Wickes Agriculture. At the same time he
revamped store displays and appeared in television commercials and
offered his personal guarantee of renewed product quality and
service.
</TEXT>
