<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cambodia     08-22 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cambodia,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major Changes Announced in Cambodian Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Heng Samrin of Cambodia has
retired or shifted 11 members of his Cabinet and abolished the
office of cooperation with Soviet bloc allies, state-run radio said.
   The radio report, seen Sunday in Bangkok, said the reshuffle
included the key portfolios of defense and interior. No reason was
given for the changes.
   The moves were made Saturday at ``an ordinary meeting of the
Council of State in the presence of Comrade Heng Samrin, chairman
of the Council of State,'' the broadcast said.
   Vietnam installed the Heng Samrin government when it invaded
Cambodia in late 1978. The United Nations recognizes as Cambodia's
legitimate government a coalition of three guerrilla groups
fighting the Vietnamese occupation.
   ``It is decided to dissolve the office of the minister of
economic and cultural cooperation with Vietnam, Laos, the Soviet
Union, and other fraternal socialist countries,'' the radio said.
   The Soviet-backed Vietnamese have pledged to withdraw by early
1990 the up to 100,000 troops they maintain in Cambodia.
</TEXT>
