<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-ArmsDealer Bjt   08-22 0808</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Arms Dealer, Bjt,0829</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Arms Sales Boom: From Bullets To Jet Fighters
^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain is booming as an arms dealer, supplanting
the United States as wealthy Saudi Arabia's biggest supplier and
edging out long-time rival France globally as purveyor of
everything from bullets to jet fighters.
   Less particular than the United States about who buys its
increasingly sophisticated wares, Britain has doubled its sales in
the past three years through a mixture of politics, hard-sell and
technical advances.
   The most glittering prize is a $17 billion deal clinched last
month with Saudi Arabia that includes 50 Tornado fighter-bombers.
   It underlines Britain's major advantage over the United States:
there are no political constraints on British arms sales to
Israel's Arab enemies.
   ``The number of restrictions the United States has on sales is
preposterous,'' says Francis Tusa, analyst at the London-based
Royal United Services Institute for Defense Studies.
   ``The Saudis have made it clear that they are not going to be
told any longer by the U.S. Congress, `You can have what you want _
but only a third of it and not for another five years and providing
you don't base it where you want to','' he said in an interview.
   With the ink just dry on the Saudi deal, Defense Secretary
George Younger was back in the Middle East, this time in Kuwait,
talking arms. About the same time, the U.S. Senate blocked the sale
of Maverick air-to-surface missiles that were to accompany 40
American F-18 fighters Kuwait had agreed to buy, throwing doubt on
the near $2 billion deal.
   ``Our friends and friendly rivals have their problems,''
acknowledged an official of the Defense Ministry's Defense Exports
Services Organization, requesting anonymity.
   With a staff of 250, the organization's main job is to oil the
wheels of sales drives by privately owned British armament
manufacturers, such as the airplane giant British Aerospace, and
also check that they don't sell to banned countries.
   These include South Africa, Syria, Libya and Israel, which is
officially under a British arms embargo since the 1982 invasion of
Lebanon.
   According to Defense Ministry figures, between 1985 and 1987
Britain doubled to 12 percent its share of the world arms market
outside the East bloc.
   Britain, the Defense Ministry says, is now the world's third
largest arms supplier, ranking well behind the United States _
``Washington probably gives away more than we sell worldwide,''
said one official _ and the Soviet Union, but pushing France down
to fourth place.
   Britain signed defense contracts worth $4 billion in 1985. In
1986, the figure was nearly $9 billion with a first major Saudi
contract to buy Tornado planes, and last year contracts totaled an
estimated $5.6 billion.
   Defense Export Services Organization chief Sir Colin Chandler,
who received a knighthood this year on Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher's recommendation, says Britain's 1987 figure keeps it
ahead of France.
   In 1986, with the Saudi deal, Britain moved temporarily into
second place, ahead of the Soviet Union.
   Mrs. Thatcher has assiduously cultivated the oil-rich Saudis on
official visits and rolled out the red carpet for King Fahd in
London.
   She slips in plugs for British armaments during foreign trips,
including recently in Canada, where Britain and France are
competing for a multimillion-dollar order for nuclear-powered
submarines.
   British officials, arms manufacturers and some analysts say
prime factors in the increased sales are improved weapons and
warplanes, including the multinational Tornado developed with West
Germany and Italy, and the free-enterprise atmosphere generated by
nearly a decade of Thatcher government.
   ``It is a fact that we're producing more things with fewer
people,'' said a British official, adding the 130,000-strong
workforce in the defense industry has declined slightly in the past
few years. He requested anonymity.
   Others familiar with the secretive world of arms sales say
France has also been hurt by a tradition of gearing arms exports to
Third World countries on generous credit terms.
   Philip Parker, marketing director for Plessey, one of five
British defense electronics manufacturers, said that with Britain
cutting defense spending, companies are forced to expand foreign
sales.
   ``We have to go and slug it out in the market place in the major
countries,'' said Parker in an interview.
   Plessey says its annual turnover from defense sales has more
than trebled to $850 million since 1980, with sonar systems going
to the Swedish, Thai and South Korean navies, an $850 million
communications network for the Australian army, and smaller deals
with Oman, New Zealand, Greece and an unidentified Far Eastern
country.
   But British manufacturers have suffered some big failures too.
   The most expensive was the scrapping of the Nimrod spy plane in
1986, after nine years' work by Britain's General Electric Company
costing nearly $1.7 billion. Britain ordered the U.S. Boeing
Airborne Warning and Command System instead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
