<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-22 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Hoylman spent much of the weekend
puzzling down and across before coming up as winner of the 11th
Annual American Crossword Puzzle Tournament.
   Hoylman, of Chevy Chase, Md., took 10 minutes and 44 seconds to
perfectly fill in a crossword puzzle Sunday at the competition that
drew puzzle aces from around the country, according to tournament
director Will Shortz.
   The three finalists from a field of 136 reached the playoff
round after scoring points on accuracy and speed in earlier rounds.
Hoylman's first-place efforts won him $500.
   Second place finisher was Jon Delfin, a pianist from New York
City, who clocked 13 minutes and 4 seconds to finish the puzzle
without an error.
   Ellen Ripstein of New York scored the best time of 7 minutes 19
seconds, but she had one error.
   Shortz said the final puzzle was very difficult and offered some
examples: ``One clue was `court pronouncement' which make you think
about the legal area but the answer actually was `game, set and
match' in the tennis court.''
   Another clue was the state in which you might see stars.
   ``It's supposed to make you thnk about California, but the anwer
was `senseless,''' he said.
   The competition was sponsored by the publishers of the New York
Herald Tribune Crosswords magazines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supermarket checker Vicki McClure says she's
glad her moment in the spotlight as solo singer at the opening of
the 1984 Olympic Summer Games didn't catapult her to instant
success.
   ``I'm not disappointed for what has happened because being
thrust in at that level with my inexperience would have been a
mistake,'' McClure said.
   ``I really wouldn't have had an inkling of how to handle it.''
   Still, she has fond memories of the grand event four years ago.
   ``It was the most spectacular moment. It was bigger than life,''
she said recently. ``It was a really magical experience.''
   Ms. McClure sang the hit, ``Reach Out and Touch (Somebody's
Hand)'' at the opening ceremonies of the 1984 Olympics at Los
Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
   The $7 million opening ceremony had a cast of thousands and was
staged before a capacity crowd of 90,000 and an international
television audience.
   The show included a 1,000-voice choir, a 750-piece marching
band, a 100-piece symphony orchestra, 7,500 athletes and 2,500
pigeons.
   Ms. McClure, who was 30 at the time, appeared as the lead singer
in the Los Angeles Jazz Choir, a position originally intended for a
star of the caliber of Diana Ross.
   But after Olympics officials heard her sing, they chose her to
perform because they liked the idea of having an unknown singer.
``It was kind of in keeping with the amateur spirit of the
Olympics,'' she said.
   Ms. McClure said she is happy working as a professional singer,
performing at banquets and ceremonies and with the group Daddy's
Money, which performs nostalgic and rhythm and blues songs.
   ``I haven't really done a Vicki McClure act as of yet,'' she
said. ``I'm still looking for a repertoire. It's hard to find
material you're comfortable with by yourself.''
</TEXT>
