<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Harassment 2ndLd-Writethru a0736 08-22 0782</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Harassment, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0736,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials Say Harassment Of U.S. Military in Panama Increases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS graf after 3rd graf `Noriega is...' with summary of
PDF statement. Pickup 4th graf pvs `Ms. Farrell...'; INSERTS 2
grafs after 14th pvs, `The story...' with more from statement.
Picks up 15th graf pvs, `Washington imposed ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military personnel are reporting
increased harassment by local officials, but there is no indication
the actions are part of a new campaign by the government of Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, U.S. authorities said Sunday.
   Cynthia Farrell, a spokeswoman for the U.S. Embassy, said the
incidents involved harassment, ``not attacks.''
   Noriega is commander of Panama's Defense Forces and controls the
civilian government. He was indicted in February by two grand
juries in Florida on drug trafficking charges and the United States
has imposed economic sanctions in an effort to force him to resign
and leave Panama.
   A statement by the Defense Forces late Sunday called the
accusations of harassment part of a campaign of disinformation in
an effort to destabilize Panama and listed numerous allegations of
misconduct by U.S. forces in Panama.
   Ms. Farrell said the reports of harassment are coming only from
U.S. military personnel.
   ``Civilians, business people and embassy personnel have reported
no increase in harassment,'' she said. She added she did not know
if U.S. military personnel are being bothered more or are ``simply
reporting more cases.''
   An official at the U.S. Southern Command in Panama, who spoke on
condition of anonymity, said 240 cases of harassment had been
reported between February and August of this year.
   He said incidents of harassment have increased in number and
gravity but denied reports the incidents were being considered
attacks.
   ``What's going on these days has been going on for months _
going way back to last year,'' the official said. ``If there was an
increase, it probably came in January, February, March and April,
not in the last month or two.''
   ``One of the things that's happening is that a lot of people are
being asked for bribes when they're stopped for traffic violations,
and that's probably because the police aren't getting paid
regularly'' the official said.
   Panama's economy has been damaged by the U.S. sanctions.
   The Southern Command official said a more serious incident
occurred last week when Panamanian Defense Forces officers refused
to let U.S. military vehicles pick up mail for three days at Panama
City's international airport. The dispute was resolved after three
days, the official said, but he did not elaborate.
   The New York Times on Sunday quoted U.S. Southern Command, State
and Defense Department officials as saying there have been an
increasing number of beatings, abductions, rape and extortion of
U.S. military personnel and their dependents in Panama.
   The story, under a Washington dateline, said the U.S. officials
view the incidents as a campaign by Noriega to pressure the United
States to lift economic sanctions against Panama.
   The Defense Forces statement said: ``The supposed U.S.
government officials (cited by the Times) must have the IQ of a
3-year-old Cro-Magnon when they assert that actions taken by the
Panama Defense Forces against U.S. military personnel are attempts
to force the Reagan administration to lift or soften economic
sanctions imposed on Panama.''
   The statement said U.S. troops cause daily problems for
Panamanian authorities, including fights, mistreatment of women,
venereal disease, shooting in public places and refusing to pay bar
and restaurant tabs.
   Washington imposed economic sanctions on Panama in March after
the Noriega ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   Delvalle has since been in hiding, but the United States
continues to recognize him as Panama's legitimate president.
   About 12,000 U.S. servicemen are stationed in Panama by treaty
to protect the Panama Canal, a vital waterway linking the Atlantic
and Pacific oceans. They are attached to the Southern Command,
which is in charge of all U.S. military operations south of the
U.S.-Mexico border.
   The first Southern Command official reached by The Associated
Press acknowledged several specific incidents reported by the
Times, including a case in June in which an enlisted man and his
wife were assaulted at gunpoint by a man described as a Panamanian
military officer.
   The assailant forced the enlisted man into the trunk of his car,
then beat and raped his wife.
   ``The individual was dressed in a camouflaged uniform, but he
could have been military, paramilitary, a civilian guard or just
some guy who knows somebody in the PDF (Panamanian Defense Forces)
and somehow managed to get himself a uniform,'' said the Southern
Command official. ``As far as I know, we don't have a definite
description or identification.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
