<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LuccheseTrial Bjt   08-22 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lucchese Trial, Bjt,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mob Trial Concluding After Nearly Two Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The trial of 20 alleged mob associates is
nearing an end after 22 months during which a prosecutor twice
became a father, one defense attorney was elected mayor and another
died.
   The trial, believed to be the longest federal criminal trial in
U.S. history and expected to go to the jury this week, has heard
from 89 witnesses and has produced a 5{-foot-thick file containing
40,000 pages of transcripts and 850 exhibits.
   During the U.S. District Court trial, one defendant attended
court for a time in a hospital bed until his moaning interfered
with the proceedings. One passed out from a too-full bladder.
   One prosecutor became a father twice. A defense attorney who had
been commuting from Florida died of cancer.
   ``It's a nightmare,'' said defense attorney Miles Feinstein.
   The case is United States of America vs. Anthony Accetturo, et
al.
   The 20 reputed members and associates of the Lucchese organized
crime family are charged with racketeering and, variously, loan
sharking, illegal gambling, credit card fraud and drug dealing.
   ``No one imagined when we took this case in November 1986 that
we'd still be here,'' said Michael Critchley, a defense lawyer
whose closing arguments lasted five days.
   Critchley, who leads the defense, represents Michael Taccetta,
charged as the group's New Jersey boss. Accetturo is the reputed
Lucchese family captain who allegedly acted as the ultimate
authority from his home in Hollywood, Fla.
   The group allegedly operated out of the Hole-in-the Wall
luncheonette in Newark, where pictures of Al Capone, Meyer Lansky
and Charles ``Lucky'' Luciano decorated the walls.
   Witnesses testified about kisses of respect for the boss,
``tribute'' payments to mob superiors, ``sit-downs,'' where
disputes were resolved, and visits to hangouts by manicurists to do
the nails of defendants.
   The Administrative Office of the Courts in Washington, D.C.,
says the trial is the longest federal criminal trial ever,
according to courtroom Deputy Clerk Lisa Horton.
   One of the longest trials in history, a state lawsuit in
Belleville, Ill., against a chemical company, ended in 1987 after
3{ years.
   Jurors here have been paid more than $175,000. Court-appointed
attorneys have received an estimated $3 million. The defense
calculates the goverment paid or reimbursed cooperating witnesses
some $300,000.
   That's in addition to the salaries of three prosecutors and an
FBI agent who spent nearly two years full-time on the case, extra
deputy marshals for security and U.S. District Judge Harold A.
Ackerman. Then there's copying costs for a mountain of documents.
   ``Obviously it's been very expensive, but I think it's been very
worthwhile,'' said U.S. Attorney Samuel A. Alito Jr., who came to
the job after the case began.
   ``I don't think anybody would say we can't go after organized
crime just because it's too expensive.''
   Ackerman, almost miraculously, has been able to keep up with his
civil calendar. But he has been removed from the pool of judges
assigned criminal cases, worsening the court's backlog.
   The length has taken its toll on everyone involved.
   ``It's difficult to run a town when you are down here,'' said
Robert L. Brown, a defense attorney who was elected mayor of Orange
in May. ``It has caused a lot of late nights at city hall.''
   ``It's taken a piece out of all of us, not just our practices,
but spiritually and emotionally as well,'' said Feinstein.
   One witness was on the stand for four months. He was among a
half-dozen cooperating witnesses _ many with criminal records _
brought to the stand by prosecutors to tell the group's inside
story.
   The defense seized on the issue, telling the jury not to trust
convicted criminals and liars. The government countered by saying
choir boys wouldn't know the Mafia's inner workings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0125EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle'sRockyRoad Bjt 1stLd-Writethru 08-22 0936</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle's Rocky Road, Bjt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Running Mate Has Rocky Debut In Political Big Leagues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0426 to add editor's note at end</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle's rocky entry into big-league
politics, stumbling over questions about his military record that
threaten to overshadow George Bush's campaign, has left the
exuberant young senator bloody but seemingly unbowed.
   Back in the nation's capital to prepare for his first solo
campaign trip Wednesday, the Indiana senator remains adamant that
he is not an embarrassment to Bush, has not considered removing
himself from the ticket, and sees nothing improper in the way he
entered the National Guard at a time when other young men were
marching off to fight in Vietnam.
   But the Republican ticket's public debut at the New Orleans
convention and on a three-day Midwestern campaign swing saw these
extraordinary events:
   _Quayle, asked at a New Orleans news conference about his
reasons for going into the National Guard in 1969, stumbling over
his thoughts and finally declaring: ``I did not know in 1969 that I
would be in this room today, I confess.''
   _Quayle standing in mock attention before a Republican Party
farewell convention breakfast, reciting to the uneasy audience his
name, rank and serial number and proclaiming ``Indiana National
Guard. Six years and proud of it!''
   _Quayle, surrounded by reporters and a raucously partisan crowd
in his hometown of Huntington, Ind., asserting ``I got into the
National Guard fairly'' but acknowledging that he assumed a friend
of his wealthy publishing family made calls on his behalf after
Quayle expressed interest in joining the Guard.
   _Quayle, telling reporters in Cleveland, Ohio that he could not
recall what communications he had with his draft board 20 years ago
but insisting he distinctly remembered having no conversation ``in
the 1980s'' with a Pennsylvania Democrat quoted as saying Quayle
told him he ``rode out'' Vietnam in the Guard.
   _Bush, calling the controversy a ``tempest in a teapot'' and
asserting that his initial campaign swing ``has gone great'' except
for ``this frenzy'' of media interest in Quayle's military record.
   Whether that assessment is accurate remains to be seen.
   Quayle seems likely to continue to have to fight portrayals of
himself as a wealthy young man who spoke in favor of the Vietnam
War but had strings pulled to avoid the draft as his college
student deferment was about to expire.
   Bush, a Navy bomber pilot who saw extensive combat in World War
II, defended his running mate, saying that the Vietnam War years in
which Quayle, now 41, pondered his own military service ``were
different times.''
   As for Quayle being vulnerable in the area of defense, an area
in which Bush has portrayed Michael Dukakis as weak, the vice
president said, ``The difference between the person I'm running
against and my running mate are night and day on defense.''
   Bush aides insist they are happy with how Quayle has handled
himself in publicly answering questions about his military record.
   Quayle himself says he does not feel the issue has overshadowed
Bush.
   But there was a clear change in campaign strategy after Quayle's
outdoor news conference Friday that was piped over a public address
system to Quayle's hometown supporters. Their booing of reporters'
questions and cheering of Quayle's answers helped create a
circus-like atmosphere reminiscent of a Roman gladiatorial bout
while Bush remained out of sight in a holding room.
   That day, on which the ticket opened its first joint campaign
trip in the nation's heartland, Quayle dominated news stories about
the event.
   The next day, Bush took charge, defending his running mate in no
uncertain terms at a joint news conference and declaring that
Quayle's qualifications and background had been examined to his
satisfaction.
   Bush said his aides had to spend a lot of time last week running
down ``rumor after insidious rumor,'' and added that the
controversy ``is behind us.''
   However, some questions may yet need to be answered.
   There have been conflicting reports, for example, on whether
there were vacancies in the Guard at the time Quayle entered or
whether there was a waiting list. Quayle has said he cannot recall
those kinds of details.
   And he has not spelled out publicly the extent of his knowledge
about what calls were made on his behalf or to whom they were made.
A retired Guard official, who is a friend of Quayle's family and
worked for the family newspaper, has said he did contact the Guard
on Quayle's behalf. The commander of the Guard unit to which Quayle
was assigned, however, has said he did not receive a call from
anyone urging Quayle's enlistment.
   Quayle insists that ``no rules were broken'' in the way he
entered the Guard. He says he was willing to serve in Vietnam had
his unit been called up, although he concedes that he was generally
aware the likelihood of that happening was not great.
   Quayle has been angered at implications that he was trying to
avoid the draft, although he has tried to appear unperturbed
throughout the controversy. Over the weekend, Quayle appeared not
to hear some spectators' chants of ``Quayle, who went in your
place?'' or to see signs reading ``This Quayle is a chicken.''
   He seems to be philosophical about the most intense and public
scrutiny of his meteoric political career.
   ``I'm in politics in what they call the big leagues,'' Quayle
says, adding: ``Running for the vice presidency is a definite
honor.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Eileen Putman is a Washington-based reporter for
The Associated Press covering the vice presidential candidates.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Candidates-ForeignPolicy Bjt   08-22 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Foreign Policy, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Do Voters Care?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>An AP News Analysis</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign policy is getting very little
attention from the candidates as the campaign gets started. The
Republicans seem to be content to play vaguely on George Bush's
experience, while the Democrats are saying even less.
   Even so, the basic approach of the two parties is becoming
clear. Bush and his running mate, Sen. Daniel Quayle, intend to
sound the traditional conservative themes of a powerful military
structure and keeping a wary eye on the Russians.
   Dukakis and his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, are playing
down ideology and playing up ``competence,'' being careful to
strike a skeptical stance on the Soviets while sounding the peace
theme.
   Both sides are bound to get more specific in the 2{ months of
campaigning ahead. It's likely to get sticky. Bush will be
challenged about the Reagan administration's secret arms sale to
Iran while Dukakis' lack of foreign policy experience will be
tested over a wide range of issues.
   Don't look for foreign policy treatises, though. Campaigning for
president in the television age encourages snappy or catchy
one-liners, not a thoughtful exposition of how the candidates stand
on tricky arms control issues, the Arab-Israel dispute, leftist
movements in Central America and apartheid in South Africa.
   Besides, politicians and their managers operate on the theory
the voters are far more concerned with pocketbook issues such as
jobs and inflation than with American foreign policy.
   There have been striking exceptions and mixed results. Franklin
D. Roosevelt ran for a fourth term as president in 1944 while the
United States was still at war. The overriding issue was whether to
take a chance on changing leaders. The voters stuck with Roosevelt.
   In 1972, on the other hand, George McGovern, the Democratic
candidate, ran primarily as an anti-war candidate whose opposition
to American involvement in Vietnam and Cambodia was the central
theme of his futile race against President Richard Nixon.
   The 1988 campaign is just now unfolding, but there is no reason
to believe either the Republicans or Democrats will give that sort
of weight to a single foreign policy issue.
   In fact, the selections of Quayle and Bentsen suggest the
presidential candidates intend to place the focus elsewhere.
   Bush's choice of Quayle is above all a gesture to the GOP's most
conservative elements, while Dukakis chose Bentsen primarily for
his experience in Congress and his ties to conservative Democrats,
especially in Texas.
   In 1960, when Nixon was pondering a running mate for his first
race for the presidency, he assembled 36 party elders at a midnight
meeting in Chicago. The governor of Illinois, William Stratton,
offered this advice: ``You can say all you want about foreign
affairs, but what is really important is the price of hogs in
Chicago.''
   Nixon picked Henry Cabot Lodge, who had served as the U.S.
permanent representative at the United Nations. They lost to John
Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson, but Nixon's explanation, as recalled by
former Undersecretary of State Warren Christopher, may still be
relevant: ``If you ever let the Democrats campaign only on domestic
issues, they will beat us. Our only hope is to keep it on foreign
policy.''
   That doesn't mean, however, that the candidate has to be an
expert on the pecking order in the Kremlin, the history of the West
Bank or the strengths and weaknesses of the Nicaraguan economy.
   Ronald Reagan won in 1980 without any experience in foreign
affairs. He lacked the background to be specific about foreign
policy issues. But he had a well-developed image of opposing
communism, and he relied on generalities whenever dealing with the
Soviets _ the primary foreign policy issue of our time _ came to
the fore.
   Reagan is leaving office on an entirely different note.
   He has held four summit meetings with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and signed a treaty with Moscow to scrap
intermediate-range nuclear missiles.
   Bush, his vice president, is trying to capitalize on the
improvement in U.S.-Soviet relations, suggesting he is far more
capable than Dukakis to maintain the momentum.
   The fact that Reagan _ like Dukakis _ was inexperienced when he
ran for the presidency is not stopping Bush from questioning the
credentials of his opponent.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid covers foreign affairs for The
Associated Press from the State Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0136EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AfghanTerrorism Bjt   08-22 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan Terrorism, Bjt,600</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release at 12 noon EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Afghan Terrorism in Pakistan Increases, US Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government was
responsible for repeated attacks on civilian targets in Pakistan in
1987 and carried out well over half of all incidents of
state-sponsored terrorism worldwide in that year, a State
Department report said today.
   The report, titled ``Patterns of Global Terrorism: 1987,'' was
completed before the incident last Wednesday in which a Pakistani
C-130 crashed, claiming the lives of President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq,
U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel, Brig. Gen. Herbert M. Wassom and
27 others.
   Pakistani officials believe terrorists were responsible and a
U.S. official said Afghan agents have to be ``among the suspects''
because of the stepped up campaign Afghan authorities are alleged
to be carrying out against Pakistan.
   The conflict between the two countries stems from Pakistani
support for Afghan rebels based in Pakistan who are fighting the
Kabul government and Pakistan's role as a haven for millions of
Afghan refugees.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said Sunday that any
comments on the cause of the crash would be speculative because
investigators, including U.S. experts flown to Pakistan, are just
beginning their work.
   Redman spoke at Andrews Air Force, where the remains of Raphel
and Wassom were flown and a ceremony was held that included remarks
by Secretary of State George P. Shultz and Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci.
   Acting Pakistani President Ghulam Ishaq Khan said Saturday his
government suspects last Wednesday crash was the result of sabotage.
   ``Judging from the circumstances of the tragedy ... enemies of
Pakistan are actively posing a threat to the security of our
country,'' Ishaq Khan said.
   Paul Kriesburg, a senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, said it would be a mistake to assume
automatically that Afghan agents were responsible for the crash
because Zia had many other enemies. They included some from within
the Pakistani military and others who were alienated by his
authoritarian rule.
   The State Department report said Afghan agents carried out 127
of the 189 incidents last year attributable to state-sponsored
terrorism.
   Iran was second with 44 and Libya followed with seven, the
report said.
   All told, there were 832 international terrorist incidents last
year. ``When the Pakistani numbers are subtracted, the number of
incidents in the rest of the world declined by almost 10 per cent
from 1986 statistics,'' it said.
   The report said the Afghan campaign had been largely limited to
the northwest part of Pakistan where rebel forces are based but
spread to major cities last year.
   It said the campaign is being waged by the Afghan Ministry of
State Security, known by the acronym WAD.
   Zia said last November that the assassinations and bombings
carried out against Pakistani civilians were ``at the behest of the
Soviet Union'' but Moscow has denied the allegation.
   U.S. and Pakistani officials estimate that bombs planted by
Afghan agents have killed more than 400 civilians in Pakistan. The
bloodiest incident occurred in July 1987 when three car bombs
exploded in the main bazaar of Karachi, killing 72 and injuring 260.
   The report said it is likely that the Soviets have been aware of
Afghan operations in Pakistan because of the close ties between WAD
and the Soviet intelligence agency, KGB.
   It said that while some of the material for the explosive
devices can be purchased on the black market, other items can be
obtained only through Soviet sources.
   Pakistan estimates that about 1,500 Soviet advisers work with
WAD.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
