<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     08-22 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Emphasizes National Themes During Regional Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is emphasizing national campaign
themes as he visits northeastern Massachusetts, a region the
Democratic presidential nominee often cites when discussing his
record of economic development.
   As he did during a visit to central Massachusetts last week,
Dukakis is kicking off the visit with a meeting attended by area
elected officials, educators and business and labor leaders.
   The Massachusetts governor also planned today to distribute
grants for a new manufacturing research center and for improvements
at the Middlesex Community College campus in Lowell.
   From there, Dukakis was to attend an event to promote his
Homeownership Opportunity Program, which provides state assistance
to low- and moderate-income families looking to buy homes.
   Dukakis was to return to the northeastern corner of the state
Tuesday for several more events. He frequently mentions the
northeastern Massachusetts communities of Lawrence and Lowell, both
former mill cities, when discussing his efforts to spur economic
development in economically depressed areas.
   Dukakis spent Sunday at his Brookline home, where he returned
late Saturday night after a four-day campaign swing through parts
of Minnesota, Florida, Alabama, Illinois, Missouri, Arkansas, Texas
and Tennessee.
   That trip started in the middle of the Republican National
Convention and was part of a campaign effort to keep Dukakis
visible during the GOP gathering.
   Aides billed the trip as highly successful. Dukakis revealed no
new positions on issues but was widely covered in the national news
media, particularly after Republican nominee George Bush's
selection of Sen. Dan Quayle as a running mate sparked controversy.
Questions have centered on Quayle's use of his wealthy family's
influence to help him join the National Guard and avoid the draft
at the height of the Vietnam War.
   Dukakis at virtually every stop indirectly criticized Quayle and
Bush's judgment for choosing him. Dukakis repeatedly discussed the
lenthy Senate record of his own running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of
Texas, telling crowds the ``true test'' of presidential leadership
should be the quality of people selected to fill key positions.
   After spending today and Tuesday in Massachusetts, Dukakis plans
to campaign Wednesday and Thursday in Washington, D.C., Ohio and
Pennsylvania. He is scheduled to be back in Boston on Friday and
then back in the nation's capital Saturday to participate in a
march marking the 25th anniversary of the civil rights march on
Washington led by Martin Luther King Jr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
