<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SovietRocket     08-22 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Rocket,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Rocket Descent Puts on Light Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet rocket that plummeted to Earth in
northeastern Canada put on a spectacular light show for residents
of the western and northern United States, but it was not all that
unusual in other respects, Pentagon officials say.
   The craft that crashed Sunday, causing no reported injuries or
damage, was also not Cosmos 1900, the Soviet spy satellite that has
been drifting out of orbit for several months and arousing concern
because it is nuclear-powered.
   The rocket had been launched last Thursday to boost a Gorizont
communications satellite into orbit, said Maj. Alex Mondragon,
spokesman for the North American Aerospace Defense Command and the
U.S. Space Command, speaking from Peterson Air Force Base near
Colorado Springs.
   The vehicle, which came down at about 1 a.m. EDT, was most
likely an SL12, one of the most frequently used Soviet launchers,
he said.
   The craft was tracked by officials at the U.S. Space
Surveillance Center at Cheyenne Mountain in Colorado, where about
7,200 space vehicles are constantly being observed. An average of
one space vehicle reenters the Earth's atmosphere each day,
Mondragon said.
   ``It's not unusual for a rocket body not to stay in orbit,'' he
said. ``There's nothing to keep it there.''
   Cosmos 1900, launched last Dec. 12, is now expected to reenter
the Earth's atmosphere in late September or early October,
Mondragon said.
   Mondragon and Pentagon spokesman Maj. Mike Stepp provided no
further details about the craft's condition when it reached the
Earth or the precise location where it came down.
   Mondragon said it usually takes about 24 hours to pinpoint where
downed satellites plummet to Earth.
   The spokesmen said the descending rocket was visible to
residents of New Mexico, Colorado, Nebraska and Michigan.
   ``I do understand it was pretty spectacular,'' Stepp said.
   He said the downing of the craft, which he referred to as a
``non-nuclear Soviet rocket body,'' was expected by U.S. officials.
   ``It was predicted it would come down, it came down as predicted
and it came down where it was predicted,'' he said.
   Mondragon said officials do not try to recover parts of such
rocket bodies because 95 percent of them usually burn up upon
reentry.
   ``That spectacular light show that they provide folks with is
the rocket body burning up,'' he said.
</TEXT>
