<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeopleHelenHayes     08-22 0287</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People Helen Hayes,0294</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Actress Helen Hayes Hospitalized for Apparent Fatigue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar-winning actress Helen Hayes
was in good condition after being hospitalized for irregular heart
beat, and doctors were trying to determine if she suffered a heart
attack or only altitude sickness.
   Miss Hayes, 87, had been visiting her son, actor James
MacArthur, in Crested Butte when she became ill.
   She was flown the 100 miles from the Rocky Mountain town whose
elevation is nearly 10,000 feet to St. Mary's Hospital here.
   ``She is very tired and really apprehensive about the media
learning about her being here,'' Karen Bennett, a nursing
supervisor, said Sunday night.
   ``I really feel it was just the altitude that was bothering
her,'' said Dr. Dan Tullius of Crested Butte. ``But she was sent to
Grand Junction to confirm whether or not she had a heart attack.
... She had an irregular heart beat and it could be secondary to
altitude.''
   Grand Junction's elevation is about 6,000 feet.
   Miss Hayes had attended the Republican National Convention in
New Orleans last week and ``had gone from a lower elevation to a
higher elevation and her body wouldn't tolerate it,'' said Bennett.
   The silver-haired actress ended her theater career in 1971,
after 66 years, because of allergies to dust that aggravated her
chronic asthmatic bronchitis. She has continued to work before the
camera and is active in causes such as the rights of the elderly.
   She has won a Tony, two Oscars and an Emmy, and in 1981 received
the Kennedy Center Honors for lifetime achievement. In 1980, she
was selected as one of 10 American artists to be commemorated on a
gold medallion issued by the Treasury Department.
</TEXT>
