<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CommunityPlant     08-22 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Community Plant,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mississippi Residents Volunteer To Clean Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLARKSDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank presidents, schoolchildren,
housewives and the unemployed worked side-by-side to prepare a
city-owned plant that will house a chemical factory and employ 25
workers.
   Chicago-based Omnitech is the first company to locate in the
area since the city made industrial recruitment its top priority in
late 1986.
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' car dealer Gregg Cocker, 33, said
as he scrubbed walls. ``This will help out the town and I want to
do my part. It will come back and help me in the future.''
   About 130 residents volunteered Saturday to clean the plant in
the work-hungry community of 21,000 people about 75 miles south of
Memphis.
   ``I think it's incredible,'' Omnitech president Jack Cook said.
``I've never seen anything like it.''
   The company expects to begin production in October with 25
workers, and hopes to employ 50 people within two years.
   Economic problems in the city are similar to those throughout
the Mississippi Delta. Unemployment ran as high as 21 percent in
1987, dropping to 10.6 percent in June.
   Omnitech will use the 86,000-square-foot building formerly
occupied by a motor-home manufacturer. The plant has been vacant
since March 1986.
   ``We got our big frog,'' George F. Walker, president of the
Coahoma County Industrial Foundation, said referring to a campaign
inviting industries to be a big frog in the Clarksdale's ``little
pond.''
</TEXT>
