<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Cable Car Accident,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Receive Minor Injuries When Cable Car Loses Grip On Steep
Hill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cable car on a steep, damp hill above
Fisherman's Wharf lost its grip and rolled backward, hitting a car
and causing three minor injuries, officials said.
   The accident occurred on the Hyde Street hill, about a block
from a May 16 accident in which a runaway cable car hit a truck,
injuring 36 passengers.
   On Sunday, the car carrying 25 to 30 riders was headed up the
hill when it disengaged from the underground cable near Francisco
Street, officials said.
   The gripman applied the regular and emergency brakes, but the
car rolled backward into an automobile, which then hit a parked
auto. The cable car slid down the hill for about 200 feet before
stopping.
   Three passengers were treated for minor injuries at the scene,
and the damage to the two cars was minor, officials said. The cable
car was apparently undamaged.
</TEXT>
