<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CocaineBust     08-22 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cocaine Bust,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bust Nets 5,000 Pounds of Cocaine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agents seized about 5,000 pounds of pure cocaine
and $2 million in cash, including some stashed in bags marked
``Just Say No,'' authorities said in announcing one of the nation's
largest drug confiscations.
   Four people were arrested, including the local leader of a
Colombian drug cartel, authorities said Sunday.
   The cocaine, with an estimated street value of $400 million, was
the largest amount confiscated in New York City, said Robert M.
Stutman, special agent in charge of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration's office here.
   The largest cocaine shipment ever seized in the United States,
in Tampa, Fla., on April 28, involved 9,230 pounds found in plastic
containers that were concealed in hallowed-out lumber. The largest
in the New York City area occurred last month in Hicksville, where
agents discovered 6,000 pounds of cocaine hidden inside blocks of
chocolate from Ecuador.
   Only a few cocaine seizures nationally have exceeded 5,000
pounds. But Customs Service agents in 10 months have seized 10 tons
more cocaine than they did in all of the last fiscal year, Customs
Commissioner William von Raab said earlier this month.
   Among those arrested this weekend was Hernando Grajales Rizzo,
39, Colombia, a leader in the Cali drug cartel, Stutman said.
   Stutman would not say when or how the smugglers brought the
drugs into New York. The drugs were found in the Queens apartment
where Rizzo and two other men were arrested, officials said.
   The arrests were announced at a news conference where
authorities displayed small plastic-wrapped boxes containing the
5,000 pounds of cocaine and boxes of U.S. currency.
   Some of the money was in supermarket bags imprinted with the
Reagan administration's slogan, ``Just Say No To Drugs.''
   The arrests would likely cause the cartel to suffer a setback,
but not end its activity in the lucrative New York market,
officials said.
   ``I hope it will have an impact, but the amount of the drugs
coming in is very, very large,'' said Chief Raymond L. Jones of the
city Police Department's Organized Crime Control Bureau. ``The
problem is that a 2-pound, 2-ounce package, a kilo, can be broken
down to about 14,000 vials of crack. That is our major problem.''
   The suspects will be arraigned this week, authorities said.
</TEXT>
