<HEAD>Thunderstorms Strong in Midwest Drought Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Strong thunderstorms hit South Dakota, Nebraska and Iowa today,
bringing heavy rains and hail to the drought-plagued region, while
temperatures dipped to the 40s in the Northeast.
   Golf ball-size hail dented cars at Mayfield, S.D., while winds
toppled trees at Marcus, Iowa.
   Also in Iowa, winds gusted to 60 mph at Sioux Center knocked
down tree branches; street flooding was reported in the town, after
4 to 5{ inches of rain drenched Sioux County. Thunderstorms dumped
3 inches of rain near Sibley, 4 inches at Laurens, and 2{ inches at
Larabee.
   In Arizona, heavy rains fell Sunday night in Wenden, putting at
least one street under 3 feet of water, but much of the
precipitation eased elsewhere.
   Thunderstorms were intense Sunday night along Texas' Coast, with
power outages reported in the Crockett area of southeast Texas.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered in eastern and
southwestern Texas, Alabama, the Carolinas, Utah and Colorado.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from Arizona across the central and southern Rockies and the
central Plains to the upper Mississippi Valley, and from coastal
South Carolina across Georgia, Florida and the Gulf coastal states
to Arkansas and southeast Texas.
   High temperatures in the 70s were expected from the mid-Atlantic
states across the Great Lakes region to North Dakota and northern
Montana.
   Readings should reach only the 60s in most of New England.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were forecast along the Pacific Coast
and in some of the mountainous areas of the Southwest.
   Temperatures should climb to about 100 degrees in central
Oklahoma, north-central Texas and southwest Oregon, with readings
near 105 degrees in parts of the desert southwest.
   The rest of nation should get highs in the 80s or 90s.
   The high in the nation Sunday was 103 degrees at Hill City,
Kan., Altus Air Force Base, Okla., and Borrego Springs, Calif.
   Temperatures this morning were in the 40s in northern parts of
the Great Lakes, northeast New York state, northern parts of New
England and the northern Rocky Mountain region.
   Readings in the 50s and 60s covered much of California, the
Pacific Northwest, the central Rockies, most of the northern
Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes, the Ohio
Valley, the central Appalachians, and the mid-Atlantic states.
   Temperatures were in the 80s from central Texas to southwest
Iowa and the desert Southwest.
   The remainder of the nation had readings in the 70s.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 37 degrees
at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 87 at Fort Worth, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 fair; Boston 57 fair; Buffalo 50 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 75 foggy; Cincinnati 67 fair; Cleveland 56 fair;
Detroit 57 fair; Miami 78 fair; New York 63 fair; Philadelphia 62
fair; Pittsburgh 58 fair; Portland, Maine 49 fair; Washington 68
fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 53 fair; Chicago 70 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
83 windy; Denver 64 rain; Des Moines 77 showers; Indianapolis 68
fair; Kansas City 81 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71 cloudy;
Nashville 75 hazy; New Orleans 73 fair; St. Louis 77 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 partly cloudy; Anchorage 51 rain; Las
Vegas 82 fair; Los Angeles 63 fair; Phoenix 83 partly cloudy; Salt
Lake City 67 fair; San Diego 66 fair; San Francisco 60 fair;
Seattle 62 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 52 partly cloudy; Toronto 48 fair.
</TEXT>
