<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspectors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0483,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Inspectors to Visit Two Missiles Bases in U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RETRANSMITTING a0483 to restore dropped material</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three teams of inspectors from the Soviet
Union were scheduled to arrive in the United States today to
conduct on-site inspections at two military bases under terms of
the treaty to eliminate medium- and shorter-range nuclear weapons,
according to a Defense Department official.
   The Soviet Union has notified us ``that three Soviet inspection
teams are to arrive at Travis Air Force Base to conduct baseline
inmspections,'' said Susan Franklin, a spokeswoman for the Defense
Department's On-Site Inspection Agency.
   Franklin said the Soviets notified the agency early Monday
morning that three 10-man teams were scheduled to arrive at 10:30
p.m. EDT today for the inspections under the terms of the
Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty signed in December.
   The inspections would be conducted at Pueblo Army Depot in
Colorado and Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in Arizona said Franklin.
   The purpose of the Soviet inspections is to verify information
in diagrams of the sites and about the number of missiles provided
by U.S. officials.
   Under the accord the Soviet Union and the United States would
eliminate within three years all land-based missiles with ranges of
300 miles to 3,400 miles.
   Pueblo is as a repair center for Pershing II missiles, and the
Davis-Monthan base is a training center for ground-launched cruise
missiles. Both locations would serve as elimination sites said
Franklin.
   The first U.S. weapons destruction is to begin with the
solid-fuel rocket motors for the Pershing II missiles at the
Longhorn Army Ammunitions plant near Marshall, Texas on for Sept. 8.
</TEXT>
