<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0491,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abu Nidal Group Claims Responsibility For Grenade Attack In Haifa</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads to recast, move up claim of responsibility for bombing.
Edits for transition. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian guerrilla group led by Abu
Nidal today claimed responsibility for a grenade attack that
injured 25 people in the Israeli port city of Haifa.
   Also today, the army said a Palestinian died of wounds sustained
in an overnight clash with Israeli troops that left four other
Palestinians wounded. Arab reports said Palestinians stayed off the
job for a second day to protest Israeli tax raids.
   In the northern city of Haifa, police on Sunday announced the
arrest of four West Bank Palestinians suspected of hurling a
grenade at a crowded sidewalk cafe Saturday night. Twenty-five
people were wounded.
   The Palestinian guerrilla group led by Abu Nidal claimed
responsibility for the attack. The claim came in a statement from
his Fatah-Revolutionary Council faction, published in the Beirut
independent newspaper An-Nahar.
   The statement dedicated the attack to Khalil Wazir, also known
as Abu Jihad, the military commander of the Palestine Liberation
Organization who was assassinated in a suburb of Tunis in April.
Israeli officials have privately acknowledged killing Wazir.
   Dan Meir, 8, was the most seriously injured in the grenade
attack. Both his feet were amputated and he suffered head wounds.
   Officials at Al Ittihad Hospital in Nablus identified the
Palestinian who died in the overnight clash as Ahmad Sharnobi, 22,
of Askar refugee camp. They also said three were injured.
   He was the third Palestinian fatality since Sunday and the 252nd
in violence since Dec. 8, when Palestinian revolted against two
decades years of Israeli occupation in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip. Four Israelis have been killed.
   A military spokesman said violence erupted after security forces
entered the Askar camp ``for initiated operations'' aimed at
preventing riots during the strike. The spokesman refused to
elaborate.
   Arab news reports said the injuries came when plainclothes
security agents opened fire after activists warned Palestinians
through loudspeakers that Israelis were in the camp.
   After the incident, soldiers imposed a curfew on Askar, two
neighboring refugee camps and the city of Nablus, the army said.
The restrictions confined about 140,000 people to their homes.
   The Palestinian general strike was called in leaflets issued
earlier this month by the underground United National Leadership of
the Uprising.
   It shut down public transportation and shops in Israeli-annexed
Arab east Jerusalem and major cities in the occupied territories
including Nablus, Ramallah, Hebron and Bethlehem, Arab news reports
said.
   Near Bethlehem, a group of 17 masked Palestinian youths gathered
on the Hebron-Jerusalem highway and stoned dozens of Arab cars
carrying workers to jobs in Israel, forcing them to turn back.
   Associated Press reporter Haitham Hamad saw 14 cars with windows
smashed stopped along the highway near the Dheishe refugee camp.
   Leaflets said the strike was to protest Israel's confiscation of
the property or restriction of movement of Arabs who refused to pay
taxes.
   Tax boycotts have been a main element of the Palestinian revolt
against Israeli rule.
   Israel has deported 33 Palestinians since the beginning of the
uprising and an army spokesman said recently that about 5,500 Arabs
have been jailed, many without trial under administrative detention
orders.
</TEXT>
