<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--TrainFire     08-22 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Train Fire,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blaze Backs up Service on New York-Washington Amtrak Corridor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROVE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak service was back to normal today after
service between New York and Washington was blocked for four hours
by a fire in the locomotive of a passenger train, officials said.
   The 172 passengers aboard an Amtrak Metroliner were evacuated to
a rear car at 8:10 p.m. Sunday. No injuries were reported, Amtrak
spokeswoman Marci Larson said. The cause has not been determined,
and an investigation is under way.
   Overhead electric lines were shut off while firemen extinguished
the blaze. The tracks were reopened about 10:50 p.m. Sunday, but
had to be closed again at 12:10 a.m. for more than an hour because
the fire flared up a second time, officials said. A dozen trains in
the busy corridor were delayed.
   Amtrak spokeswoman Debbie Marciniak said morning traffic was
running normally.
