<1ST_LINE>u i PM-SAfrica-Conscription     08-22 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Conscription,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans Anti-Conscription Organization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today banned a
nationwide organization opposed to conscription laws requiring
white men to serve in the armed forces.
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok, acting under
state-of-emergency regulations, said the End Conscription Campaign
was banned from carrying out any activities.
   Action against the organization was expected since 143 young
white men, in the broadest challenge ever of the conscription
system, announced Aug. 3 that they would refuse to perform
mandatory military service. Most of the men face six-year jail
terms.
   Leaders of the End Conscription Campaign denied involvement in
organizing the mass resistance, but Defense Minister Magnus Malan
said he held the group responsible for the ``subversive action.''
   The organization appealed unsuccessfully for a system of
alternative, non-military service for men politically or morally
opposed to joining the army.
   It has argued that no one should be forced to serve
involuntarily in the army units that patrol black townships or in
the forces combating pro-independence guerrillas in South-West
Africa, also known as Namibia.
   Vlok, in a statement, said the End Conscription Campaign's
primary purpose was to undermine public support for the armed
forces.
   ``The ECC attempts to create an impression of political
neutrality,'' Vlok said. ``But it is not difficult to see the
organization's role in the revolutionary onslaught against South
Africa.''
   The End Conscription Campaign was formed in 1983, and many of
its members were detained or restricted since a national state of
emergency was declared in June 1986.
   In February, the organization said it suspected army involvement
in a harassment campaign that included anonymous telephone calls,
smear pamphlets and vandalism of members' property.
   South Africa's conscription laws allow conscientious objection
only for religious reasons, not on political or moral grounds. Only
whites are subject to conscription _ military service for other
races is voluntary.
   Vlok said the End Conscription Campaign's effort had been
endorsed by the African National Congress, the outlawed guerrilla
group waging a sabotage and bombing campaign aimed at ending
apartheid and overthrowing the South African government.
   Vlok also said the End Conscription Campaign had assisted draft
dodgers, helping them obtain residence permits to live in Britain.
   The government no longer disclosed how many men refuse to serve
in the military. In 1985, the last year figures were disclosed,
7,589 men declined to serve.
   The ban on the End Conscription Campaign is similar to bans
imposed in February on 17 anti-apartheid organizations. Under the
bans, the organizations are allowed to exist in name only.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
