<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Lebanon-UN     08-22 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-UN,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Peacekeeper Dies in Gun Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Irish soldier of the U.N. peacekeeping
force in south Lebanon accidentally shot and killed himself while
cleaning his rifle, a U.N. statement said today.
   Pvt. Patrick Wright, 27, was hit in the stomach Sunday, the
statement said. He was flown by helicopter to a U.N. field hospital
in the Lebanese border town of Naqoura but died a short while later.
   The shooting occurred in the village of Haddassa, which is
located within the area where the Irish battalion of the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon is stationed.
   Wright is the 156th U.N. peacekeeper to die since the 5,800
troops were deployed in south Lebanon in 1978 to serve as a buffer
between guerrillas and Israel. He was the 25th member of the
600-strong Irish battalion to die in the region.
   The U.N. force is made up of troops from France, Ireland,
Norway, Sweden, Finland, Nepal, Ghana, Fiji and Senegal.
</TEXT>
