<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Gittens     08-22 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Gittens,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`The Archers' Actor Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chriss Gittens, who performed for 35 years in the
British Broadcasting Corp.'s long-running radio serial ``The
Archers,'' has died at age 86.
   Gittens, who had a heart attack in 1959, had been in a nursing
home since the beginning of the month. The BBC said he died Sunday
in his sleep.
   Gittens played the irascible old countryman Walter Gabriel in a
series heard by 7 million listeners every weeknight. Anyone who
misses an episode can tune in to a Sunday ``omnibus'' edition of
the week's highlights.
   ``The Archers,'' concerning the everyday dramas of life in
fictional Ambridge in the English Midlands, began in 1951.
   Gittens, who was also an electrician for many years, made
appearances in the early days of the program as a policeman, a bank
manager and various government inspectors. He joined the permanent
cast in 1953, on the death of the actor who created the character
of Walter Gabriel.
   Over the years, he made the role his own. Gittens will not be
replaced, the BBC's head of network radio for the Midlands, Jock
Gallagher, said Sunday.
   ``We wouldn't think for a minute of casting someone else in that
part,'' he said.
   David Hatch, managing director of BBC network radio, said:
``Chriss was one of the great personalities. He created a character
that will live in the minds and hearts of listeners for a long time
to come. There are not many actors in soap operas who achieve the
kind of affection that Chriss established for that rascal Walter.''
</TEXT>
