<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AndeanCondors     08-22 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Andean Condors,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Andean Condor Dies En Route to Experiment for California Condor
Recovery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL FLEEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One zoo-hatched Andean condor died in transit
to a wilderness area but three others survived for an experiment
intended to show the best way to reintroduce endangered California
condors into the wild.
   The surviving birds were safely placed in secret holding pens
Saturday in Los Padres National Forest, and more Andean condors
will be taken to the area in October, said Joe Dowhan, condor
recovery coordinator for the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   The dead bird was sent to San Diego for an autopsy, Dowhan said.
   He said its death will have little effect on the program. ``In
some ways, you kind of want things to go wrong now instead of
later,'' he said.
   The South American birds, all females to prevent breeding in the
wild, are being used to test techniques biologists hope to use to
begin returning the California condor to the wild after their
numbers are increased in a captive breeding program.
   Only 28 California condors are known to survive, all in
captivity at the San Diego Wild Animal Park and the Los Angeles Zoo.
   The Andean condor was chosen for the experiment because it is
the closest living relative to the California condor. Though the
Andean condors are also endangered, they number in the thousands.
   Scientists are conducting the experiment to see how birds
hatched in captivity adapt to freedom and fend for themselves
without native birds of their species to serve as examples.
   The 3- and 4-month-old birds will spend several weeks in mesh
enclosures in the forest 75 miles northwest of Los Angeles.
   When the Andean birds are able to fly, around November,
scientist will fit them with radio transmitters, release them and
monitor their progress.
   The Andean birds will remain in the wild until it's time to
release California condors, perhaps as early as 1992 if the captive
breeding program continues to succeed, Dowhan said.
</TEXT>
