<HEAD>Hawke Appoints Constitutional Lawyer As New Foreign Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANBERRA, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke today
appointed Sen. Gareth Evans as minister for foreign affairs and
trade.
   Evans, 43, a constitutional lawyer and a former attorney
general, was most recently minister for transport and
communications. He fills the vacancy made when Bill Hayden resigned
last week to become governor-general.
   In other major Cabinet changes announced today, Sen. Robert Ray
will take over from Clyde Holding as minister for immigration,
local government and ethnic affairs.
   Ralph Willis will become minister for transport and
communication and Peter Morris will succeed Willis as industrial
relations minister.
   Holding will take over the arts and territories portfolio from
Gary Punch, who will become a junior minister in transport and
communications.
   The changes take effect Sept. 2.
</TEXT>
