<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HuntBrothers-Troubles     08-22 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hunt Brothers-Troubles,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silver Decision Another Slip In Hunts' Fortunes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury's order that the Hunt brothers pay
more than $130 million to a Peruvian company for their scheme to
corner the world silver market marks another setback in the
fortunes of the flamoyant Dallas family.
   However, Saturday's jury decision in New York will have little
effect on the Hunts' efforts to settle a $1.5 billion dispute with
their lenders, a Hunt bankruptcy attorney said.
   Besides the legal judgment, the collapse of silver, sugar and
real estate investments have all contributed to the steady decline
of the family fortune, once estimated at $20 billion.
   The jury said the three Hunt brothers conspired to artificially
raise the price of silver in the late 1970s to the detriment of
Minpeco S.A., the mining marketing company of the Peruvian
government.
   Bunker Hunt, 62, and Herbert Hunt, 59, also were found to have
engaged in a pattern of racketeering activity to monopolize the
silver market. The case is a civil action, so no criminal penalties
are attached to the finding.
   Minpeco had said Lamar Hunt, 56, owner of the National Football
League's Kansas City Chiefs, and his two brothers conspired
unsuccessfully with several Middle East businessmen to corner the
silver market.
   But an attorney in the two-year dispute with lenders said the
damages awarded in the silver battle were relatively small.
   ``I feel like the Hunts won,'' Henry Simon, the bankruptcy
attorney representing Placid Oil Co., which is owned by the trust
estate of the Hunt brothers, told the Dallas Times Herald.
   The $130 million damages could be reduced by the $33.4 million
amount Minpeco earned on silver it held during the period, Simon
said. And $64.7 million, which Minpeco received from other
defendants in a pretrial settlement, could also be deducted from
the amount the Hunts must pay, he said.
   The Hunts will file motions that raise other issues in the
silver case, said Tom Whitaker, Hunt Energy Corp. vice president.
   ``The brothers are confident that this wrong result will
eventually be overturned as they proceed through the court
system,'' Whitaker said Saturday.
   At first, the Hunts, sons of the late Texas oilman H.L. Hunt,
took their losses with aplomb. In March 1980, when the silver
market crashed, Bunker Hunt said, ``A billion dollars just ain't
what it used to be.''
   In 1986, the brothers were all on the Fortune 400 list of the
richest Americans with combined estimated assets of $1 billion.
Last year, they dropped off the list.
   This year, when forced to sell his seven Kentucky farms and
600-horse stable of thoroughbred race horses, the eldest Hunt
didn't attend the auction.
   ``It would be too sad to watch,'' he said.
   The Hunts sued their banks and lenders in July 1986, after they
could not renegotiate loans for their Placid Oil Co. and Penrod
Drilling Co.
   The two companies had failed to make payments on a total of $1.5
billion in loans.
   To settle the dispute, the Hunts proposed this spring to pay
$663.5 million from funds raised through Placid operations,
primarily in the North Sea. Hearings on the bankruptcy settlement
proposal were scheduled to begin this month.
</TEXT>
