<1ST_LINE>r n PM-LostTown     08-22 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lost Town,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reunion For Former Residents Of Town Lost To Reservoir</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANA, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dana hasn't existed for a half-century,
except in the hearts of its former residents.
   But for five hours Sunday, there was a homecoming for the
survivors and children of the 500 people who once lived in the
town, first settled in 1763 but erased 50 years ago so Boston could
have drinking water.
   Four little central Massachusetts towns died on April 27, 1938,
on order of the state Legislature to form the 38-square-mile
Quabbin Reservoir, after the U.S. Supreme Court rejected their
appeals.
   Three _ Enfield, Prescott and Greenwich _ now lie under 413
billion gallons of water. Only the Dana Common, surrounded by empty
cellars on high ground on the east side of the Swift River valley,
escaped the inundation.
   ``It's the one place left where people can touch what was
formerly there. Everything else is under water,'' said Terry
Campbell, who runs weekly teas for former residents, many now in
the 70s and 80s.
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis declared 1988 a Year of Remembrance for
the 2,500 people who lost their homes to the reservoir. Many of
those who moved away have returned this spring and summer to attend
events sponsored by local historical societies.
   ``I was just 10 years old when we had to go. It was hard,'' said
Florence Avery. ``I remember them digging up the bodies in the
cemetery. And my grandfather's house.''
   Mrs. Avery, her five brothers and one of her five sisters, as
well as her 90-year-old mother, Jennie Belle Cooley, visited the
site of their former home beside the deserted Common.
   ``There's still a lot of heavy sentiment that's passed on from
generation to generation,'' said Robert Boutelle, past president of
the Petersham Historical Society and Sunday's master of ceremonies.
``It was like the people who lost their homes were put on a ship
and removed from the United States.''
</TEXT>
