<DOCNO> AP880822-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1110EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LBJInsider     08-22 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LBJ Insider,0695</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former LBJ Aide Tells of President's Irrational Fears</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note language in 8th, 12th grafs may be offensive to some
readers</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A book describing Lyndon B. Johnson as a fearful,
even paranoid president was criticized today by a former Johnson
press secretary as the work of someone who barely knew the former
president.
   Former Secretary of State Dean Rusk, meanwhile, disputed one
incident described in the book.
   In a soon-to-be-published book entitled, ``Remembering America:
A Voice from the Sixties,'' former Johnson speechwriter Richard
Goodwin describes Johnson as intensely fearful of his political
rivals and prone to lapse into irrational ramblings about them.
   ``I am very very uneasy about diagnoses of paranoia, even when
they're made by an expert and Goodwin's not an expert,'' said
former press secretary George Reedy. ``Goodwin really only knew him
for a year or so and didn't really know him too well for that
year.''
   Johnson frequently ``would blow off steam,'' Reedy said, and
White House aides understood that they should ignore some of the
wild directives he would issue during these episodes, Reedy said.
In addition, he said, Johnson was highly manipulative and may have
intended to shock Goodwin, whom he knew to be a friend of Robert F.
Kennedy.
   ``I don't think he has enough background to put it in the right
perspective,'' Reedy said of Goodwin.
   Rusk, in a telephone interview today, said, ``I pay no attention
whatever to talk like that from Richard Goodwin. I consider it
irresponsible and untrue.''
   The book quotes Johnson referring to blacks as ``niggers;''
calling top foreign service officials as ``those damn Kennedy
ambassadors trying to get me and discredit me;'' and accusing
liberals and top newspaper columnists of being communists. Johnson
is also portrayed as obsessed with Robert Kennedy, whom he accused
of plotting against him.
   An advance chapter of the book provided to The Associated Press
focused on Johnson's behavior in 1965, a year when he was at the
height of his political power. Johnson was planning the first
full-scale commitment of American troops to Vietnam while in
Congress he was pushing landmark legislation on poverty and civil
rights.
   In April 1965, Goodwin wrote, Johnson canceled a scheduled visit
by the leaders of Pakistan and India after the two expressed
opposition to the Vietnam War. Goodwin described a heated
conversation between Johnson and Rusk after the U.S. ambassadors to
those countries suggested Johnson send Vice President Hubert
Humphrey to South Asia to ease any hurt feelings.
   ``Johnson read them, then, his face contorted in fury, rose and
slammed them onto his desk. `I don't want telegrams like that,' he
almost shouted, then picked up the phone. `Get me Rusk. ... Listen
Mr. Secretary,' he began, softly sardonic, `You know those
telegrams about Humphrey?'... The president suddenly raised his
voice: `If they send me any more telegrams like that, I want you to
call them back. Fire the bunch of them.'''
   Johnson hung up and said to his aides, ``It's those damn Kennedy
ambassadors trying to get me and discredit me.'' Goodwin said he
was told by a White House correspondent that Johnson had referred
to the snubbed leaders as, ``those two niggers.''
   Rusk said today, ``No such phone call took place and I don't
remember the cancellation of those two visits.''
   Goodwin, although not a trained psychologist, argued that
Johnson exhibited paranoid behavior. The conclusion is based on
Goodwin's observations as well as discussions about Johnson the
author had at the time with a psychiatrist.
   ``Lyndon Johnson had become a very dangerous man,'' wrote
Goodwin, a resident of Concord, Mass. ``There is no question in my
mind that both the atmosphere of the White House and the decisions
taken until 1965 (the only period I personally observed) were
affected by the periodic disruptions of Lyndon Johnson's mind and
spirit.''
   Goodwin was an aide to President John F. Kennedy and later was
the senior speech writer for Johnson. Goodwin left the Johnson
administration in 1965 and later became an opponent of the Vietnam
War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
