<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Britain-IRA 1stLd-Writethru a0524 08-22 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-IRA, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0524,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Won't Rule Out Internment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Thatcher saying she hasn't
ruled out internment, edit for transition. Picks up 11 graf pvs
``Heath said...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher today refused to
rule out detention without trial for guerrilla suspects, saying she
wanted to keep the IRA guessing following the killing of eight
British soldiers.
   ``You do not tell your enemies precisely what it is you are
going to do, ever,'' she said. ``We are having a thorough
(security) review of all matters and nothing has been ruled out.''
   Her comments appeared to contradict The Times of London, which
quoted unidentified government sources saying she had rejected
calls by Protestant leaders in Northern Ireland for the internment
of 60 to 80 known Irish Republican Army guerrillas.
   Internment without trial was introduced in Northern Ireland on
Aug. 9, 1971 by the government of Conservative Prime Minister
Edward Heath. Following worldwide criticism, it was abandoned by
the government of Labor Prime Minister Harold Wilson in December
1975.
   Speaking to reporters after opening a hospital in the southwest
England port of Plymouth, Mrs. Thatcher branded the IRA bus bombing
an assassination. She vowed, ``We must never let the terrorists
win.''
   Official Unionist lawmaker Ken Maginnes, one of the lawmakers
who wants internment brought back, confirmed today that he gave
Mrs. Thatcher the names of three IRA men he claimed were involved
in Friday night's bombing.
   The attack killed eight and wounded 27 young members of the
First Battalion of the Light Infantry who were just coming off
furlough in mainland Britain. The IRA claimed responsibility
immediately afterward.
   It was the deadliest IRA attack since 1982 and brought the
number of military deaths in a summer blitz to 26.
   Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, the Cabinet member
responsible for the province, visited some of the injured and
promised a relentless campaign against ``the men of evil.''
   He said the government and the army would take whatever steps
were necessary to defend ``what is good and what is right in
Northern Ireland.''
   However, the British Broadcasting Corp. said King is convinced
reintroduction of internment would be counter-productive. King met
with security chiefs in Northern Ireland today.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Northern Ireland. It wants to unite the predominantly Protestant
province with the overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic.
   Heath said in a BBC radio interview Sunday that his government
quickly realized after the introduction of internment in 1971 that
the policy had been a major mistake.
   He said: ``The people who were interned really bore very little
resemblance to those who were out to cause damage. The way in which
they were arrested ... caused reaction ... throughout the United
States and the rest of the world, which was very damaging to us.
   ``Thirdly, it gave the IRA a means of recruiting from amongst
people who were interned,'' he said.
   Critics of internment said many of the hundreds of people
rounded up were innocent. They also said many of the internees were
brutally treated and that the policy discriminated against Roman
Catholics.
   In 1978, the European Court of Human Rights ruled that Britain
had been guilty of inhuman and degrading treatment, in a case
brought by 12 former internees subjected to in-depth interrogation.
</TEXT>
