<2ND_LINE>PM-Leftover Money,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Treasury Closer to Getting $100,000 Left by Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than four years after a widow with
no children died and left about $135,000 to the federal government
to reduce the national debt, the money is still in the bank drawing
interest.
   Lawyers for three parties _ the deceased, Minnie Vogel, the
federal government and the Kentucky Revenue Cabinet _ only recently
worked out an agreement to dispose of the estate.
   The agreement capped a lengthy dispute over whether the state is
entitled to claim inheritance tax from Ms. Vogel's estate. Under
the agreement, the state may claim its share _ about $30,000 _ and
the federal government gets the rest.
   The agreement was recently approved by Jefferson Circuit Judge
Edmund P. Karem. Now the parties are awaiting final approval from
Jefferson District Probate Court, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Michael F. Spalding, who is handling the case for the federal
government.
   When Ms. Vogel, of Louisville, died in May 1984 at age 85, she
left about $35,000 and some property to seven nieces and nephews.
The rest, about $135,000, ``I bequeath and devise to my beloved
country, the United States of America, to be used to reduce the
national debt,'' the will stated.
   Efforts to settle the estate hit a snag soon after her death
when the state tried to claim inheritance taxes from the money that
was to go to the federal government. The federal government agreed
to pay the inheritance tax, but Vogel's lawyer sued, saying he did
not think it was Ms. Vogel's intent that part of her money should
go to the state.
   Although the federal government will still receive more than
$100,000 if the compromise is approved, David Liebschutz, a
spokesman for the U.S. Bureau of Public Debt, noted that it won't
make a noticeable dent in the public debt, now at $2.5 trillion.
</TEXT>
