<HEAD>Wheel Flies Off Car, Bounces through Bus Windshield, Killing
Driver</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with comments from man who helped steer
bus. No pickup. Removes BRF designation from slugline.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wheel flew off a car on a freeway and
crashed through a bus windshield, killing the driver, but two
passengers steered the bus to safety without injuries, authorities
said.
   Bobby Hall, a 52-year-old Southern California Rapid Transit
District driver, was killed in Sunday's accident on the Harbor
Freeway, said Officer Diane Lowery of the California Highway Patrol.
   Hall had been driving southbound about 55 mph when a vehicle
traveling in the opposite direction lost its left front wheel. The
wheel bounced over the highway divider and crashed into the
windshield, Lowery said.
   An unidentified woman, partially blocked by Hall's body,
grappled with the steering wheel while Rancho Palos Verdes
pharmacist William H. Patterson operated the accelerator and brake.
   ``I don't know anything about gears or anything like that,''
Patterson said. ``I was afraid to take my foot off the brake. I was
really just pressing radio buttons asking for help.''
   It took the two a tense three minutes to bring the bus to a halt
after the bus ran into an embankment. None of the 12 passengers
aboard the 40-seat bus was injured.
   The car involved was found abandoned on the freeway. Authorities
were searching for its owner, Lowery said.
