<HEAD>Preaching Boy Suspended on First Day of School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with school videotaping
confrontation to back up principal's version; Picks up 6th graf,
`The father ...'; SUBS grafs 10-11, ``They just ...' with 3 grafs
with details on suspension, warning; Picks up 12th graf, `Duffey
and ...'; SUBS 19th graf, `Ricketts and ...' to conform; DELETES
last two grafs to tighten.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A street-preaching 11-year-old was suspended
minutes after arriving for the first day of school today after he
stuck a Bible in the principal's face and told him ``you go to
hell,'' school officials said.
   ``I have trouble when a child says (that) to an authority
figure,'' said Jim Gorst, principal of Eastfield Elementary School.
   Duffey Strode, 11, had taken only about 10 steps on school
property before he confronted Gorst, said David Strode, the boy's
father, who quoted his son as telling the principal, ``you'll go to
hell.''
   School officials, however, captured the confrontation on
videotape which confirms Gorst's version, said Shirley Ramsey,
Eastfield's assistant principal.
   Strode said he took all three of his preaching children home
after Duffey's suspension, and did not know whether he would take
them to school Tuesday. Last year, Duffey was repeatedly suspended
for shouting Bible verses and preaching against ``whoremongers''
and ``fornicators.''
   The father said today's trouble began when a sheriff's deputy
took the hand of Pepper, 7, who started screaming, and Duffey
``became enraged.''
   Strode and his wife, Robin, have been banned from school
property and watched from beyond the gates.
   Family friends had planned to escort the children from the gate
to the school building, but officials instead ordered the deputies
to take the children. That's when Pepper began screaming, Strode
said.
   Gorst then asked Strode to bring his children into the school.
Strode said he refused and walked away with the three children. At
that point, Gorst asked him to bring the younger children back,
saying only Duffey was suspended, Strode said.
   ``They just don't want Duffey at school, period,'' Strode said.
   Duffey was suspended for 10 days for disruptive and
disrespectful behavior, Ms. Ramsey said. And she warned that a
long-term suspension that could last the entire school year ``can
be enacted at any point.''
   ``School officials have simply said at this point that they will
not have this continue for the year,'' she said.
   Duffey and his brother, Matthew, 6, were preaching on their way
to the school grounds, Strode said. Pepper, who did not preach last
year, yelled ``repent'' a couple of times, he said.
   Earlier, McDowell County Schools Superintendent David Ricketts
said he and other school officials dreaded the first day of school
because last year, the Strode children had preached about
``whoremongers and ``fornicators.''
   ``We cannot go through another year like we did last year,'' he
said.
   Ricketts on Friday notified Mrs. Strode and her husband, David,
in a registered letter that they were barred from the school
grounds; he warned them that ``appropriate action'' would be taken
if they came onto school property.
   The trouble began last spring when Duffey, a fifth-grade A
student, came to school one morning in March and stood near the
back entrance shouting Bible verses.
   When teachers and students passed, Duffey shouted verses about
whoremongers and fornicators. When the principal asked Duffey to
come inside the school, he refused.
   Soon after, kindergartener Matthew did the same thing.
First-grader Pepper accompanied Matthew but did not preach. Mrs.
Strode said Pepper would join her brothers in quoting scriptures
this year.
   Ricketts and Ms. Ramsey say they're concerned about the Strode
children's effect on other children at the school, especially
kindergarten students, who on their first day of school will be
confronted by yelling children and parents.
   They're urging parents to stay calm.
   ``We're hoping the citizens of the county will be understanding
and realize we are doing everything we can as fast as we can,''
Ricketts said.
</TEXT>
