<1ST_LINE>u a PM-ContraSupplies     08-22 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Supplies,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictment Accuses Six Of Running Private Contra Supply Operation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Cuban-Americans are accused of violating the
U.S. Neutrality Act by mounting a private Contra supply operation
out of a clandestine southwest Florida camp, according to an
indictment unsealed today.
   At one point, 60 men were being trained in the camp on the
outskirts of Naples, Fla., with money supplied by two Miami-area
men, Eulalio Francisco Castro and Joseph Marcos, prosecutors said
today.
   Some of the men are accused of shipping weapons to Costa
Rican-based commandoes for use against Nicaragua's Sandinista
government.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Schnapp said other names had come
up in the investigation, and that part of the case had been turned
over to the special prosecutor's office in Washington.
   Schnapp refused to answer any questions that he said were
outside the scope of the indictment, turning away queries about
whether U.S. military or intelligence officials oversaw the
supplying of weapons and mercenaries to fight the Sandinistas.
   The activities detailed today lasted from June 1983 until
September 1986, according to the indictment.
   Four of the six named in the June 28 indictment _ Castro,
Marcos, Rene Corvo and Sergio Becerra _ surrendered today to U.S.
Magistrate Lurana Snow in Fort Lauderdale, Schnapp said.
   Arrangements were being made for the surrender of the other two,
Rafael Torres Jimenez and Francisco Hernandez, he said. All were
expected to be released on bond, as were the defendants in an
associated indictment unsealed in Fort Lauderdale last month.
   The six were named on two counts of violating and conspiring to
violate the Neutrality Act and, if convicted on all charges, face a
maximum of eight years in prison. Corvo was also charged with
firearms violations, and faces up to 38 years if convicted on all
counts.
   The earlier indictment, returned by the same federal grand jury,
accused Mario Calero and ex-mercenary Jack Terrell, among others.
Mario Calero is a brother of Contra director Adolfo Calero.
   The only person to plead guilty in the earlier indictment was
sentenced by U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger of Fort Lauderdale
to one day's probation.
</TEXT>
