<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1253EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma Bjt   08-22 0778</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma, Bjt,0798</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds of Thousands Demand Democracy in Burma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES W. HATTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People filled the streets of Burmese
cities Monday demanding an end to 26 years of military rule, and
soldiers peacefully stopped protest marches in Rangoon, the
capital, diplomats and news reports said.
   The Japanese news agency Kyodo said hundreds of thousands of
people, including children, demonstrated in the northern city of
Mandalay in response to student calls for nationwide protest and a
general strike. Some waved the peacock flag used in the struggle
that led to independence from Britain in 1948.
   Many train and bus operators joined the strike, halting public
transport in Burma's second-largest city 350 miles north of the
capital, Kyodo said. There were sketchy reports of demonstrations
in other parts of the Southeast Asian country.
   Diplomats in Rangoon said about 20,000 people gathered outside
the Rangoon General Hospital, a center of protest, for the largest
demonstration in the capital since the street protests of Aug. 8-12
rioting that forced the resignation of President Sein Lwin, a
former general. Security forces killed more than 100 people that
week.
   No violence was reported Monday. Witnesses said large numbes of
soldiers, the most seen in recent days, manned barricades and
armored cars patrolled the capital. Reports of gunshots could not
be confirmed.
   A Western diplomat said 3,000-4,000 people shouted
anti-government slogans outside the U.S. Embassy, but soldiers and
barricades stopped them from marching down the street.
   Protesters demand that new President Maung Maung, who on Friday
became the country's first civilian leader in 26 years, end the
stern one-party rule of the Burma Socialist Program Party and the
economic hardship it has created.
   Burmese authorities ``want to avoid violence, but at the same
time they're determined that things don't get out of control,'' a
Western diplomat said. He added that students have called for daily
demonstrations.
   Diplomats said most people went to work despite the strike and
most shops in Rangoon were open.
   Kyodo said demonstrators students, Buddhist monks, public
servants and professionals were among demonstrators at the
hospital. It said they held banners and shouted slogans, including
``Down with one-party dictatorship!'' and ``Now more than ever
democracy!''
   Some attempted a one-mile march to the Sule Pagoda, where huge
rallies were held Aug. 8-12, but up to 15 truckloads of soldiers
were parked in front of it.
   ``When about half of those taking part in the rally set out to
march, they were blocked by soldiers,'' an Asian diplomat said.
   ``We've heard that the soldiers sent marchers running away but
there have been no reports of any injuries or deaths. From what I
observed, those taking part in the rally were generally ...
peaceful and the soldiers also seemed to be holding back.''
   At Victoria Point, at the Thai border in the south, about 10,000
people marched to the town hall Monday shouting anti-government
slogans, a Thai police official said.
   Victoria Point, 490 miles southeast of Rangoon, is a market ton
on the frontier between Megui province and Thailand's Ranong
province. Security forces there turned against the government
during the protests of Aug. 8-12 and gave protesters free rein,
Thai officials said.
   A man claiming to speak for a coalition of 16 university student
unions called news agencies in Bangkok and said the alliance was
seeking help from Burmese rebel groups in Bangkok. He claimed it
has about 50,000 members.
   Rebels hold large areas of Burma bordering Thailand. Brang Seng,
a leader of the National Democratic Front of 10 guerrilla armies,
declared last week it would join the protesting students.
   The Karen National Union, one of the strongest rebel groups,
issued a statement Monday in Bangkok declaring support for the
students and calling on foreign governments to halt aid to burma
until one-party rule ends.
   Maung Maung, the Western-educated attorney general, became
Burma's first civilian leader since Ne Win seized power in a 1962
military coup. Ne Win resigned in July and ally Sein Win replaced
him.
   Burma has been in turmoil since September 1987, when the
government voided 60 percent of the currency in circulation without
compensation. University students rioted to protest the resulting
hardship in a nation whose per capita annual income of less $200 is
among the world's lowest.
   More riots, increasingly focused on political demands, occurred
in March and June. Protesters accuse Sein Lwin of personally
ordering ruthless suppression of the demonstrations.
   Rioting resumed after Sein Lwin became president and party chief
July 27, and soldiers fired into crowds. The government has said
112 people were killed and 267 wounded in Rangoon alone, but
diplomats said they believed the toll was higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
