<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChallengerSuit     08-22 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Challenger Suit,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow, Rocket Company Reach Tentative Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tentative, undisclosed settlement was
reached today in a lawsuit filed by the widow of astronaut Michael
J. Smith, the pilot of the space shuttle Challenger, against the
manufacturer of a faulty booster rocket.
   ``We've resolved the matter subject to working out some
details,'' said William Maready, an attorney for Jane Smith.
   John Adler, a lawyer representing rocket manufacturer Morton
Thiokol Inc. said both sides would request that details of the
settlement not be disclosed.
   Mrs. Smith initially filed a wrongful death suit against Morton
Thiokol in federal court in Florida, but the case was transferred
to Virginia because of a backlog of cases in the Florida court.
   Smith, a Navy pilot, was one of seven crew members killed when
Challenger exploded after it was launched on Jan. 28, 1986. A
hearing on summary judgment motions was set for today before U.S.
District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr., but Merhige called the
attorneys into chambers and after two hours the tentative
settlement was announced.
   Maready and Adler said a statement would be released Tuesday,
but terms of any payment to Mrs. Smith would not be disclosed.
   The case was the last of the Challenger-Morton Thiokol suits to
be settled. Terms of the company's payments to the other families
also were not disclosed.
   Morton Thiokol manufactured the solid-fuel booster rocket blamed
for the explosion that destroyed the shuttle.
</TEXT>
