<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1319EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Pakistan     08-22 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Pakistan,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Cautions Soviets, India On Pakistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has informed the Soviet
Union and India that American support for Pakistan's security
remains strong in the wake of the death of President Mohammed Zia
ul-Haq.
   Separate messages were sent to both Moscow and New Delhi after
Zia's 11 years of rule ended in an air crash Wednesday in which
U.S. Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel and Brig. Gen. Herbert M. Wassom,
chief of the U.S. military group in Pakistan, also perished.
   ``The point is we wanted to reassure them that our policy is
unchanged, and that we are going to stand by Pakistan,'' said a
U.S. official who spoke Monday on condition of anonymity.
   The tone of the messages and conversations here and in Moscow
with Soviet diplomats was more pointed than in dealing with India,
said a second U.S. official. ``With the Soviets it was more in
terms of cautioning them about Afghanistan,'' said this official,
who also spoke anonymously.
   ``So far, the behavior is quite correct in each case,'' a third
U.S. official said.
   Pakistan under Zia was the closest U.S. ally in central Asia and
the conduit for the shipment of American and Chinese weapons to
Afghan rebels fighting a guerrilla war against the Afghan
government and Soviet troops.
   While the State Department has complimented caretaker President
Ghoulam Ishaq Khan about the steps he took after Zia's death,
including a decision to go ahead with national elections in
November, there is concern there could be prolonged instability in
Pakistan.
   So far, U.S. officials said, there is no indication that the
Soviets are slowing the pace of their troop withdrawal from
Afghanistan or seizing on the death of Zia to raise tensions in the
area.
   ``Their hostility to Pakistan has not ended,'' a U.S. official
told The Associated Press. ``They haven't backed off. But there is
no escalation. I think they understand very clearly our position.''
   India, which has gone to war several times with Pakistan since
the 1940s, has strong military ties with the Soviet Union.
   A funeral service for Raphel was held Monday at the Fort Myer
chapel in Arlington, Va. The speakers included Deputy Secretary of
State John C. Whitehead and veteran diplomat Philip C. Habib.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
