<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Writers     08-22 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Writers,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Writers Seek Release Of Imprisoned South Koreans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American delegation led by novelist
Susan Sontag plans to dramatize the imprisonment of four South
Korean literary figures to try to obtain their release.
   The 52nd International P.E.N. Congress, which will bring
together about 700 writers from Aug. 29 to Sept.2 in Seoul, plans
to introduce a resolution calling on South Korea's government to
release the four, a spokeswoman said Monday.
   P.E.N. identified those in prison as publisher Lee Tae-bok,
writer Kim Hyon-jang and poets Lee San-ha and Kim Nam-ju. Publisher
Kim Sang-bok was released from prison Aug. 15 as part of a general
amnesty program.
   The South Korean P.E.N. Center, which also has pressed for
release of the four, scheduled meetings this week with Justice
Minister Chong Hae-chang and sent letters to President Roh Tae-woo.
   ``The congress is a good chance to draw atention to this matter
worldwide,'' said H.B. Lee, a professor at Seoul National
University and a P.E.N. member. ``We hope this will be the right
setting at the right time to press for release.''
   Karen Kennerly, executive director of the American P.E.N. Center
in New York City, said Monday that while ``we recognize the great
strides toward democratization in South Korea, we find it
disturbing that four writers and publishers remain in jail.
   ``We had hoped to come to Seoul to celebrate their release and
hoped and expected them to join us, and other colleagues, at the
meetings,'' Ms. Kennerly said.
   She said Ms. Sontag plan to make an appeal to South Korea's
government for release of the four at a reception Aug. 30. The
delegations of Canada, Australia, Denmark, Sweden and the
Netherlands are to be co-hosts for the reception.
   Ms. Sontag, a novelist and essayist, is president of the
American chapter of P.E.N. and was one of four human rights
activists who sent South Korean President Roh Tae-woo a letter July
22 protesting the imprisonments.
   ``The April 1 sentencing of poet Lee San-ha to 1{ years in
prison for writing a poem is alarming evidence that the practice of
censorship _ in its most reprehensible form _ still exists,'' the
letter said.
   ``We note, too, that scores of books are subject to confiscation
because of their political content and that films and plays are
subject to censorship,'' the letter said.
   The letter claimed that licensing controls on foreign
publications ``severely limit the free flow of information ...
limit not only the right of Korean citizens to receive information,
but that of the participants in the P.E.N. Congress.''
   In addition to Ms. Sontag, those who signed the the letter
included Roland Algrant, chairman of the International Freedom to
Publish Committee, Sophie C. Silberberg, executive director of the
Fund for Free Expression and Jack Greenberg, chairman of Asia Watch
in Washington D.C.
</TEXT>
