<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Could it be that the Rolling Stones can't get no
satisfaction from playing apart? Former Stones vocalist Mick Jagger
says the splintered band is planning a reunion.
   ``We are talking about (a reunion) for 1989,'' Jagger told a
reporter Monday at Heathrow Airport en route to Australia from his
home in New York.
   Jagger refused to give details, but when asked what the
essential element of such a reunion would be, he answered,
``Pleasure.''
   The Rolling Stones' last album was ``Dirty Work'' in 1985. The
band's ``(I Can't Get No) Satisfaction'' was named the best single
recording from 1963-1988 by Rolling Stone magazine last week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Michael Thomas said his dual career of
singing and acting ``is like a coin _ heads is `Miami Vice' and
tails is music.''
   ``I was doing music long before I got into acting,'' said
Thomas, best known as the dapper detective Tubbs on the NBC series.
   Thomas visited the Warner Bros.@Elektra@Atlantic Records office
over the weekend, signing autographs and chatting with folks who
will handle distribution of his second album, ``Somebody.''
   ``Somebody'' features several songs written by Thomas and was
recorded with help from singers Nickolas Ashford, Valerie Simpson
and Maria Muldaur.
   Thomas, 42, was accompanied by his younger brother George, who
serves as his bodyguard.
   ``I can handle myself if there are any negative vibes,'' said
Thomas. ``George is just for getting through crowds and things. I
want to stay forever signing autographs and things, and there are
people who want to reach out and touch you.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Statler Brothers bassist Harold Reid
celebrated his 49th birthday with 6,500 ``guests'' at the Indiana
State Fair.
   When the country band announced during their performance Sunday
night that it was Reid's birthday, fans deluged him with cakes,
flowers, balloons and other presents.
   After the gift-giving, Reid's brother, Don, told the 6,500 fans,
``We've got a lot of things to do tonight, a lot of songs to sing,
a lot of memories to remember.''
   ``And a lot of things to forget,'' the birthday boy interjected.
   The band then launched into a string of songs that have earned
the Statlers more awards than any other country group, including
``Hello, Mary Lou,'' and ``Bed Of Roses.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>STATESVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``It's kind of weird seeing someone
else playing my life,'' says teen-age AIDS victim Ryan White, whose
struggle to attend public school is being made into a television
movie here.
   But Ryan, 16, is more than a bystander on the movie set. He has
been given a small role as an older hemophiliac who, like Ryan,
contracted AIDS from a blood transfusion.
   ``He's a natural,'' said Linda Otto, co-executive producer of
``The Ryan White Story,'' an ABC movie starring George C. Scott
which is being filmed in Statesville through Sept. 9.
   To Ryan, his small role reinforces the film's message that AIDS
cannot be transmitted through casual contact. ``It tells the story,
plus it helps educate people about AIDS and the hardships people go
through,'' he said in an interview Friday.
   The role of Ryan is being played by Lucas Haas, who starred
opposite Harrison Ford in ``Witness.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stage and screen legend Helen Hayes
has been hospitalized for an irregular heartbeat after falling ill
while visiting her son, actor James MacArthur.
   Doctors were trying to determine whether Miss Hayes, 87, had
suffered a heart attack or only altitude sickness. She was listed
in good condition Monday at St. Mary's Hospital.
   ``She is very tired and really apprehensive about the media
learning about her being here,'' Karen Bennett, a nursing
supervisor, said Sunday night.
   MacArthur's home is in Crested Butte, which has an elevation of
nearly 10,000 feet.
   ``I really feel it was just the altitude that was bothering
her,'' said Dr. Dan Tullius of Crested Butte. ``But she was sent to
Grand Junction to confirm whether or not she had a heart attack.
... She had an irregular heart beat and it could be secondary to
altitude.''
   The silver-haired actress has won a Tony, two Oscars and an
Emmy, and in 1981 received the Kennedy Center Honors for lifetime
achievement.
</TEXT>
