<HEAD>Plans Return to Vegas Stages After Five-Year Absence</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ann-Margret plans to return to the Las
Vegas stage in November after a five-year absence from the city
where she began her stage career as a teen-ager.
   She will perform Nov. 9-21 at Caesars Palace to start an
exclusive two-year pact which also includes performances at Caesars
World hotels in Atlantic City and Lake Tahoe, Nev.
   Ann-Margret was one of the hottest attractions in Las Vegas
until she quit to spend more time with her husband, actor Roger
Smith, and to pursue other career interests.
   During the last six years, Ann-Margret has received critical
acclaim and three Emmy nominations for ``Who Will Love My
Children,'' ``A Streetcar Named Desire,'' and ``The Two Mrs.
Grenvilles.''
   She recently co-starred with Alan Alda in ``A New Life.''
   The Swedish beauty burst upon the Las Vegas scene in 1960 when
comic George Burns selected her as an opening act for his show. In
the years that followed, she became one of Las Vegas' most popular
singers and dancers.
