<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Afghan-Terrorism     08-22 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Terrorism,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghanistan Blamed For High Terror Rate in Pakistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A terrorist campaign in Pakistan carried out
by agents of Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government accounted for
well over half of all incidents of state-sponsored terrorism
worldwide last year, according to a State Department report
released Monday.
   Out of 189 such cases, Afghanistan carried out 127 against
Pakistan in its campaign of retaliation for Pakistan's backing of
Afghanistan's anti-communist guerrilla movement, the report said.
   The report was prepared before last Wednesday's incident in
which a mysterious plane crash killed Pakistani President Mohammed
Zia ul-Haq, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel, Brig. Gen. Herbert
Wassom and 27 others.
   Pakistani officials suspect sabotage but investigators lack
conclusive evidence as to the cause of the crash, which occurred
330 miles south of Islamabad.
   State Department officials, insisting on anonymity, said any
comment on the cause of the crash would be speculative but added
that Afghan agents have to be ``among the suspects'' because of
their alleged role in fomenting terrorism in Pakistan.
   Diplomats at the Afghan Embassy here were unavailable for
comment.
   Paul Kriesburg, a senior associate at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, said it would be a mistake to assume
automatically that Afghan agents were responsible for the crash
because Zia had many other enemies. They included some from within
the Pakistani military and others who were alienated by his
authoritarian rule.
   The State Department compilation indicated that Afghan-sponsored
terrorist acts almost tripled those of Iran, listed second with 44.
Libya was third with 7 terrorist episodes.
   All told, there were 832 international terrorist incidents last
year, according to the study.
   ``When the Pakistani numbers are subtracted, the number of
incidents in the rest of the world declined by almost 10 per cent
from 1986 statistics,'' the report said.
   It said the Pakistan campaign is being waged by the Afghan
Ministry of State Security, known by the acronym WAD.
   Zia said last November that the assassinations and bombings
carried out against Pakistani civilians were ``at the behest of the
Soviet Union'' but Moscow has denied the allegation.
   U.S. and Pakistani officials estimate that bombs planted by
Afghan agents have killed more than 400 civilians in Pakistan. The
bloodiest incident occurred in July 1987 when three car bombs
exploded in the main bazaar of Karachi, killing 72 and injuring 260.
   The report said it is likely that the Soviets have been aware of
Afghan operations in Pakistan because of the close ties between WAD
and the Soviet intelligence agency, KGB.
   It said that while some of the material for the explosive
devices can be purchased on the black market, other items can be
obtained only through Soviet sources.
   Pakistan estimates that about 1,500 Soviet advisers work with
WAD.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
