<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtHay     08-22 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Hay,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought-Stricken Iowa Farmers Go A-Haying To Idaho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER MUNNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers leaving for 10 days of
harvesting free hay in Idaho boarded buses in a downpour Monday,
providing hope that their own drought-ravaged pastures might be
green by the time they get home.
   ``But it will still take several weeks for that forage to grow
back up, assuming we get enough rain, and even then you wonder what
kind of growth there will be,'' said Dale Johnson, manager of the
Farm Bureau Spokesman, a publication of the Iowa Farm Bureau.
   ``The drought has killed off part of it, and then if you have a
frost the first part of October, that will curb things a little
bit, too,'' he said.
   About 60 farmers boarded two chartered buses for the trip,
hoping to harvest a train load of hay from reserve acreage.
   ``A lot of these guys really need the hay, so they made a quick
decision to come. Some people hired people to go in their place,''
Johnson said.
   The venture is a cooperative effort of the Farm Bureau in Idaho
and Iowa, with Greyhound donating the buses, Burlington Northern
railroad donating freight space for the baled hay and three banks
in Chariton, south of Des Moines, putting up cash for meals along
the way. Murdock said he expects other banks will also chip in.
   In spite of the donated services, organizer Don Murdock said he
initially had trouble recruiting a crew for the excursion because
the drought has made it even more difficult for farmers to leave
home for extended periods.
   Murdock, a regional manager of the Farm Bureau's office in
Chariton, said many farmers were reluctant to commit a week to 10
days because the drought makes it necessary for them to haul water
and feed to cattle.
   But when word spread, he said, the first bus filled up quickly
and the second bus was filled nearly as fast.
   In addition, he said, about 15 more farmers will leave for Idaho
later this week.
   Murdock said the Idaho Farm Bureau offered unlimited hay to
drought-stricken farmers if they would supply the labor for the
harvest. The hay will come from private fields ordinarily idled
under the federal government's Conservation Reserve Program but
freed because of the drought.
   Murdock said he was told that 200 tons of hay already has been
shipped to North Dakota and that he hoped Iowans could fill a
freight train.
   ``I don't know how much we can harvest, but if we've got 75 guys
out there on modern machinery haying all day, that's a lot of
hay,'' said Johnson.
   Murdock said first priority for the hay will go to those making
the trip.
   Those next in line will be farmers needing hay but unable for
physical or other reasons to go to Idaho, including an elderly
couple that Murdock said were feeding their cattle by cutting down
trees so the animals can eat the foliage.
   ``The lady is about 70 and said she can run machinery and wanted
to go while her husband, about 75, stayed behind,'' Murdock said.
``I wouldn't let her go but I'm going to make darn sure they get
some hay.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
