<DOCNO> AP880822-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1454EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-TheQuayleImage Bjt   08-22 0797</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-The Quayle Image, Bjt,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Not Exactly What Bush Had in Mind For His Post-Convention Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN WOLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dan Quayle dilemma, revolving generally
around questions of inexperience and privilege, has ensnarled
George Bush at a critical moment and threatens the Republican
candidate's appeal to the ``Reagan Democrats'' who helped make him
what he is today.
   The emerging image of Quayle as an overindulged rich kid is not
so much Quayle's problem as Bush's: the issues reflect as much on
Bush's judgment in 1988 as Quayle's judgment as a 22-year-old in
1969.
   While decrying the ``shrill partisan attacks'' against Quayle,
Bush apparently can't answer the Quayle questions himself. Last
Friday he was asked by Time magazine if the media was overreacting
to the Quayle questions, and said:
   ``Yes. Damn right. But I don't know what the facts are. I have
to wait and see what facts are driving this.''
   Bush would rather be talking about his ``L-word,'' the brand of
Democratic liberalism he associates with George McGovern, Jimmy
Carter, Ted Kennedy and now Michael Dukakis. But the Quayle matter
makes that practically impossible; in political terms, Bush has
lost control of the agenda.
   ``I wish all this weren't churning around out there,'' Bush told
Time. ``It's distracting attention from the campaign itself.''
   Republican activists across the country have been supportive of
Quayle, while the Washington GOP establishment is openly wary.
   Karen Stram, chairwoman of the Maine Republican Party, calls the
Quayle controversy ``peripheral,'' and says voters deserve to hear
a clear dialogue between Bush and Dukakis. She complained that TV
coverage of Bush's big night in New Orleans last Thursday could be
summed up: ``He gave a good speech. And the latest on the Quayle
story is ...''
   House Republican Leader Bob Michel, asked if Quayle should be
taken off the ticket, said Monday, ``If there was something
additional that came up that was a distraction or a
disqualification, well, the option's always there. But I don't see
it at this juncture.''
   Was Bush's choice of Quayle a mistake? ``I'm not going to call
it a mistake yet,'' he said, adding, ``Once you've committed
yourself to a role, you pretty much have to see it through.''
   A similar not-too-ringing endorsement came Sunday from Senate
Republican Leader Bob Dole, the World War II combat hero who
apparently ran second in Bush's vice presidential deliberations. He
embraced the ticket again, but said, ``Right now I'd guess there
are a number of Reagan Democrats who are going to remain undecided
or maybe go the other way (to Dukakis).
   ``I mean, they're out there in my little hometown,'' he said of
these crossover voters who put Reagan and Bush in office, ``And I
must tell you, in my generation you knew who was in the Guard and
who was in uniform fighting for their country. So they're very
sensitive about it _ they didn't have anybody they could call ...
Well, my father wore overalls, who's he going to influence?''
   Most recent surveys indicate Dukakis leads Bush among the
Reagan-Democrats already; the scent of special privilege can't help
among the overall and blue-collar voters that Dole refers to.
   Today, the questions of Quayle privilege amount to this:
   Did Quayle use unusual family influence to get into the National
Guard, thereby ducking the draft and an almost certain ticket to
Vietnam? Did Quayle trade on family influence to get into Indiana
University Law School after being a ``proverbial C+ student,'' as
an undergraduate.
   ``There's been nothing that has been substantiated that any
rules were violated, that we did anything that was unfair,'' Quayle
said Monday in response to questions about his entry to law school
and the guard.
   On another matter, Quayle was asked last week what executive
experience had prepared him to become vice president, and cited,
among other things, his work in the attorney general's office while
attending law school at night.
   Now questions are being raised as to how the young Quayle landed
this job. Quayle's father says an influential family employee got
Quayle an interview with the attorney general.
   These matters caught off-guard a presidential campaign that is
bragging about its competence and had since March 8 to evaluate the
many Republicans who might add to the Bush ticket. Did Quayle
mislead the Bush interviewers? Did Bush and his people ask the
right questions?
   However voters eventually decide to judge the Quayle candidacy,
answering these questions is not the way George Bush hoped to take
advantage of the momentum he earned Thursday night in New Orleans.
Conservative columnists Evans and Novak described the Quayle
questions as a ``skunk at the picnic.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Jonathan Wolman is assistant bureau chief for
the AP in Washington.
</TEXT>
