<2ND_LINE>AM-Preaching Kids,0512</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Preaching Strode Child Suspended On First Day Of School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARION, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A street-preaching 11-year-old was told to
go home on the first day of school Monday after reportedly telling
his principal to ``go to hell.''
   ``I have trouble when a child says (that) to an authority
figure,'' Jim Gorst, principal of Eastfield Elementary School, said
Monday.
   David Strode, said his son, Duffey, had told Gorst ``you'll go
to hell.'' School officials said the boy's message was a more blunt
``you go to hell.''
   After Duffey was suspended for 10 days, Strode took all three of
his children home, and said he did not know whehter they would try
to go to school on Tuesday.
   Before classes opened, school officials said they would not
permit classes to be disrupted as they were last year when Duffey
staked out a back entrance of the school and yelled out Bible
verses condemning ``whoremongers'' and ``fornicators.''
   The boy yelled at the principal after a sheriff's deputy tried
to escort the children onto the grounds of the school, said Strode.
   When a deputy took the hand of Pepper, 7, she screamd and Duffey
``became enraged,'' said the father, who watched the proceedings
from outside the school gates.
   ``They (school officials) wanted to provoke those children and
they did,'' Strode said.
   Shirley Ramsey, the assistant principal, said the school had
videotaped the incident, as it has done in previous instances of
Duffey's preaching. She said the recording indicated the boy told
Gorst, ``you go to hell.''
   ``The issue here is God and the devil,'' Strode said. ``The gods
of the public school system are Horace Mann and John Dewey. Their
religion is this _ humanism, evolution, integration. That's why
they don't want the kids promoting the King James Bible around the
school anywhere.''
   Duffey was suspended for disruptive and disrespectful behavior,
Ms. Ramsey said. She said a year-long suspension ``can be enacted
at any point.''
   ``School officials have simply said at this point that they will
not have this continue for the year,'' Ms. Ramsey said.
   Strode and his wife, Robin, were notified Friday they had been
banned from school property.
   The Weavers, family friends, were to escort the children from
the gate to the school building, but officials instead ordered the
deputies to take the children.
   After the confrontation between the boy and the principal, Gorst
asked Strode to bring his children into school. Strode said he
refused and walked off with the three children.
   At that point, Gorst asked him to bring the younger children
back, saying only Duffey was suspended, Strode said.
   ``They just don't want Duffey at school, period,'' he said.
``Pepper, she's scared to death now.''
   Duffey and Matthew were preaching on their way to the school
grounds, Strode said. Pepper, who did not preach last year, yelled
``repent'' a couple of times, Strode said. All three had book bags
on their backs and Bibles in their hands, he said.
</TEXT>
