<2ND_LINE>AM-Dynamite Catch,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fisherman Snares Dynamite; Police Think It Was Stolen Last Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fisherman reeling in his hook found
sticks of dynamite instead of a fish, and that led to a search in
which police believe they have recovered dynamite stolen last month
at gunpoint.
   The July 19 theft of 100 pounds of dynamite, along with 200
blasting caps, caused concern, in part, because it took place
during the Democratic National Convention in Atlanta.
   But on Saturday, a man fishing in the Yellow River reeled in a
surprise.
   Newton County Sheriff's Detective Lt. Ezell Brown said Danny
Duffey of Jackson called officers in nearby Butts County and
reported that he had snagged two sticks of dynamite.
   Butts County deputies contacted Newton County deputies, who went
to the scene that night but found no more dynamite. On Sunday, fire
officials from both counties went to the river and eight divers
found more dynamite, Brown said.
   Newton County police think it was the dynamite stolen July 19
from a worker for a Douglasville explosives company who was robbed
by an armed man wearing a ski mask.
   ``We feel that we've done a total recovery of what was stolen
from Henry County,'' Brown said, but he would not disclose how much
dynamite was found.
