<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Reagan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru a0599 08-22 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0599,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Staying Out Of Quayle Flap</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Adds 4 grafs with more on Reagan schedule</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House declined comment
Monday on the controversy surrounding Republican vice presidential
nominee Dan Quayle, saying only that Quayle ``is the vice
presidential candidate and he's a good one.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said he had no comment
on the prediction of Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., that the issue of
Quayle's enlistment in the National Guard during the Vietnam War
``is going to last awhile.''
   Asked whether President Reagan believed Quayle should be dropped
from the ticket, Fitzwater replied, ``It is not a relevant question.
   ``Senator Quayle is the vice presidential candidate and he's a
good one,'' the spokesman said.
   Fitzwater said Reagan has not talked with Vice President George
Bush since making a brief telephone call to him after his
acceptance speech at the Republican National Convention in New
Orleans last Thursday.
   He said the two would have a chance to confer, perhaps for half
an hour or an hour, prior to a joint appearance in Los Angeles on
Wednesday. He did not speculate on what they would talk about.
   Fitzwater said Reagan's principal role in the fall campaign will
be to ``draw distinctions between liberals and conservatives,
between Democrats and Republicans.''
   He said four or five appearances had already been scheduled and
somewhere between eight and 15 are expected. He said the president
would go to the South, the Northeast, the West and ``all around the
country.''
   The president and his wife, Nancy, will leave Tuesday for Los
Angeles and return to their ranch north of here on Saturday,
staying until Sept. 6, when they return to Washington.
   On his way to Los Angeles, the president will stop at Long
Beach, Calif., to sign a bill designed to reduce U.S. deficits in
world trade.
   Asked whether it was politically embarrassing to the president
that the prime sponsor of the bill was Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, the
Democratic vice presidential nominee, Fitzwater said it was not.
   ``Senator Bentsen did a good job with this,'' Fitzwater said.
``He has worked on it a lot of years, and so have we.''
</TEXT>
