<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JudgeThreatened     08-22 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Threatened,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sasson Jeans Creator Surrenders, Ordered Held Without Bail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The creator of the bankrupt Sasson jeans empire
surrendered Monday and was ordered held without bail for violating
an agreement that had freed him while he awaited trial for
allegedly threatening the life of a judge.
   Paul Guez, who gave himself up to federal marshals, had
disappeared last week while free on $100,000 bond, then appeared
without his lawyers before the judge he is accused of threatening.
   Guez appeared before U.S. District Judge Michael B. Mukasey, who
rejected the defendant's argument that he misunderstood the
arrangement that allowed him to come to New York from California
last week to attend to bankruptcy proceedings.
   ``I find your account of how confused you were unconvincing,''
Mukasey said. The restrictions were ``reasonable and perfectly
obvious. They would have been obvious to a child.''
   Mukasey had revoked Guez's bail and issued a warrant for his
arrest Friday after the government said Guez violated the
conditions of his release after his arrest in May for threatening
the life of U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland.
   After his release, Guez was sent to California, where he spent
28 days in a drug rehabilitation center. Since getting out he has
been staying with relatives in the Los Angeles area.
   Early last week, Guez came to New York on the condition that he
remain in the custody of one of his two lawyers. But the lawyers
lost track of him Wednesday and Guez appeared before Lifland on
Thursday without the lawyers.
   Lifland notified Assistant U.S. Attorney Gilbert Childers.
   Guez's lawyer, Gerald J. McMahon, argued Monday that his client
did not ``willfully violate the terms of his bail,'' and had
remained in close contact with another lawyer, Guillermo A. Gleizer.
   According to federal prosecutors, Guez, 43, threatened to kill
Lifland and the trustee he appointed to oversee Sasson's
reorganization ``if a result contrary to his interest were to be
reached.''
   The Tunisian-born Guez arrived in the United States in 1976 with
$74 and a new style of French cut jeans. Through clever advertising
he made millions, also licensing the Sasson label for watches,
lingerie and luggage.
   But the company, beset by to internal feuds, was swamped by
lawsuits leading to the Chapter 11 reorganization.
