<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraSupplies     08-22 0628</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Supplies,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Six Accused Of Training Contra Mercenaries in Florida</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Cuban-Americans ran a mercenary training camp
in Florida to aid Nicaraguan rebels, according to a federal
indictment unsealed Monday.
   One of the six is also accused of shipping a cannon, a mortar
and other weapons to Contras under the guise of humanitarian aid.
   The Miami-area men allegedly violated the Neutrality Act, which
bans private action against a government at peace with the United
States. The indictment alleges that the defendants operated from
June 1983 to September 1986.
   ``There is no declared war against Nicaragua,'' Assistant U.S.
Attorney Mark Schnapp said. ``People don't have the option to go
down there and engage in combat on their own.''
   Eulalio Francisco ``Frank'' Castro, 46, one the two men who
allegedly financed the 60-man training camp on the outskirts of
Naples, had been arrested here in June 1983 for allegedly smuggling
loads of marijuana by sea, U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration
spokesman Jack Hook said Monday.
   The mercenary camp allegedly began operations the same month,
and the charges against Castro were subsequently dismissed. Hook
said he did not know why the charges were dropped.
   Schnapp turned away questions about a possible drug link to the
Contra aid operations, which has been the subject of congressional
investigations.
   ``There is no allegation of any drug shipment involved in any of
this,'' Schnapp said.
   Also indicted was Rene Corvo, who has been accused by some
witnesses before congressional committees of engaging in drug
traffic. A 1986 U.S. State Department report said there was no
information connecting Corvo's group in Miami to drug smuggling.
   Corvo, Castro, Joseph Marcos and Sergio Becerra turned
themselves in Monday before U.S. Magistrate Lurana Snow in Fort
Lauderdale, while agents were trying to contact the other two
defendants, Rafael Torres Jimenez and Francisco Hernandez.
   Corvo faces the most serious charges in the indictment, which
was prepared by the same federal grand jury that indicted Contra
leader Adolfo Calero's brother Mario Calero, ex-mercenary Jack
Terrell and others on similar charges.
   Corvo faces a maximum 38 years in prison on four weapons charges
plus counts of violating the Neutrality Act and conspiring to
violate it. The other five face only the Neutrality Act violations,
and face a maximum eight years in prison.
   In March 1985 Corvo allegedly shipped nine weapons to Costa
Rican anti-Sandinista groups through Fort Lauderdale and El
Salvador, and faces federal weapons counts, Schnapp said.
   One shipment allegedly landed on the ranch of John Hull, a
one-time CIA contact, according to congressional witnesses and
other reports.
   Schnapp said questions about Hull, if any, would be forwarded to
the special prosecutor's office in Washington.
   ``There was a portion of the overall investigation of
individuals who were facilitating Contra activities that was turned
over to the special prosecutor's office,'' Schnapp said.
   Castro and Marcos are accused of financing the camp's
operations, while Corvo and the other three allegedly trained
mercenaries, mostly Cubans and Nicaraguans, at the camp. The
activities were apparently not secret, and the camp was filmed in
1985 by a television crew, Schnapp said.
   Some of the defendants in the earlier case have argued their
activities were sanctioned and even directed by the Reagan
administration. They have a motion before Roettger asking him to
decide if the United States was really at peace with the
Sandinistas, as is required under the act.
   Schnapp said the new indictment did not include any evidence
that the men were acting on behalf of the Reagan administration.
``The indictment would indicate that they were not sanctioned,''
said Schnapp.
   Joe Adams, who pleaded guilty to Neutrality Act violations in
the earlier indictment, was sentenced to one day's probation by
U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger.
</TEXT>
