<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   08-22 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>13 Arabs Wounded, Abu Nidal Claims Responsibility for Grenade
Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and wounded 13 Arabs Monday
during a strike called to protest Israeli tax raids. The
Palestinian guerrilla group led by Abu Nidal claimed responsibility
for a bombing in the city of Haifa that injured 25 people.
   A Palestinian also died of wounds suffered in a clash with
troops a day earlier, bringing to 252 the Arab death toll in the
eight-month rebellion in Israeli-occupied territories. Four
Israelis have died.
   The worst violence erupted in the coastal Gaza Strip, where
troops opened fire to disperse hundreds of stone-throwing
protesters at the Shati and Jabaliya refugee camps, Arab hospital
officials said.
   Eleven Palestinians ranging in age from 11 to 21 were shot and
wounded in the clashes, the hospital officials said. Two suffered
serious injuries and were transferred to an Israeli hospital.
   Two protesters were also shot and wounded in the West Bank, one
in the town of Nur el Shams and one in the town of Zawiyeh.
   The army imposed a curfew on Nablus, the West Bank's largest
city, and surrounding refugee camps following violent protests
overnight.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, meanwhile, condemned as an
``outrageous terrorist act'' the grenade attack Saturday night on a
crowded pedestrian mall in Haifa.
   Twenty-five people were wounded in the bombing, including an
8-year-old boy who lost his left leg below the knee. Four
Palestinians from the West Bank city of Jenin are being held in
connection with the attack.
   In a statement published Monday in the Beirut newspaper
An-Nahar, Abu Nidal's Fatah-Revolutionary Council claimed
responsibility for the attack, saying it was in revenge for the
April 16 assassination of PLO military commander Khalil Wazir, also
known as Abu Jihad.
   Israeli officials have acknowledged privately that Israel
carried out the assassination.
   Shamir, head of the right-wing Likud bloc, told Israel army
radio the Haifa attack ``shows again that this struggle (the
uprising) ... is not for certain territories under Israeli rule,
but against the security and existence of Israel.''
   But Shamir's political rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of
the left-of-center Labor Party, said the attack was not linked to
the uprising. ``I think this has nothing to do with the intefadeh
(Arabic for uprising),'' Peres told army radio.
   Palestinian activists denied Shamir's claim that the goal of the
uprisng was to eliminate Israel.
   ``The purpose of the intefadeh is not to destroy Israel or the
Israeli people, but to establish a Palestinian state and end the
occupation,'' read leaflets distributed Monday in the West Bank.
   The leaflets, written in Hebrew and Arabic, also called on
Israeli soldiers to refuse service in the occupied lands.
   In Gaza, wall posters appeared overnight expressing Arab
defiance of harsh Israeli measures against firebomb throwers,
including house demolitions and deportations.
   ``We're not afraid. Our young will continue to throw
firebombs,'' said the posters, which showed youths hurling stones
and bottles at Israeli jeeps.
   Streets were deserted and stores shuttered in the occupied lands
Monday, the second day of a strike called by undergropund leaders
to protest raids in which Israelis confiscate property of Arabs
refusing to pay taxes.
   Tax boycotts have been a key source of resistance to Israeli
rule during the uprising.
   A court extended the detention of two Israeli Jews suspected of
setting fire to a shack near Tel Aviv, killing three Palestinians.
A fistfight broke out outside the courthouse when the suspects
scuffled with a television cameraman, breaking his camera, Israel
radio said.
   Ahmad Sharnobi, 22, of the Askar refugee camp near Nablus died
Monday of a bullet wound in the stomach. He was shot Sunday night
by plainclothes Israeli agents.
   The army confirmed the death and said security forces had
entered the camp to try to prevent expected riots during a strike.
</TEXT>
