<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Pakistan     08-22 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan,0403</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caretaker Cabinet Meets As Rumors Continue Of Military Coup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The caretaker cabinet of the late
President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq agreed Monday to continue his
policies, and government officials denied recurring rumors of a
military takeover.
   Ismail Patel of the Ministry of Information said, ``We are
hearing the rumors but there is no basis to them.''
   U.S. Army Gen. Cloyd Pfister led a group of American
investigators to the site of the C-130 airplane crash that killed
Zia, U.S. Ambassador Arnold Raphel and 28 other people on Wednesday.
   American and Pakistani crash experts searched the debris to
determine what caused the transport plane to explode minutes after
takeoff near the Indian border.
   Caretaker President Ghulam Ishaq Khan, the former Senate
chairman who became the new leader by constitutional succession,
says he is convinced the crash was caused by saboteurs.
   Ishaq Khan, 73, held his second Cabinet meeting Monday. Patel
said the Cabinet ``discussed the continuation of Islamization,''
the process set in motion by Zia to make the Moslem Koranic code of
justice the law of the land.
   Although there was no official statement, Patel said the cabinet
decided to continue Zia's policies, including support of the Moslem
insurgents fighting the Soviet-backed government in Afghanistan.
   Several officials and Pakistani newspapers reported hearing
rumors of the imposition of martial law and the arrest of Ishaq
Khan or of Army Chief of Staff Gen. Aslam Baig. Authorities said
nothing was afoot.
   There have been no reports of unrest since Zia's death ended his
11-year rule. Ishaq Khan said a state of emergency was in effect
but said it had not been necessary to invoke martial law or
restrict civil rights.
   The United States has informed the Soviet Union and India in
separate messages sent to Moscow and New Delhi that American
support for Pakistan remains strong in the wake of Zia's death.
   ``The point is we wanted to reassure them that our policy is
unchanged, and that we are going to stand by Pakistan,'' said a
U.S. official who spoke Monday in Washington on condition of
anonymity.
   Pakistan under Zia was the closest U.S. ally in central Asia and
the conduit for the shipment of American and Chinese weapons to
Afghan rebels fighting a guerrilla war against the Afghan
government and Soviet troops.
</TEXT>
