<DOCNO> AP880822-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1616EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burundi-Glance     08-22 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burundi-Glance,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burundi at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Burundi Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts and figures about Burundi:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Burundi covers 10,759 square miles, about the size of
Maryland. It is astride the main Nile-Congo dividing crest, bounded
on the west by the narrow plain of the Ruzizi River and Lake
Tanganyika. The interior is a broken plateau at an average altitude
of about 5,000 feet, sloping eastward to Tanzania and the valley of
the Maragarazi River. Its neighbors are Zaire on the west, Rwanda
on the north and Tanzania on the east.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ Burundi is densely populated with 5 million people,
of whom 84 percent are of the Hutu tribe. Although the Tutsi make
up only 15 percent of the population, they control the army and
government.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY _ Some nickel deposits still are exploited but
Burundi's main economic activity, and the main source of
employment, is subsistence agriculture. Beans, kassava, maize,
peanuts, peas, sorghum and bananas are grown but the main cash crop
is coffee, which accounts for 90 percent of exports. There has been
little industrial development.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY _ Tradition recounts the establishment of a Tutsi
kingdom as early as the 16th century. Germany occupied the country
in 1890 and incorporated it into German East Africa. In 1919 it
became part of Ruanda-Urundi, administsered by Belgium, first as a
League of Nations mandate and then as a U.N. trust territory. It
became independent in 1962 and has had several governments, the
most recent ones military.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
