<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     08-22 0735</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Quayle Pick An Issue; Criticizes Bush On Foreign
Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis on Monday urged
voters to compare his selection of a running mate to George Bush's
choice when weighing their vote for president.
   He also said he was eager to debate his Republican opponent on
foreign policy and national security issues.
   Dukakis has shied away from direct criticism of Bush's selection
of Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle to round out the Republican ticket but
on Monday said it ``obviously will be an issue'' in the election.
   ``How we make our decisions, how we make the presidential
selections, who we select ... whether or not that person should be
a heartbeat away from the presidency, obviously will be an an issue
in the campaign,'' Dukakis told a news conference in Lowell during
a gubernatorial trip to northeastern Massachusetts.
   ``This is a judgment the American people will have to make,''
said Dukakis, who last week touted the credentials of his running
mate, Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, as a way of questioning Bush's
judgment in picking Quayle.
   ``They've had an opportunity now to watch Michael Dukakis make
his selection and Geoge Bush make his decision,'' Dukakis said.
``And they will judge us on this and other issues.''
   Dukakis criticized Bush for not yet agreeing to a debate
schedule and asked that the first face-to-face confrontation be
devoted to national security and foreign policy. Bush has
frequently criticized Dukakis as a novice at national security and
foreign policy and did so again Monday.
   ``How someone who sat there and did nothing while we sold arms
to the ayatollah can seriously talk about leadership in the Persian
Gulf is beyond me,'' Dukakis said.
   The governor filled his visit with references to his higher
ambitions, touting state health insurance, economic development and
housing programs as models he would promote nationally if elected
president.
   Dukakis was returning to his Brookline home tonight for a
briefing on national security issues to be led by William Webster,
director of the Central Intelligence Agency. Bentsen also was to
attend the briefing, one of a series the presidential and vice
presidential nominees will receive before the election. Rep. Louis
Stokes, chairman of the House Intelligence Committee,, and Rep. Lee
Hamilton, its former chairman, also were invited.
   Bentsen and his wife, Beryl Ann, were to have dinner with the
Dukakises prior to the briefing. Dukakis aides said the governor's
home would be checked for electronic surveillance devices prior to
the session.
   Dukakis also issued a statement supporting demonstrations in
Poland in favor of the outlawed Solidarity trade union, referring
to Solidarity leader Lech Walesa as the `true leader of the Polish
people.''
   The visit by Dukakis to northeastern Massachusetts, which he
will resume Tuesday, is part of his annual summer tradition of
visiting different regions of the state.
   As he did with a trip last week to central Massachusetts,
Dukakis began the visit at a luncheon with area officials,
educators and business and labor leaders before attending state
events that mesh with themes of his presidential campaign.
   In Lowell, a once-thriving mill city that fell on extremely hard
times in the 1970s, Dukakis announced the construction plans for a
new downtown community college at a mill complex destroyed by fire
two years ago and a $150,000 grant for a manufacturing research
center to provide technical assistance to smaller manufacturing
operations.
   The city has made a dramatic economic comeback and its former
mills have been refurbished for a variety of business, housing and
other projects. Dukakis frequently refers to Lowell and nearby
Lawrence, a city on his Tuesday agenda, as examples of how he has
encouraged economic development in struggling areas.
   ``We can do for this country ... what we have done here,''
Dukakis told the luncheon, recalling his visist last week to
struggling rural areas of Illinois, Missouri and Arkansas. ``They
too want to have to have the same hope and optimism, the same
vision of what's ahead, that you have created in Lowell,'' Dukakis
said.
   Former U.S. Sen. Paul Tsongas told the gathering he hoped a
visit to Lowell by reporters covering the presidential campaign
would put to rest Republican charges that Dukakis overstates his
role in the area's resurgence.
   ``We were getting irritated by those who say that Michael
Dukakis had nothing to do with the `Massachusetts Mircale,'''
Tsongas said.
</TEXT>
