<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Rowan-Shooting     08-22 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rowan-Shooting,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Columnist Probably Told He Needn't Register Gun, Memo Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syndicated columnist Carl T. Rowan probably
had been told he did not have to register a revolver he used to
shoot a teen-ager trespassing in his yard, the city government's
top lawyer says.
   However, city officials on Monday refused to drop charges
against Rowan, who has written in favor of gun control. He was
charged with possession of an unregistered handgun and ammunition
after wounding a youth who had been taking an unauthorized predawn
swim in his backyard swimming pool June 14.
   Rowan has claimed that the weapon was given to him in 1982 by
his son, Carl Jr., a former FBI agent. Both Rowans have steadfastly
maintained that city officials instructed them that the gun did not
have to be registered, since Rowan Jr. was a federal agent.
   That was buttressed by a memo written Aug. 11 from District of
Columbia Corporation Counsel Frederick D. Cooke Jr. to Police Chief
Maurice T. Turner, indicating that some police officers have erred
in enforcing the gun registration law.
   ``It has come to my attention that some officers in the MPD
(Metropolitan Police Department) have interpreted the provision so
as to exempt from registration firearms owned by MPD officers or
other law enforcement officers,'' Cooke wrote Turner in the memo,
obtained by The Associated Press on Monday.
   ``I understand further that when an officer ceases to be an MPD
or other law enforcement officer this `exempt' status is not
revoked and the former officer is not required to surrender the
weapon.''
   The city's far-reaching 1976 handgun ordinance, which requires
that all weapons purchased after that date be registered with the
city, should be amended to make clear that law enforcement officers
are not exempt from this regulation, Cooke concluded.
   ``Police were telling people that once they left any police
force, they didn't have to register the weapon,'' said Raoul L.
Carroll, Rowan's attorney. ``The memo makes that clear.''
   The document was included in material Carroll submitted to
District of Columbia Superior Court in hopes of getting the charges
dismissed.
   Beverly Burke, a spokeswoman for Cooke, said city officials
still intend to prosecute the columnist. She would not comment on
the memo, which she described as ``private, not something that
should be in the public domain.'' Police also declined to comment.
   Efforts to reach Rowan for comment were not immediately
successsful.
   Rowan's trial has been set for Sept. 22. If convicted of
possessing an unregistered weapon and ammunition, he could receive
up to one year in jail and a $1,000 fine on each count.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
