<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PLO     08-22 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Executive Committee Meets, Still No Date For Council Session</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUNIS, Tunisia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Executive Committee of the Palestine
Liberation Organization on Monday wrapped up three days of meetings
without setting a date for a Palestine National Council session
expected next month in Algiers.
   A Palestinian source authorized to convey results of the
closed-door meeting said members discussed the ramifications of
King Hussein's decision in July to cut Jordan's links with the
Israeli-occupied West Bank.
   A senior PLO offcial, meanwhile, said Monday he expects the PLO
to proclaim an independent Palestinian state before the end of the
year.
   Salah Khalaf, also known as Abu Iyad, a close associate and
deputy to PLO chief Yasser Arafat, told Austrian radio that the
executive committee was reviewing proposals on the issue by various
political and judicial commissions.
   In the interview, monitored in Vienna, Khalaf said the issue
would be on the agenda of the PNC session in Algiers.
   ``Proclamation of a Palestinian government, a state will
certainly come this year,'' Khalaf said.
   Khalaf made clear that the PLO wants recognition from Israel
before the Palestinians would officially recognize the Jewish
state. He said it was the Israelis who are refusing dialogue with
the PLO.
   ``We are not prepared to give something away prematurely,'' he
said, but added that ``we are realists. Israel is there. It exists
as far as the political reality is concerned.''
   Israel refuses to deal with the PLO, which it views as a
terrorist group. Israeli leaders have denounced any attempt to set
up an independent Palestinian state.
   Khalaf was in Vienna for a day of talks with Foreign Minister
Alois Mock and Interior Minister Karl Blecha.
   The 450-member Palestine National Council, a sort of Palestinian
parliament-in-exile, is widely expected to consider setting up a
Palestinian government with a claim to the West Bank and the Gaza
Strip, captured by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Palestinian sources in Algiers have said they expect the council
to convene late next month.
   The executive committee is expected to meet again later this
week, after Arafat returns from Baghdad, Iraq.
</TEXT>
