<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1656EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CyprusTalks     08-22 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyprus Talks,0544</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek,Turkish Cypriot Leaders To Hold Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leaders of the Greek and Turkish communities
in Cyprus said Monday they will strive to achieve a settlement that
would lead to the withdrawal of Turkish troops from their
war-divided island.
   President George Vassiliou, the Greek Cypriot leader, and Rauf
Denktash, the president of the breakaway Turkish Cypriot state,
arrived Monday at the invitation of U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar.
   At a meeting Wednesday, they are expected to discuss differences
that have fueled tensions on the island since Turkey invaded north
Cyprus in 1974 in the wake of a coup by supporters of union with
Greece. It is the first time leaders of the divided nation have met
in nearly three years.
   ``The Cyprus problem has lasted too long, 14 years of continuous
occupation of a large part of our small island is too much, and it
is high time it was settled,'' Vassiliou told reporters. ``The
withrawal of the Turkish troops is the key problem.''
   ``I want a settlement very badly,'' Denktash told reporters
earlier.
   Denktash is president of the Turkish-Cypriot Federated State of
North Cyprus, established in 1983 and recognized only by Turkey.
   He said the estimated 35,000 Turkish troops would begin
withdrawing from Cyprus only ``after the formation of a
transitional government and after the Turkish Cypriot community
begins feeling it does not need the guarantee of their continuing
presence for its safety.''
   The main obstacles to a settlement have been Greek Cypriot
demands for the withdrawal of the Turkish troops and 45,000 Turks
who have settled in north Cyprus, as well as the repatriation of
200,000 Greek Cypriot refugees, one third of the island's
population.
   ``I am going into these negotiations with cautious optimism ...
I know it is not easy to find a solution and it is going to be a
long process,'' Vassiliou said.
   After the meeting Wednesday between the two leaders in the
presence of Perez de Cuellar, the talks will move to Nicosia,
Denktash said.
   Vassiliou, a businessman, entered politics for the first time in
February, when he was elected president. He has declared his
intention to settle the Cyprus problem within a year of his
election.
   By contrast, Denktash became a prominent Turkish Cypriot leader
before the island gained its independence from British colonial
rule in 1960. He has engaged in fruitless negotiations with other
Greek Cypriot leaders since tensions began in the 1960s.
   ``This new leader, Mr. Vassiliou, we are told, intends to
establish a partnership through a bi-zonal federation with us and
he has created a good reputation as a man of good intentions who
really wants a settlement, that's why we are here,'' Denktash said.
   Vassiliou told reporters:
   ``It would be nice if the Turkish troops could be withdrawn in a
day, but that is impractical. What is important is for the troops
to be withdrawn and that we arrive at an agreed solution.''
   Perez de Cuellar, who arrived Monday night, said he hoped the
talks with the two leaders will produce a date for the resumption
of the intercommunal talks ``and a climate of dialogue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LastTemptation     08-22 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Last Temptation,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Greek Orthodox Church Calls for Film to be Banned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Greek Orthodox Church said Monday it
has called for a ban on the film ``The Last Temptation of Christ''
in Greece, claiming its interpretation of the life of Jesus is
``horrifyingly vulgar.''
   Archbishop Seraphim of Athens, the Orthodox Church leader in
Greece, sent a letter to the government saying Martin Scorsese's
film would ``clash directly with the religious sensitivities of our
people.''
   ``The film attempts a horrifyingly vulgar representation of the
person of the founder of the Christian faith,'' the letter said.
   In his appeal, Seraphim cited the Greek Constitution, which
enshrines Orthodox Christianity as the country's official religion.
   Church spokesman Yiannis Hadzifoti said the letter was sent to
Education Minister George Papandreou and Minister to the Premier's
Office Akis Tsochatzopoulos ``just a few days ago,'' but so far
there had been no official response.
   In the movie's most controversial scene, the crucified Jesus
imagines making love to Mary Magdalene. Scorsese has said it
shouldn't offend audiences when taken ``in context'' as Christ's
last temptation _ to get married and lead a normal human life.
   Scorsese's film is based on a novel by Greek author Nikos
Kazantzakis, who was threatened with excommunication by the
Orthodox Church when the book came out in 1954. ``The Last
Temptation'' is one of Kazantzakis' most popular books and it is
still a big seller in Greece.
   The film is expected to be released in Greece next month ``a
couple of weeks after it's shown at the Venice Festival'' according
to a spokesman for United International Pictures, the distributor.
   It has provoked accusations by religious traditionalists that it
distorts Christian theology. Thousands of people demonstrated when
it was released two weeks ago in the United States, where it was
seen by packed houses in several cities.
   In Europe, both Protestant and Roman Catholic church groups have
denounced the film. In Britain, a conservative watchdog group is
seeking a ban on grounds of blasphemy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
