<DOCNO> AP880822-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1726EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WheatOutlook     08-22 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wheat Outlook,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Supply May Recover In 1989</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If farmers boost plantings and the drought
eases, this year's massive drain on the U.S. wheat stockpile could
be brought under control in 1989, the Agriculture Department said
Monday.
   Total wheat supplies in the 1988-89 marketing year that began on
June 1 are estimated at about 3.1 billion bushels, down more than
20 percent from last season and the lowest in almost a decade, the
department's Economic Research Service said in an outlook report.
   More than 22 million acres of wheat land were idled under the
USDA's acreage program this year when farmers were required to
set-aside 27.5 percent of their base acres. For 1989, they have to
idle only 10 percent.
   ``With increased area and average yields in 1989-90, the United
States would be able to produce 2.5 billion bushels of wheat,
enough to cover likely use without a further stock decline,'' the
report said.
   Although the supply _ this year's harvest plus excess left over
from previous crops _ will be more than enough to meet expected
use, the wheat inventory by next June 1 is expected to be down to
around 597 million bushels, down from 1.266 billion bushels this
June 1.
   Based on the current rate of wheat use for domestic consumption
and exports, the U.S. wheat supply next June 1 would represent an
87-day supply, compared with reserves for 185 days this June 1. It
also would be the smallest since 1973-74.
   This year's wheat harvest of 1.82 billion bushels is far short
of the more than 2.5 billion bushels needed to cover expected
domestic and export demands in 1988-89. The shortfall of 684
million bushels has to come out of reserves.
   Thus, according to the report, the beginning inventory of 1.266
billion bushels is drawn down by the shortfall to 582 million
bushels. When imports of 15 million bushels are added, the
projected U.S. wheat stockpile next June 1 becomes 597 million
bushels.
</TEXT>
