<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1836EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Vincennes-Research     08-22 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vincennes-Research,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Seeking Money For Airplane `Recognition' System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon has asked Congress to restore
government financing for research on advanced airplane
``recognition'' systems of a type that might have prevented the
shootdown of an Iranian airliner by a Navy cruiser.
   Such systems, if proven feasible, could make it easier for radar
centers on the ground or at sea to identify the types of planes
they detect _ for example, distinguishing between a jet fighter and
a cargo plane.
   The funding request was presented formally by Gordon A. Smith,
the assistant defense secretary for command, control,
communications and intelligence systems, just two weeks after the
USS Vincennes on July 3 shot down an Iranian A-300 Airbus carrying
290 people that the cruiser mistook for a F-14 fighter jet.
   In a letter to the House and Senate Appropriations committees,
Smith urged Congress to restore $9.2 million for research and
development of so-called ``non-cooperative target-recognition
systems.''
   Congress had cut the money from the Navy's fiscal 1989 budget
bill after discovering the Navy and Pentagon were not prepared to
commit themselves to continuing the research in fiscal 1990 and
beyond.
   The Navy says it made a decision to scrap a five-year research
program in the field because of the overall Pentagon budget squeeze.
   ``It is requested that consideration be given to a floor
amendment to restore the requested $9.2 million in Navy funding for
non-cooperative identification efforts,'' Smith wrote on July 18.
   Smith made no reference to the Vincennes incident, but added:
``The Department of Defense is striving to develop aircraft
identification systems to provide effective control of our
increasingly lethal air defense weapons. This is not an easy
problem; however, there is a non-cooperative identification
technique which has the potential to identify hostile and civil
aircraft.''
   Non-cooperative identification is military slang for any system
that doesn't rely on aircraft radio emissions to make an
identification. So-called cooperative systems, now in use by most
air forces, involve one plane determining whether another is
friendly by ``asking'' for a special radio transmission.
   The Vincennes, in mistakenly classifying the Iranian airliner as
a hostile jet fighter, apparently made a mistake in the way it
interpreted that plane's radio signal response.
   A non-cooperative system attempts to identify an airplane
without asking for a radio transmission.
   Smith, in his letter, did not include any details of the Navy
research because he said the work was classified. But he did say a
new non-cooperative system ``has been tested on one ship with very
good results.''
   The Senate already has responded to Smith's plea by agreeing to
provide the research money. The House has yet to act, however, and
the prospects for restoring the money still are uncertain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0142 </DOCNO>
