<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0615 08-22 0710</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Accuses Iran Of Moving Troops In Violation Of Cease-fire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD 4 grafs UPDATING with U.N. chief's comments in Geneva.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq on Monday accused Iran of redeploying
its troops along the central border region in violation of the
3-day-old cease-fire in the Persian Gulf.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said Iranian troops on Saturday
and Sunday moved closer to Iraqi positions on the central front as
well as moving troops to other, unspecified ``new areas.''
   The dispatch said Iraq complained to United Nations observers in
the area, warning that unless the Iranians pulled back, Iraq would
``forcibly return them'' to their previous positions.
   ``The U.N. team intervened and asked the Iranian side to
withdraw, and the Iranian troops actually started withdrawal'' late
Monday, the dispatch said.
   The state-run agency did not identify the area beyond saying it
was on the central front, and gave no further details in its
three-sentence dispatch.
   There was no immediate response to the Iraqi claim from Iran or
from the peacekeeping force.
   At the United Nations, a U.N. official refused to discuss the
alleged cease-fire violations but said U.N. truce observers were
defusing tensions successfully on the front line.
   Spokeswoman Nadia Younes also declined comment on reports from
shipping sources in the Persian Gulf that U.N. patrol boats had
been seen cruising the Strait of Hormuz in the southern gulf and
the Shatt al-Arab waterway separating Iran and Iraq.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar's report to the
Security Council calling for the establishment of the U.N.
Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group requested a naval patrol for
``certain sensitive areas in or near the Shatt al-Arab.''
   Ms. Younes declined to discuss whether the Strait of Hormuz, 525
miles southeast of the Shatt al-Arab at the opposite end of the
Persian Gulf, could be considered ``near'' that waterway.
   Both areas have been flashpoints in the nearly 8-year-old war.
The conflict broke out in the Shatt al-Arab in September 1980 when
Iraq invaded Iran.
   In Manama, Bahrain, a Kuwait-flagged cargo vessel, one of 93
vessels trapped in Iraqi waters since the war began, became the
first to reach its homeport Monday after the cease-fire.
   The owners, the Kuwait-based United Arab Shipping Co., said the
Ibn Haithem reached the Kuwaiti port of Shuweikh.
   According to Lloyd's Register of Ships, there were nine vessels
trapped at Khor Zubair, nine at the adjacent Umm Al-Qasr water
inlet, and 75 in the Shatt Al-Arab estuary separating Iraq and Iran.
   Iran-Iraq peace talks being overseen by the United Nations are
set to begin Thursday in Geneva, following a cease-fire that was
implemented Saturday as a first step in ending a conflict that has
claimed about 1 million lives.
   Iran and Iraq began observing the cease-fire Saturday morning,
but have not given up swapping accusations and counter-charges.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said an Iranian sniper killed an
Iraqi soldier Saturday, and Iran claimed Iraqi troops fired shots
near a U.N. observer team in the central region of the war front on
Saturday.
   The U.N. secretary-general's office in New York released a
letter from Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz on Monday stating
that if the Iranian Navy attempts to search Iraqi ships for war
material, Iraq ``will resist it by such means as it deems
appropriate.''
   Aziz said such searches would violate the cease-fire provisions
of U.N. Security Council Resolution 598, which called for the
cease-fire, troop withdrawal, exchange of prisoners, peace talks
and establishment of an impartial commission to decide who was
responsible for the conflict.
   Perez de Cuellar told an airport news conference in Geneva on
Monday that a peace settlement will require long and tedious talks,
but ``if there is a political will the rhythm could be quite
rapid.''
   He said he may later name a deputy to lead the negotiations.
Asked when he expected a comprehensive settlement, he said this was
a ``$100,000 question.''
   The U.N. chief said a major question in the talks' initial phase
was repatriating the ``more than 80,000'' prisoners of war.
   He said he expects ``great cooperation from both sides'' on the
POW issue, and that he was pleased with the cooperation U.N.
military observers received from Iran and Iraq in monitoring the
cease-fire.
</TEXT>
