<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Cattle-Electricity     08-22 0132</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cattle-Electricity,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beef Won't Sizzle Beneath Power Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-year study demonstrates that cattle
can graze safely under high-voltage power lines, the Agriculture
Department said Monday.
   David C. Ganskopp, a rangeland scientist for the department's
Agricultural Research Service in Burns, Ore., said the $1.7 million
field study in Oregon showed that ``farmers do not have to make
allowances for cattle if high-voltage lines are overhead.''
   The study was paid for by the Bonneville Power Administration in
the Pacific Northwest and nine other U.S. and Canadian power
companies. The 500,000-volt power line used in the study stretches
900 miles from Bonneville Dam in Oregon to the Los Angeles area.
   ``We found no significant differences in the body weights of
cattle or in the number of calves born,'' Ganskopp said.
</TEXT>
