<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola     08-22 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-Fire Treaty Signed</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   RUACANA, South-West Africa (AP) _ Military representatives from
South Africa, Cuba and Angola signed a treaty Monday formally
ending hostilities in southern Angola.
   A cease-fire went into effect on Aug. 10, but the treaty
formally declared an end to the fighting and provided for a joint
military monitoring committee to be formed.
   The accord was concluded after three days of meetings near
Ruacana, a town in South-West Africa about 200 yards from the
Angolan border,
   According to the South African Press Association, the treaty, in
English, Spanish and Portuguese, was signed by Lt. Gen. Leopoldo
Cintras Frias of Cuba, commander of Cuban and Angolan troops; Col.
Antonio Jose Maria, the Angolan presidential secretary for defense
and security; and Maj. Gen. Willie Meyer, commanding officer of the
South-West African Territorial Force.
   The accord is part of an overall agreement among the three
nations calling for South African troops to withdraw from Angola by
Sept. 1; for independence to begin for the South African-controlled
territory of South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, by Nov. 1,
and for withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from Angola.
   UNITA, the guerrilla group supported by South Africa and the
United States, is not part of the negotiations. UNITA _ or National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola _ has vowed to keep
fighting the Marxist Angolan government until it agrees to
negotiate.
   The South-West African People's Organization, or SWAPO, which
has been fighting for more than two decades to end South African
rule over South-West Africa, reportedly said it would abide by the
cease-fire if South Africa did the same. The report came from the
Zimbabwean news agency, Ziana, which quoted SWAPO information
officer Charles Mubita.
   The South African Defense Force said Monday that a 19-year-old
soldier died Friday ``in action against terrorists in the
operational area when the vehicle in which he was traveling was
struck by an RPG-7 rocket.'' It gave no details.
</TEXT>
