<HEAD>Judge Allows Guerrillas to Testify Fromn Abroad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing will be held in London
so six members of the African National Congress can testify for
colleagues being tried in South Africa on treason and terrorism
charges, a judge ruled Monday.
   Judge H.R. Daniels granted a defense request that a commission
be named to hear evidence abroad from members of the outlawed
guerrilla group fighting white domination in South Africa. The
hearing is expected next month.
   Defense lawyers contended active ANC members, who could not come
to South Africa for fear of arrest, were the only people in a
position to rebut evidence from state witnesses.
   One of the three defendants is Ebrahim Ebrahim, described by the
government as the highest-ranking ANC commander captured in the
past 20 years.
   Daniels said Johan Herhold, a partner in the London law firm of
Shepstone and Wilie, would take evidence at the special hearing and
that cross-examination of the six ANC members would be allowed.
   The ANC has fought a bombing and sabotage campaign since 1961.
Its exile headquarters are in Lusaka, Zambia, and the ANC's London
office is one of its largest.
