<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Workers     08-22 0492</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Workers,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Figures Show Sharp Drop in Number of Palestinian
Workers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   JERUSALEM _ The number of Palestinians traveling to jobs in
Israel from the occupied lands has declined by nearly 20 percent in
the 8-month-old uprising, and workers say fear of attack by Jewish
extremists is a major reason.
   The loss of manpower has caused serious problems in construction
and agriculture, which are dependent on cheap Arab labor.
   Only about 85,000 of the 105,000 Palestinians who worked in
Israel before the rebellion began last Dec. 8 still hold those
jobs, said Arie Pikel, the Labor and Welfare Ministry spokesman.
   He said most Arabs who had stopped working in Israel were
unskilled day-laborers who were not registered with authorities and
received no social benefits.
   Israeli employers want to replace the Palestinians with imported
labor. The initial response was negative, but Labor and Welfare
Minister Moshe Katzav has begun approving such requests.
   Many Palestinians quit their jobs because of pressure from
leaders of the uprising and gangs of masked youths who enforce the
leadership orders. Buses taking Palestinian workers to Israel are
stoned and workers who defy orders to strike are threatened.
   Recently, increasing anti-Palestinian violence inside Israel has
added a new dimension to the problem.
   Last Saturday, a Palestinian guarding a construction site in
downtown Tel Aviv told police a gang of seven Israelis beat him
unconscious.
   A shack was set on fire on a construction site in Tel Aviv's Or
Yehuda suburb two weeks ago, killing three sleeping workers from
the Gaza Strip.
   The attack inspired riots in the Gaza Strip and the army imposed
a three-day curfew.
   Police arrested two Israeli suspects and said Monday
investigators found the fire to be criminal and not related to the
Arab-Israeli political conflict.
   Many Palestinians say the increasing tensions keep them closer
to home.
   Fadel Mohammed Qik, 21, of the Arub refugee camp near Bethlehem,
opened a photography studio after leaving a job as a watchman in
Israel that paid the equivalent of $360 a month.
   ``Even if I make only $180 a month, it's better to work in the
refugee camp than in Israel,'' Qik said.
   Qik's 50-year-old father, Mohammed, and his brothers, Zakariyeh,
17, and Nabil, 16, also have stopped working in Israel and are
unemployed. According to residents, about half the 2,000
Palestinians from Arub once employed in Israel no longer work there.
   Some raise chickens to survive the hard times, and a few
operations have become commercial with up to 1,500 fowl.
   Abdel Fatah Khamis, 22, said he used to sleep in Tel Aviv rather
than make the 35-mile trip home to Arub, but has gone home each
night since the Or Yehuda fire.
   Parliament member Amnon Linn, an Arab affairs expert in the
Labor Party, said Jewish violence against Arabs was not widespread.
He called it the work of ``marginal groups on on the fringes of
Israeli society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
