<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1914EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DroughtInsurance     08-22 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Insurance,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chubb Mobilizes Forces To Deal With Drought Insurance Criticism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chubb Corp. wants to make sure this
summer's drought doesn't claim another victim along with parched
crops: the company's reputation.
   Stung by criticism that it backed away from drought insurance
and left thousands of farmers high and doubly dry, the Warren-based
company has set up a crisis center, mobilized phone-answering
troops for toll-free numbers and taken out newspaper ads.
   ``They're meeting this like meeting a (natural) catastrophe _
you set up a crisis center,'' said Gloria Vogel, who follows the
company for the investment bank Bear, Stearns & Co.
   ``I think the company has done the best they can,'' she said
Monday.
   Chubb has said applications for the insurance far exceeded the
original $30 million in coverage it had authorized. In response to
the demand, the company later increased the authorized amount to
$40 million.
   Chubb has paid about $20 million to farmers who applied for the
coverage before the June 15 deadline but after the coverage limit
had been reached. Chubb is the nation's 16th largest property and
casualty insurer, with a net worth of $2.1 billion as of June 30.
   Management appointed a senior underwriting officer, Terry
Vangilder, to handle the company's response to the complaints, said
spokeswoman Mary Lou Korkuch, who said she has spent a
``substantial amount of time on this question'' in the past two
months.
   The efforts are aimed at repairing ``the damage that may have
been done to our reputation and really get back on track,'' she
said.
   But to Davenport, Iowa, attorney Terry M. Giebelstein, who has
sued Chubb on behalf of 2,000 Iowa farmers, the campaign ``doesn't
address the fundamental issues: The entitlement of the farmers to
the policies.''
   Chubb says that despite its authorization for only $30 million
in insurance, agents offered an estimated $400 million to nearly
9,000 farmers in Ohio, Minnesota, Indiana, Iowa, Illinois,
Kentucky, Michigan, Missouri, Tennessee and Wisconsin.
   The policies specify that Chubb had to approve the applications
before they were accepted, the company said. Only 1,160 were
approved, said Ms. Korkuch.
   Farmers across the Midwest have sued, and a federal judge in
Cincinnati recently granted class-action status to one suit. The
others probaby will be consolidated there, said Giebelstein. State
insurance regulators also are examining the company.
   But all may be sound and fury signifying nothing, depending on
the weather.
   Because the policies are pinned strictly to the cumulative
amount of rain for a given area from June to Aug. 31, rain before
the deadline could render the matter moot.
   Already enough rain has fallen recently to relieve the company
of its obligation for about half the $40 million in coverage
already granted, said Gail Devlin, Chubb's senior vice president
for finance.
   ``We'll just have to wait until Aug. 31 and see how it shakes
out,'' Giebelstein said when asked whether he would continue the
legal action despite the rain. ``If it rains enough, it's hard to
complain.''
</TEXT>
