<2ND_LINE>AM-Albania,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Albanian Leader Condemns Yugoslav Policies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albanian leader Ramiz Alia said in a
speech reported Monday that Yugoslavia is producing ``sinister
propaganda'' in an attempt to blame its ethnic discord on Albania.
   In a speech Sunday to a rally in Peshkopia near the Yugoslav
border, Alia denounced criticism of ethnic Albanians who live in
the adjacent Yugoslav province of Kosovo, the official Albanian
news agency ATA said Monday. Ethnic Albanians make up nearly 90
percent of Kosovo's population.
   Alia said the alleged Yugoslav campaign has ``taken aim even at
those few rights'' recognized in the Yugoslav constitution.
   ``The difficult problems Yugoslavia is undergoing now are not
solved and cannot be solved at the expense of the Albanians,'' Alia
said.
   Serbs and Montenegrins in Kosovo claim they are harassed by
ethnic Albanians. At least 30,000 held a rally Saturday in
Titograd, in Montenegro near the Albanian border, to protest such
harassment.
   More than 30,000 people have left Kosovo since bloody riots in
1981, when some ethnic Albanians demanded greater autonomy.
Official figures say most of those who left were Serbs and
Montenegrins who claimed discrimination by the Albanians.
   Last week, an Albanian-language daily in Pristina, the Kosovo
capital, reported 9,000 ethnic Albanians also had left the province
but said the reasons were economic rather than political. Kosovo is
a rural province with much less development than the rest of
Yugoslavia.
</TEXT>
