<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NewOrleansTax     08-22 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Orleans Tax,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barthelemy Hopes Voters Will Approve Property Fee After Convention
Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN McGILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Sidney Barthelemy disclosed Monday that
the city faces a $19 million budget deficit this year and said
officials kept the shortfall secret to avoid negative publicity
during the Republican convention.
   The mayor proposed a two-year ``property service charge''
designed to raise $10 million to help bridge the gap. Voters have
turned down two revenue raising proposals since Barthelemy took
office in 1986, but the mayor said he hopes a wave of good feeling
that swept the city during the GOP national convention would
generate support for his proposal.
   ``This last week was a spectacular week,'' said the mayor. ``I
think people felt a sense of pride in the city.''
   If the City Council approves the idea, a proposal for a flat
$125 fee on properties would be put on the November ballot. If
approved, the city would collect this year's fee in December.
   Spending cuts and other adjustments also would be needed to
balance the city's $280 million budget, said Kurt Steiner, the
mayor's chief administrative officer.
   Barthelemy said city officials realized in July there would be a
shortfall after the Louisiana Legislature _ facing its own fiscal
crisis _ cut funding for the city by $7.5 million. City tax
collections also are coming in below budget, officials said.
   But officials kept a lid on the news, Barthelemy said, so as not
to offset the good publicity the city was getting during last
week's convention.
   ``I think the positive press that we would have gotten would
have been countered by the `City in Crisis' or the `City Faces a
Deficit,''' Barthelemy said.
   Barthelemy, a Democrat, has been dealing with financial problems
since taking office. In 1986, he wiped out an impending $30 million
deficit by laying off workers, putting city employees on a four-day
work week and shutting down City Hall one day a week.
</TEXT>
