<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Trial,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Demand 15 Years For Former President's Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors asked Monday that a
brother of former President Chun Doo-hwan be sentenced to 15 years
in prison and fined $5.84 million on charges of embezzling public
funds, taking bribes and peddling influence.
   Chun Kyung-hwan, 46, is accused of taking 7.6 billion won ($10.5
million) in embezzlement, extortion and bribes while head of the
Saemaul Movement, a semi-official community development project.
   At the closing session Monday, senior prosecutor Lee Myung-jae
said the younger Chun deserved a heavy penalty for amassing an
illegal fortune by using Saemaul projects as cover. The Saemaul
Movement, once heavily subsidized by Chun Doo-hwan's government,
oversaw development projects in both urban and rural areas.
   Lee said the defendant showed no remorse and refused to admit
most of the alleged wrongdoing despite the evidence and testimony
from witnesses. He was arrested soon after his brother left the
presidency in February at the end of a seven-year term.
   Court officials said a verdict and sentencing in the case are
expected Sept. 5.
   It was the first prosecution of a corruption case arising from
the Chun administration. But the National Assembly, in which the
government party has lost its majority, has set up a special
committee to investigate alleged irregularities involving the
former president and his family.
   The prosecution also demanded prison terms ranging from one to
seven years for 11 other defendants, most of them former Saemaul
officials, who are charged with embezzlement, breach of trust, tax
evasion and other offenses.
   In his final statement to the court, Chun Kyung-hwan asked for
leniency because of his efforts on behalf of the Saemaul Movement.
</TEXT>
