<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1917EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Sudan-Floods     08-22 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan-Floods,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prime Minister Says Nile Floods Easing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi of Sudan said
Monday a drop in the Nile River water level would diminish flooding
in three days but the critical time lies ahead: early September,
when the rainy season peaks.
   Mahdi said foreign news media had exaggerated the effects of the
floods. His comments were carried by Egypt's official Middle East
News Agency in a dispatch from Khartoum, capital of Sudan.
   He said the Blue Nile's level at Dima, Ethiopia, about 530 miles
southeast of Khartoum, fell by four inches Monday and would be
followed by a drop in the water level in Sudan.
   ``This means that, however heavy the flood is today and
tomorrow, it will diminish in three days,'' the agency quoted him
as saying. ``The time to be reassured about the Nile flood is the
first week of September.''
   Torrential rains Aug. 4-5 caused flooding in northern, eastern
and central Sudan that killed more than 90 people, destroyed at
least 150,000 dwellings and left 1.5 million people homeless _ more
than a third of Khartoum's nearly 4 million inhabitants.
   Health officials predict epidemics of water-borne diseases as
people cut off from drinking water supplies are forced to drink
from standing pools.
   Thousands of people already have developed diarrhea. Malaria and
typhoid are on the rise and cholera is an imminent risk.
   The last flood of similar magnitude was in 1946, but Mahdi said
his country was coping better this time. He said foreign news
reports potrayed ``a drowning Sudan, with spreading plagues and the
first threat of locusts in a thousand years.''
   He acknowledged, however, that swarms of locusts are expected to
invade Sudan from neighboring Chad and Nigeria and will threaten
five million acres of cultivated land. He said the government had
22 airplanes ready to spray affected areas and enough insecticides
for 15 days.
   ``Sudan will fight the danger, with assistance from friends,''
he said.
</TEXT>
