<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Miracle-Aftermath     08-22 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miracle-Aftermath,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Launches Investigation of Miracles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LUBBOCK, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of bishops will be appointed to
study the reports of miracles at a charismatic church where three
parishioners claim to receive messages from the Virgin Mary,
Lubbock's bishop has announced.
   About 12,000 people gathered on the grounds of St. John Neumann
Catholic Church on Aug. 15 to celebrate the Feast of the
Assumption, after the parishioners said Mary told them miracles
would occur on that day.
   During the Mass, hundreds reported seeing apparitions of Jesus
and Mary in the clouds, while others claimed that the evening sun
appeared to dance in the sky and that silver-colored rosaries
turned a golden hue.
   ``I am asking the National Conference of Catholic Bishops to
assist me in preparing an investigation of the event and a panel of
specialists will be appointed shortly for this task,'' Lubbock
Bishop Michael Sheehan said in a statement issued late Friday
afternoon. It was his first comment on the Mass since the
apparitions were reported.
   Sheehan's secretary said he declined to speak to reporters.
   A spokesman for the National Conference of Catholic Bishops in
Washington said the organization has no involvement in the
investigation. ``He is free to set up his own investigation and ask
experts in on his own, but the national organization has nothing to
do with that,'' said Joe Lipovsky.
   Sheehan said he also has talked with an official from the office
of Pope John Paul II's envoy to the United States. ``An
investigation of this kind is normal and the panel will be charged
with studying the authenticity of the events,'' the statement said.
   The three parishioners say they began receiving messages from
the Virgin Mary earlier this summer, shortly after they returned
from a pilgrimage to Medugorje, Yugoslavia, where six youths claim
they have seen apparitions of Mary since 1981.
   Hundreds have begun attending Monday night rosary services in
which Mary Constancio, Theresa Werner and Mike Slate read aloud
messages they claimed to have received.
   The church has printed books containing these messages and more
than 50,000 copies have been distributed.
   In his statement, Sheehan said he has asked St. John Neumann
pastor Monsignor Joseph James not to promote or print the books
until the investigation is concluded.
   Calls to James' office Monday for comment were not immediately
returned.
   Sheehan said earlier that people shouldn't assume anything
supernatural is happening at the church.
   ``I take a cautious attitude about the rosary messages spoken
about by several parishioners at St. John Neumann,'' he said in
July. ``I neither encourage people to participate in the events nor
do I discourage them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
