<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1906EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-CBSPoll     08-22 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CBS Poll,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Poll: Bush Up Although Voters Question Quayle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Republican convention boosted George Bush to
a narrow lead in the presidential race, although many voters harbor
doubts about Sen. Dan Quayle of Indiana as his running mate, a
national poll said Monday.
   Half the respondents in the CBS News survey said they did not
believe Quayle has the experience to be a good president, and
another 28 percent were unsure. Thirty-nine percent said they
wished Bush chose someone else.
   Bush nonetheless led Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis by 46
percent to 40 percent in the poll of 1,221 registered voters
nationwide. Dukakis, enjoying his own convention bounce, had led by
17 points early this month.
   The survey was the first conducted entirely after the GOP
convention in New Orleans ended Thursday with a well-received
speech by Bush. It found favorable views of Bush and confidence in
his leadership well up from their pre-convention levels.
   But voters expressed reservations about the qualifications and
background of the 41-year-old Quayle, who has faced a barrage of
questions about his enrollment in the National Guard during the
height of the Vietnam War.
   Forty-nine percent of the respondents said phone calls made on
behalf of Quayle to the guard represented ``an unfair attempt'' to
gain his admission; 40 percent said such calls were acceptable and
21 percent were unsure.
   Among the seven in 10 who had heard of the issue, 48 percent
said they believed Quayle had joined the guard to avoid the draft.
Just 29 percent believed that was not his main reason, and 22
percent said they didn't know.
   Also among those who had heard about it, just 50 percent
believed Quayle was telling the truth about the National Guard
issue, while 26 percent said he was not and 24 percent didn't know.
   Quayle also did not do well in comparison with the Democratic
nominee for vice president, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas. Forty-one
percent said Bentsen would be a better vice president, to 28
percent for Quayle. The rest didn't know.
   Bush received a mixed rating for his handling of Quayle's
selection. Forty-seven percent rated it fair or poor, 44 percent
said good or excellent. But twice as many said poor _ 18 percent _
as said excellent, 9 percent.
   Still, backing was up for the Republican ticket as a whole. The
Bush-Quayle ticket led by 10 points among men and roughly tied
among women, 44-42. It led by 18 points among the youngest voters,
age 18-29; among the oldest, 64 and up, the race was a 41-41 tie.
   The six-point spread in the race was just within the poll's
margin of error of plus or minus three points. But several recent
polls have shown Bush gaining and Dukakis dropping from his
post-Democratic convention lead, allowing the conclusion that the
Republicans lead slightly. In a Gallup poll this weekend they led
by nine points, 51-42.
   Bush was expected to gain in popularity following the publicity
from his convention, just as Dukakis did after the Democratic
convention. Such bounces in the polls generally settle as the
campaign progresses.
   On Bush's personal ratings, 51 percent in the new poll said they
had faith in his ability to deal wisely with an international
crisis, while 37 percent would be uneasy. His rating on this
question in a CBS News-New York Times poll early this month was the
precise opposite.
   Dukakis, meanwhile, did far worse on the confidence measure: 53
percent uneasy, 29 percent confident.
   Bush was rated favorably by 39 percent and unfavorably by 25
percent in the new survey, much improved from his
favorable-unfavorable rating of 27-33 in the previous poll. Still,
27 percent were undecided in their opinion of Bush, and 8 percent
said they had not heard enough about him, after his nearly eight
years as vice president.
   Dukakis, who came in for sharp criticism at the Republican
convention, saw his favorable-unfavorable rating drop from 38-19
before the GOP convention to 32-25 after it, with 29 percent
undecided and 13 percent saying they had not heard enough.
   Efforts by the Republicans to paint Dukakis as a liberal had
little effect; 34 percent saw him as a liberal, compared with 35
percent in the earlier poll. But 34 percent said it was more likely
Dukakis would raise taxes, up from 27 percent in early August.
   Bentsen was rated favorably by 21 percent and unfavorably by 12
percent; the rest hadn't heard enough or were undecided. Quayle
scored 24 percent favorable to 18 percent unfavorable.
   Forty-two percent said Bentsen had enough experience to be
president, 23 percent said not and 35 percent weren't sure. For
Quayle, just 22 percent said he had enough experience, 50 percent
said not and 28 percent were unsure.
   Asked if they were glad Bush picked Quayle, 33 percent said they
were, 39 percent said they wished he chose someone else, 12 percent
volunteered that it didn't matter and 16 percent didn't know.
   The poll was conducted Friday through Sunday.
</TEXT>
