<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FBI-Hispanics     08-22 0510</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FBI-Hispanics,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Hears Statistical Evidence in FBI Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI opened its defense Monday in a
discrimination trial by presenting four hours of statistics
designed to show that Hispanics are promoted as rapidly and
disciplined as fairly as other FBI agents.
   ``Hispanics have no problem getting into management,'' Dr.
Rebecca Klemm, an independent statistical consultant, testified.
``They get what they ask for in terms of promotions.''
   The 311 Hispanic agents who joined in the class-action suit in
U.S. District Court contend the FBI discriminates against Hispanics
in hiring, promoting, disciplining and assignments. They want
damages and changes in FBI policies. About 400 of the bureau's
9,000 agents are Hispanic.
   During the first week of testimony, about 40 FBI agents
testified that Hispanics are transferred more often to undesirable
offices, are given more assignments that are either less glamorous
or more dangerous and receive less recognition for their successes.
   The FBI opened the second week of the trial with Ms. Klemm, who
disputed findings of Dr. Gary LaFree, a sociologist at the
University of New Mexico. LaFree testified last week that Hispanic
FBI agents are less likely to hold higher-level jobs.
   Ms. Klemm used the same raw numbers culled from the FBI as
LaFree but reached different conclusions. LaFree testified last
week that 15 percent of Hispanic FBI agents with at least five
years of agency experience are managers, compared with 21 percent
of non-Hispanic FBI agents with the same level of experience.
   Ms. Klemm testified that Hispanics have done better head-to-head
against Anglo agents when competing against them for promotions _
that 14.4 percent of Hispanics got such promotions versus 10.5
percent of Anglo agents applying for the jobs.
   She did not say how many people from each ethnic background
applied for competitive promotions.
   She said Hispanics have an average of about two years less
experience than their Anglo counterparts when they attain the
bottom rung of the management ladder in the FBI.
   ``In terms of career advancement, they advance timely,'' she
testified. ``Therefore, even if they do different things as
Hispanic agents, they do fine as far as advancement.''
   The suit was filed in January 1987 by Bernardo ``Matt'' Perez,
who contends he was forced by superiors in Washington, Los Angeles
and elsewhere to accept demotions he didn't deserve. Perez, now the
No. 2 agent in El Paso, used to be in charge of the San Juan,
Puerto Rico, office and was second-in-command in Los Angeles before
his transfer to El Paso.
   The non-jury trial is expected to end Friday and U.S. District
Judge Lucius Bunton is expected to reach a decision within six
months. Federal employees are not entitled to jury trials when
suing the government in discrimination cases.
   Hispanic activists have said a multitude of discrimination
trials could result if the plaintiffs win. Hugo Rodriguez, a former
FBI agent and the co-counsel for the plaintiffs, has compared the
case to those fought by blacks in the '60s and by women in the '70s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
