<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-22 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavy Rain in Plains, Record Cold in Parts of Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The summer of 1988 took an uncharacteristic turn Monday as
thunderstorms dumped heavy rain on parts of the Plains and
overnight temperatures hit record lows in parts of the Northeast.
   Storms buffeted several Plains states with gusty winds and heavy
rain, helping to replenish some drought-sapped soil and causing
some isolated flooding in parts of Iowa.
   In northwest Iowa, Sioux Center recorded over 6{ inches of rain
overnight and Monday morning. The downpour pushed the Floyd River
at least 1 foot above flood stage in places and caused minor
lowland flooding. Several other locations in that corner of the
state reported at least 3 inches of rain by morning.
   ``It might help the lawns some,'' said Keith Hora, president of
the National Corn Growers Association. ``And the football fields
will be green. But the corn is history.''
   The rain should help late-maturing bean crops and activate
herbicides, preventing carryover chemical damage next season, Hora
said.
   Elsewhere in Iowa, Des Moines got an inch and two-thirds of rain
in the six hours ended at 2 p.m. EDT while Waterloo, Ottumwa and
Cedar Rapids had about 1\ inches. St. Cloud, Minn., recorded 1{
inches in the same period.
   Morning thunderstorm winds gusted to 63 mph at the Omaha, Neb.,
airport.
   Midday showers and thunderstorms also hit northeast Colorado,
northwest Kansas, eastern Nebraska, southeastern South Dakota,
Minnesota, Iowa, northwest Missouri, northeast Illinois and
Wisconsin.
   Showers and thunderstorms also remained over the Gulf Coast and
the northern half of Florida and along the Georgia and South
Carolina coast.
   Astoria, Ore., set a record high for the date with a reading of
78 degrees.
   Several other cities set cold records with their early morning
lows. Syracuse, N.Y., hit a low of 43 degrees; Youngstown, Ohio,
39; Boise, Idaho, 45. Harrisburg, Pa., tied its low of 50.
   Frost was expected Monday night in the Adirondack Mountains of
New York and the Green Mountains of Vermont.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 56 degrees at Crescent
City, Calif., to 103 degrees at Manhattan, Kan. The nation's low
Monday morning was 25 degrees at West Yellowstone, Mont.
   Tuesday's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
Great Lakes to the Ohio Valley, and from southern Louisiana to
northern and central Florida. Showers and thunderstorms also were
expected over southeast Missouri and central Arizona.
   Highs were forecast to be in the 60s in eastern New England; in
the 70s from the rest of New England to the Virginia coast and
across the Great Lakes to northern Minnesota and North Dakota; in
the 70s and 80s along the California coast; and in the 80s from
western Pennsylvania to Georgia, in the Ohio Valley and most of the
middle and upper Mississippi Valley and central and northern
Plains, the southern Rockies, the upper Missouri Valley and
northwest Washington state.
   Highs were predicted to be near 100 degrees from north-central
Texas to southern Oklahoma and Arkansas, and over southwest Oregon;
and near 110 in the desert Southwest. Highs elsewhere were expected
to be in the 90s.
</TEXT>
