<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon-Shiites 3dLd-Writethru a0644 08-22 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Shiites, 3d Ld-Writethru, a0644,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shiites Slash And Beat Selves To Mark Murder Date Of Their Saint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs: Hussein, the Shiite... to CLARIFY account
of death. PICKS up 9th graf: Other parades...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Hezbollah cleric said Monday the
holders of foreign hostages in Lebanon should stick to their
demands ``until death.''
   Sheik Sobhi Tufaili spoke to 25,000 Hezbollah faithful marking
the death of the Shiite Moslems' most revered saint, Imam Hussein.
   In a clear reference to Islamic Jihad, the group that holds at
least two American hostages, Tufaili said:
   ``I turn to those holding the prisoners (foreign captives) in
Lebanon, although we do not accept to hold the hostages. I tell
them: Adhere to your demands. Do not let go of them or retreat
until death.''
   Demands made by Islamic Jihad, or Islamic Holy War, include
release of prisoners form Arab and foreign prisons, release of
Lebanese and Palestinians from Israeli jails and withdrawal of
Israeli troops from south Lebanon. It has specifically demanded
freedom for 17 Shiites imprisoned in Kuwait for bombing the U.S.
and French embassies there in 1983.
   Hezbollah, or Party of God, has Iran's support and is widely
believed to be the umbrella organization for Shiite extremist
groups holding most of the 18 foreigners missing in Lebanon, who
include nine Americans. Held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was
kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   Tufaili closed his remarks by declaring to hostage holders:
``You must protect them (the demands) by all means.'' Listeners in
the ancient city of Baalbek beat their chests with fists and
chanted: ``God Is Great!''
   Hussein, the Shiites' martyr, and a group of his followers were
massacred in 680 in what is now the Iraqi province of Karbala in a
leadership fight between Moslem factions. Moslems subsequently
formed the Shiite and Sunni sects of the faith.
   Other parades and observances were held Monday in Beirut's
southern slums and in south Lebanon, where thousands of Shiites
slashed their heads with razors or beat themselves with swords,
axes or iron bars. Blood dripped from the faces and chests of men
and children as they re-enacted the killing of Hussein.
   No deaths were reported in the special parades, known as Ashoura.
   In southern Nabatiyeh, traditionally the focal point of the
Ashoura, 50,000 people gathered in the main square to re-enact the
killing. Afterward, scores sliced themselves with razors and
clubbed themselves with swords or axes. Some lost consciousness and
were taken to hospitals for treatment.
   In southern Beirut, Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah delivered a
sermon to mark the anniversary. He is the sect's most influential
cleric in Lebanon and the reputed spiritual guide of Hezbollah, or
Party of God.
   Fadlallah gave his sermon in the air-conditioned Bir el-Abed
Mosque. The hostages, who include nine Americans, are widely
believed held in Hezbollah's Hay Madi barracks building, about 10
blocks from the mosque.
   Fadlallah omitted his habitual references to foreign hostages
but accused the United States and Europe of trying to snatch ``our
natural resources and then claim them as theirs.''
   ``When we say `Death to America' we mean death to the aggressive
policy of America, death to the colonial policy of America and not
death to the people of America,'' Fadlallah said.
   ``We are open to the American people, mostly to the oppressed
blacks who are being treated as second-class citizens,'' he added.
   When the sermon ended, about 10,000 faithful _ including
hundreds of women and girls clad in black chadors that covered
everything except for their eyes _ began their parade in the areas
they control in war-torn south Beirut.
   Many of the marchers carried either red flags, symbolizing
Hussein's blood, or black ones for mourning.
</TEXT>
