<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-ApartheidList     08-22 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Apartheid List,0383</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Apartheid Center Lists People Who Performed in South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Robert Wagner and singer Laura
Branigan were among a dozen Americans added to a list of performers
who have appeared in South Africa despite that country's racial
segregation system.
   The list is compiled by the U.N. Center Against Apartheid.
   Other Americans placed on the list are actors Robert Forster and
William Windom, actress Jennifer O'Neill, singers Della Reese and
Bonnie Bianco, theatrical directors William Levey and Aaron Norris,
conductor Joel Rosenberg, opera singer Janice Yoes and violinist
Lyndon Taylor.
   The center's report, released this month, said the people whose
names were newly added to the list appeared in white-controlled
South Africa in 1987-88.
   More than 500 individuals ang groups from 33 countries and
territories are on the list, which dates back to 1981.
   An individual may be removed from the list by writing to the
center and promising not to appear again in South Africa until that
country abolishes its policy of apartheid.
   Among the Americans deleted from the latest list are Cher, Frank
Sinatra, Paul Anka, Eartha Kitt and the Bellamy Brothers.
   The U.N.'s Special Committee Against Apartheid, which the center
serves, said in a foreword to the report, that artists and
entertainers, ``representing a most sensitive and freedom-loving
part of humankind are capable, by their example, to exert an
important influence on public opinion and can contribute positively
to world action against apartheid.''
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
   Some of the Americans still on the center's list for visits to
South Africa are singers Ray Charles, Glen Campbell, Rita Coolidge,
Janis Ian, Ann-Margret, Johnny Mathis, Linda Ronstadt and Neil
Sedaka and the rock-music groups America, Sha Na na and Village
People.
   The Britons added to this year's list, the fifth issued by the
center, are the bands Nazareth and Wishbone Ash, ballet teacher
Margaret Barnes, writer Luanshya Greer, actress Moira Lister,
pianist David Lively, playwright Eric Paice, dance teacher Sue
Staples and actor Jeremy Taylor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
