<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Kidnapping     08-22 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Kidnapping,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazilian Police Free Kidnapped Canadians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Camille is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police seized three Brazilians
on kidnapping charges and freed unharmed two Canadian businessmen
who were being held for nearly $500,000 ransom, police and
diplomatic officials said Monday.
   A fourth gang member, identified as Alberto Sarmiento Martin of
Venezuela, is being sought, federal police spokesman Paulo Marra
said.
   Marra said 35 police agents surrounded the kidnappers Sunday and
freed Roger Desy and Camille Cote of the Desy International
livestock company of Montreal as a company employee was about to
hand over $60,000 in cash at the airport of Goiania, 135 miles
southwest of Brasilia in central Brazil.
   The two Canadian men, both in their mid-40s, had been held since
Aug. 17, he said.
   The Canadian Embassy in Brasilia said Desy and Cote came to
Brazil on Aug. 14 to conclude a sale of cattle to a Brazilian group.
   ``Apparently there was a falling out with some of the members
over commissions. Last week we heard the people (Desy and Cote)
were being held against their will, and it evolved into a
kidnapping and extortion,'' embassy spokesman Robert Benoit said by
telephone.
   Benoit said the Desy company was contacted for the ransom.
   He said Brazilian federal police were alerted though diplomatic
channels and that Canadian police also were notified.
   Marra said Brazilian authorities were unaware of the cattle deal
and that the two Canadians were officially in the country as
tourists.
   He said the kidnappers demanded $60,000 in Goiania in exchange
for one of the hostages. The other was to be released in exchange
for an additional $437,000 to be delivered in Zurich, Switzerland.
   A police team surrounded the agreed-on exchange point at 8 a.m.
and surprised the kidnappers when they showed up nine hours later,
he said.
   The police spokesman identified the three Brazilians arrested as
Joaquim Nunes and brother Luiz Rosa Lino and Divino Rosa Lino.
   Desy and Cote remained in Goiania on Monday being questioned by
police through an interpreter, Benoit said. The two were go to
Brasilia and return to Canada on Tuesday.
</TEXT>
