<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle'sFather 1stLd-Writethru a0673 08-22 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle's Father, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0673,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle's Former Dean, Father Challenge Charges of Special
Treatment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: TOP eight grafs new with former dean's comments, current
administration action; FIXES spellings of `proverbial' in 6th graf
pvs, DePauw in 8th graf prvs; picks up 9th graf, `Quayle, in...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>Quayle's Former Dean, Father Challenge Charges of Special
Treatment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former dean at the Indiana University
School of Law said Monday he was confident Dan Quayle received no
special consideration when he gained admittance to the school in
1970.
   ``I'd bet a dollar against a doughnut there was nothing unusual
or irregular about his admission to law school,'' said Prof.
William F. Harvey, the dean from 1973 to 1979.
   ``I was familiar with admissions during the '70s and am
confident if there had been something wrong I would have known
about it,'' Harvey said.
   Quayle's father, meanwhile, also challenged allegations that
family influence helped his son gain admittance to the law school
or secure a state job.
   Harvey, who taught the 41-year-old Republican vice presidential
nomineee during his last year of law school, described him as a
``very solid'' student.
   ``I remember him well enough to say without reservation that he
is not a lightweight or superficial,'' Harvey said. ``I had a high
regard for him. He was a very hard worker, gave excellent
recitations and had a very keen perception of the law.''
   Harvey made his comments shortly after current deans of the law
school said at a news conference in Indianapolis that school policy
prohibited them from making public any confidential information
related to Quayle's admission to the school.
   Associate Dean G. Kent Frandsen, who is acting dean in the
temporary absence of Dean Norman Lefstein, had huddled with other
top administrators at the law school all day Monday figuring out
how to reply to press inquiries about Quayle, said Charlotte
Wright, spokeswoman for the law school news bureau.
   A report published Sunday in The Plain Dealer in Cleveland
alleged that Quayle did not meet the admissions requirements for
the law school, but gained entrance after meeting with the
admissions dean, a Republican judge in a city where Quayle's family
owned the local newspaper.
   The candidate's father denied that charge.
   ``What people are trying to say is that Danny got his way paid
in to law school, '' said James C. Quayle. ``They're trying to
build him up like an aristocrat and then tear him down.''
   The elder Quayle, publisher of the Huntington Herald-Press, said
there was no truth to accusations that his son was admitted to the
law school with the help of his maternal grandfather, Eugene C.
Pulliam, publisher of several newspapers in Indiana and Arizona.
   ``Mr. Pulliam was a great philanthropist and he gave money all
the time to lots of schools in Indiana, as well as to zoos and
hospitals,'' Quayle said. ``But I'd risk my arm on the fact he
never gave money to the law school. His interest was in journalism
and getting better journalists.''
   Quayle described himself as the ``proverbial C+ student'' during
an interview Monday on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America,'' but said
that his family played no role in his admission to law school.
   ``What Danny did is he went down and talked somebody at the
Indianapolis law school and pointed out that he went to a private
school,'' the elder Quayle said of his son, who graduated in 1969
from DePauw University a small liberal arts college in Greencastle.
   Quayle, in a telephone interview, conceded that his son ``hadn't
put his academic skills together'' while at DePauw.
   ``He was no Mensa, but it was his thought that he probably got a
better education because they had much smaller classrooms and the
curriculum was defined for them,'' Quayle said. ``Somehow he
convinced them.''
   The young Quayle's personality also helped gain him a spot in
1970 on the staff of Attorney General Theodore L. Sendak, according
to Medford S. Evans, who was instrumental in directing the aspiring
lawyer to the Statehouse job.
   ``I think he probably got himself hired in the interviews,''
said Evans, a former editor, political columnist and editor at the
Pulliam family owned Indianapolis News. ``Danny Quayle was an
impressive young kid.''
   ``I would guess they (Sendak's staff) would take a look at
academic records but I think they would be influenced also by how
he handles himself,'' Evans said. ``This is an office that dealt
with the public.''
   Evans, who now is a staff member of the Washington-based
National Journalism Center, denied that family members pulled
strings for the Indiana senator, who worked his way through law
school.
   ``If the Quayle family had been that thick with the state
government, there would not have been any reason to contact me,''
said Evans, who contacted Sendak's office on behalf of Quayle, who
was then 22.
   Quayle's father also disputed that the family is enormously
influential in Indiana, as has been widely reported.
   ``People keep saying (Quayle) is from a prominent family, but I
tell you we run a paper with 9,500 readers. That doesn't carry a
lot of weight,'' the elder Quayle said.
   ``I like my new prominence,'' said the senior Quayle. ``The only
thing is I can't find the wealth.''
</TEXT>
