<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Argentina-Strike     08-22 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Argentina-Strike,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Strike Called To Protest Government Wage Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By OSCAR SERRAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest labor
federation said Monday it would call a strike by its 3.5 million
members next month to protest the economic policies of President
Raul Alfonsin.
   The walkout was scheduled for early September but an exact date
will not be set until later this week, said Saul Ubaldini,
secretary-general of the General Labor Confederation.
   The one-day general strike would be the 12th walkout organized
by the labor group since Alfonsin took office in December 1983. A
march by thousands of workers in the capital also is planned.
   The strike is being called to protest government economic
policies that union leaders say have caused serious inflation and
eroded the purchasing power of workers.
   Most Argentine unions belong to the federation. Its 11 previous
general strikes have been peaceful and fairly successful, shutting
down government offices and public transportation, although private
businesses have remained open.
   The cost of living rose 178 percent during the first seven
months of this year. After it increased 25.6 percent in July,
Alfonsin devalued the austral by 11.4 percent against the dollar,
implemented budget cuts and instituted a system of voluntary price
controls.
   Wages have not kept pace with inflation, and prices continue
rising despite voluntary controls.
   The labor federation has demanded an increase in the minimum
monthly wage, from the current $66 to $121. The federation on
Friday rejected the government's offer to boost the minimum wage to
$79.
   Alfonsin is asking the International Monetary Fund for $1.2
billion and the success of his economic recovery plan is a key
issue in the May presidential and legislative elections. Argentina
has a $56 billion foreign debt.
   Half of the 254 seats in the House of Deputies and about
one-third of the 46 seats in the Senate will be up for election in
May. A new president will take office in December 1989, when
Alfonsin's six-year term expires. Alfonsin is barred by the
constitution from running again.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-PresidentialMoney     08-22 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Presidential Money,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush, Dukakis Begin Using Federal Funds For General Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis and Republican George
Bush are delving into the $92 million taxpayer-funded trough for
the general election, with Dukakis getting to his share first.
   Dukakis got a headstart on Bush by receiving his party's
nomination almost a month before the Republicans formally picked
Bush last week.
   That meant he got his $46.1 million from the federal Treasury
earlier and has already spent $1.8 million, according to July
financial reports available Monday at the Federal Election
Commission.
   Bush, however, has wasted no time in laying the groundwork for
his general election campaign. He had borrowed money against the
$46.1 million he stood to receive once he became the official
nominee.
   Bush had spent $672,570 on his general election effort as of the
end of July, his financial report shows. He borrowed money he
raised during the primary campaign for his ``compliance fund,''
used for expenses to comply with election law administrative
requirements.
   Unlike the primary campaign, the candidates do not have to raise
money privately for the general election. They receive $46.1
million from the federal fund that is supported by the voluntary $1
checkoff on individual tax returns.
   As the general election campaign gets under way, the candidates
have invested heavily in polling and in media production for ads
that will be used between now and November.
   Dukakis invested more than $300,000 in polling last month.
   Bush has been spending more money getting ready for the TV wars,
paying more than $127,000 during July for media production and
consulting to the firm of his media consultant Roger Ailes.
   In addition to what the candidates are allotted, the Republican
and Democratic party organizations can spend $8.3 million each to
help elect their nominees. The limit applies to direct spending,
but the parties also have devised other ways to indirectly help
their tickets, through use of so-called soft money for generic
party activity. Those efforts will result in spending many times
the limit on direct party support.
   Dukakis closed out the last month of his primary campaign having
spent $21.7 million against the federally imposed $23 million limit
on primary spending, his reports showed. He still owed $469,000 in
outstanding bills, and his campaign committee was owed nearly that
much in receiveables.
   Bush, who was scrimping to keep from topping the limit by the
end of the campaign, was up to $22.6 million against the $23
million cap at the end of July. He was owed $255,183 and had
$61,446 in debts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0176 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-YouthSurvey     08-22 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Youth Survey,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Study: American Youth `Staying Younger Longer'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young people in the United States are living
at home longer, marrying later and taking more time to become
self-sufficient, according to a government report released Monday.
   Assistant Education Secretary Chester E. Finn Jr. said the study
of youth aged 14 to 24 indicates they are ``staying younger
longer.''
   ``They seem to be becoming autonomous, self-supporting
individuals at a slower rate than was once the case,'' Finn said.
   The report, titled ``Youth Indicators: Trends in the Well-Being
of American Youth,'' was compiled from information that had been
collected since 1950 at federal agencies and private organizations.
   Finn said the figures show young people ``are living with their
parents longer and they are slower to form their own families.''
   ``A number of indicators suggest that the transition from
childhood to adulthood is taking longer and presenting more
pitfalls than was the case several years ago,'' the study said.
   ``Youths in the 20s are living at home measurably longer; since
1970, they have been delaying marriage to significantly later ages;
and since 1980, they have found their average earnings declining
while those of older workers have increased.''
   Among the findings:
   _ The share of youth aged 18 to 24 who lived with their parents
or in college dormitories rose from 43 percent in 1960 to 53.6
percent in 1985.
   _ The number of first marriages per 1,000 never-married women
aged 20 to 24 fell from 220.1 in 1970 to 104.4 in 1984.
   _ Median income for women aged 20 to 24 fell from $12,517 in
1980 to $12,192 in 1986, using constant 1986 dollars. The
comparable figures for young men fell from $16,113 in 1970 to
$14,152 in 1986.
   The study said the trends may be related, since ``late marriage
is a reasonable response to lower earnings; living with parents is
a reasonable arrangement for those not earning enough to support
themselves.''
   Finn said the report also showed falling scores on college
entrance examinations and a last-place ranking for U.S. students in
recent international science and mathematics tests, raising concern
about how the youth will fare in the future.
   ``Compared to kids elsewhere in the world they are performing
poorly on all kinds of tests and that makes me worry,'' he said.
``They make me worry about the future of a country that's raising
up people with a number of years in school but that don't know
anything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
