<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Glasnost     08-22 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-Glasnost,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Ideologist's Spouse Criticizes Soviet Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Current Soviet culture is
``chaotic'' and the reforms of Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev
resemble those in Czechoslovakia before the Warsaw Pact invasion of
1968, a Czechoslovak educator has written.
   Eva Fojtikova, head of the Russian Department at Prague's
Charles University and the wife of the Czechoslovak Communist
Party's chief ideologist, Jan Fojtik, took a critical view of
current Soviet reforms in an article published Friday in the
cultural weekly Kmen.
   Her views of Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or openness on
selected subjects, come at a time when Czechoslovakia is trying to
find its own way toward greater openness, democracy and economic
restructuring.
   Fojtik, who was elected full member of the ruling Politburo in
April, is expected to chair a Communist Party plenary session on
ideology sometime next month.
   ``The present state of Soviet culture is very chaotic,'' said
the article by Mrs. Fojtikova. ``There is a marked effort of
newspaper journalism to suppress moderate opinions, all efforts to
guard and not betray the indisputable values created as a result of
the revolution and Socialist construction.''
   She added, ``It is not progress to substitute one cult lie with
another lie, another one-sidedness. With all due criticism of
(Soviet dictator Josef) Stalin, let us not forget that the cult is
not created by one person alone ...''
   Stalin's brutal regime has come under sharply increased public
condemnation under Gorbachev.
   ``We know from experience that idols are knocked down, mostly to
make room for new idols,'' the article said.
   The article also drew an apparent parallel between
Czechoslovakia prior to the 1968 Soviet-led invasion and the Soviet
Union today. Warsaw Pact forces invaded Czechoslovakia after a
series of reforms that came to known as the ``Prague Spring.''
   ``It is not possible to forget that in the Soviet Union people
did not live through a period of Hungarian, Czechoslovak or Polish
counterrevolution ... and have no direct experience with it.
Therefore, many illusions persist and (all) the greater is the
danger.''
</TEXT>
