<HEAD>Two More Members of Peasant Movement Arrested</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Two more members of the Peasants
Movement of Papaye have been arrested in the town of Hinchi and are
being held in the local army barracks, Radio Haiti-Inter reported
Monday.
   It said the two were arrested Sunday after they refused to pay
the tax that the town requires to sell goods in the marketplace.
Some members of the Peasants Movement have declared they will not
pay the tax until the market is provided with sanitary facilities.
   Eight members of the Peasants Movement were arrested Friday in
Hinche, 80 miles northeast of Port-au-Prince, and nearby Abriots
and accused of subversive activities, according to Radio
Haiti-Inter. It said they were released Monday ``on good
behavior,'' but they were bruised and bloody.
   The broadcast also said that officials of Haiti's military
government on Monday questioned Chavannes Jean-Baptiste, founder of
the Peasants Movement of Papaye, for five hours at the Hinche army
barracks.
   Jean-Baptiste, regional director of Caritas, a Roman Catholic
aid organization, was briefly detained by military authorities in
Hinche Saturday and told to appear at the barracks Monday.
   Radio Haiti-Inter said the officials wanted Jean-Baptiste to
allow government authorities to attend all meetings of the Peasants
Movement and it reported he refused.
   The movement is an association of peasants' groups in the
Central Plateau Department and was organized to establish
cooperatives and self-help projects.
</TEXT>
