<HEAD>Wider Distribution Doesn't Translate In Wider Box Office</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Box Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doubling the distribution of ``The Last
Temptation of Christ'' didn't translate into double ticket sales
for co-distributor Universal Pictures, according to weekend
box-office figures.
   ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' was shown to moviegoers in
Canada and the United States this past weekend on 18 screens, with
a box-office gross of $476,623, or $26,459 per theater.
   That compared to last week's $44,579 per screen for a three-day
total of $401,211 on nine screens.
   Christian groups have demonstrated against the movie, threatened
to boycott Universal Pictures and parent company MCA Inc., and
offered to buy the movie and destroy it.
   In the most controversial scene, Willem Dafoe as Jesus
hallucinates that he comes down from the cross and has sex with
Mary Magdalene. But the movie concludes with Jesus not succumbing
to this last temptation of giving up his divinity, and he dies on
the cross.
   In Athens on Monday, the Greek Orthodox Church said it has
called for a ban on ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' in Greece,
claiming its interpretation of the life of Jesus is ``horrifyingly
vulgar.''
   Archbishop Seraphim of Athens, the Orthodox Church leader in
Greece, sent a letter to the government saying Martin Scorsese's
film would ``clash directly with the religious sensitivities of our
people.''
   ``The film attempts a horrifyingly vulgar representation of the
person of the founder of the Christian faith,'' the letter said.
   Scorsese's film is based on a novel by Greek author Nikos
Kazantzakis, who was threatened with excommunication by the
Orthodox Church when the book came out in 1954.
   The film is expected to be released in Greece next month,
according to a spokesman for United International Pictures, the
distributor.
</TEXT>
