<HEAD>North Sea Killer Virus Found Among British Seals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mysterious virus that has killed thousands of
seals in the North Sea is now killing seals in British waters, the
Sea Mammal Research Unit in Cambridge reported Monday.
   Scientists of the unit monitoring the virus among the 7,000
common seals and 5,000 gray seals along the east coast said they
found the virus among seals which had been taken to a sanctuary at
King's Lynn in Norfolk.
   The virus has ravaged seals off the Scandinavian, Dutch and
German coasts. It is believed similar to the common cold or hoof
and mouth disease.
