<2ND_LINE>AM-Prison Walkaway, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0689,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Uses Chauffered Limousine to Flee Work Detail</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with inmate captured, details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate walked away from a work detail
Monday and fled in a chauffered limousine before being captured a
few hours later at a luxury hotel in Albuquerque, a state
Corrections Department spokesman said.
   Derrick Stillwell, 21, serving an 18-month sentence at the
Penitentiary of New Mexico for fraud, was among seven inmates
assigned to a work detail at the state Highway and Transportation
Department, said Corrections spokesman Kevin Jackson.
   One correctional officer was assigned to the detail, Jackson
said.
   Stillwell walked away from the detail at midmorning and was seen
getting into a late-model limousine that pulled up in front of the
highway department headquarters in Santa Fe.
   ``The driver (of the limousine) had no inkling he was an
inmate,'' Jackson said. ``I believe the driver thought it was a
business-as-usual pickup.''
   Corrections official traced the limousine and contacted the
driver, Phillip L. Pacheco, Monday afternoon. Pacheco said he made
a brief stop for Stillwell at a home in Albuquerque before dropping
him off at the airport at about 12:10 p.m.
   Dan Taylor, spokesman for the Department of Public Safety, said
late Monday afternoon that Albuquerque police recaptured Stillwell
at the AMFAC Hotel near the airport.
   The limousine had been reserved Sunday and paid for with a
credit card by a person identifying himself as Gregory Stephens,
Jackson said. The caller said he wanted the car to pick up his son,
Bruce, he said.
   The limousine driver told authorities that his passenger
mentioned he was going to catch a flight to Los Angeles and then go
to Seattle, Jackson said.
   ``We believe there might have been tickets left at the
airport,'' Jackson said.
   Stillwell, a New York City native, had entered the prison in May
and, with time off for good behavior, was scheduled for release in
December.
</TEXT>
