<HEAD>Nicaraguan Exiles Demonstrate In Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Nicaraguan exiles staged a
peaceful protest against the Nicaraguan government Monday inside
their country's embassy here until they were removed by Salvadoran
riot troops.
   The six men represented a group called the United Front of
Mestizos of the Nicaraguan Atlantic Coast and demonstrated for
about an hour and a half.
   They said they were protesting what they called the leftist
Sandinista government's failure to fulfill a year-old regional
peace accord.
   Among other measures, the treaty commits Central American
governments to democratize and negotiate peaceful solutions to
insurgencies.
   The demonstrators also distributed a leaflet calling for the
release of about 40 opposition leaders jailed in Nicaragua since
July.
   Thousands of Miskito, Rama and Sumo Indians began leaving their
tribal homelands along Nicaragua's Atlantic coast in 1981 after the
government tried to move them into relocation camps.
   Many fled to Honduras. Others joined U.S.-supported Indian rebel
movements.
   Over the past year, the Sandinistas reached agreements with most
rebel movements to lay down their arms, and the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees said most Indians returned to the
75-mile-long Atlantic seaboard.
