<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UMWSuit 1stLd-Writethru a0697 08-22 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UMW Suit, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0697,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Miners Sue Union For $1 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds two grafs of background</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PIKEVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of miners filed a $1 billion
lawsuit Monday against the United Mine Workers and its leadership,
charging that the miners were prevented from recovering wages lost
during a 3{-year strike.
   The lawsuit, filed in U.S. District Court, contended that the
union did not represent them properly and discriminated against
them because they refused to take part in picket-line violence.
   Defendants included UMW President Rich Trumka, his vice
president, Cecil Roberts, and secretary-treasurer John Banovick.
The suit accused them of conspiring to keep the 406 plaintiffs from
collecting benefits to which they should have been entitled.
   In Washington, D.C., union spokesman Joseph Corcoran said late
Monday that the union's legal department had not yet seen the
lawsuit.
   But Corcoran said, ``The union is very confident that that
settlement will be upheld in any court.''
   Jerry Hammond, a spokesman for the so-called ``Forgotten 400,''
said the suit stemmed from an agreement reached in May between the
UMW and two A.T. Massey Coal Co. subsidiaries to end selective
strikes launched against two eastern Kentucky mines in 1984.
   The agreement, requiring payment of $4.47 million to the union,
also settled a lawsuit challenging Massey's decision to turn the
Leslie and McInnes mines at Sidney, Ky., into non-union operations.
   About 700 miners, including Hammond, worked at the two mines
until February 1983 when all but a maintenance crew were laid off.
The remaining miners lost their jobs Sept. 30, 1984, the day before
the two mines were sold to Sidney Coal Co., a subsidiary of Ora Mae
Coal Co., an operation owned by Massey.
   After the agreement was announced, Roberts said the $4.47
million for lost wages and benefits would be divided among some 250
miners, who had been on selective strikes, with each receiving
about $18,000.
   Hammond said the lawsuit contends that the UMW breached its duty
of fair representation by limiting the number of members who would
receive payments. The plaintiffs also contend they have been
excluded from union meetings, thus violating the organization's
constitution.
   The lawsuit asks for a jury trial, plus $500 million in
compensatory and $500 million in punitive damages.
   Trumka pushed for the union's use of selective strikes, and on
Oct. 1, 1984 Massey Coal Co. became the first target after the
company refused to sign the union's national coal wage contract.
Signing would have given Massey's laid-off employees companywide
re-employment rights.
   The union finally called off the sometimes violent strike in
December 1985 when Massey agreed to settlement of an unfair labor
practice charge, but selective strikes against the two subsidiaries
continued until May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0189 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Eurotunnel     08-22 0363</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eurotunnel,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eurotunnel Confirms Delays in Channel Tunnel Project</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eurotunnel, the Anglo-French consortium set up to
build a 31-mile rail tunnel between France and Britain, confirmed
on Monday that the project is running well behind schedule.
   Eurotunnel issued a formal warning to Transmanche-Link about its
likely failure to meet several constuction targets.
Transmanche-Link is a joint venture of British and French
construction companies which has the contract to design and build
the tunnel by May 1993.
   Transmanche-Link declined to comment on the delays in the tunnel
project.
   Eurotunnel warned that Transmanche-Link could face fines if it
does not speed up the rate of tunneling.
   A Eurotunnel spokesman, who was not identified, in accordance
with British custom, said Transmanche-Link is ``not yet managing
the tunneling program to our satisfaction.''
   Tunneling on the British side is at about half the rate targeted
in the contract, Eurotunnel said.
   Transmanche-Link has bored only 1.1 miles of one tunnel, against
the 2.4 miles due by early last week. The link is to have three
tunnels.
   The rate of tunneling is running at about 380 feet a week,
compared with a target of 660 feet a week.
   Tunneling on the French side also is behind schedule, Eurotunnel
said.
   Project delays could affect banks' willingness to inject funds
into the project, said Richard Hannah, an analyst at the brokerage
Phillips and Drew.
   So far, the tunnel work has been financed with funds raised
through the sale of $1.3 billion worth of stock in the consortium.
Once those funds have been exhausted, Eurotunnel can draw on an
$8.5 billion loan signed last November with a syndicate of
commercial banks.
   But the banks have to be satisfied that sufficient progress on
the project has been made before they commit any money, Hannah said.
   ``They will have a very hard look at the project before putting
any money in,'' he added.
   The first drawdown of the bank financing is due in October,
Hannah said.
   Eurotunnel units, which are made up of one share in Eurotunnel
PLC and one in Eurotunnel S.A., were off 12 pence (20 cents) at 313
pence ($5.29) on London's Stock Exchange by late Monday afternoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
