<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2231EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Leftists     08-22 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Leftists,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Coalition to Run in 1989 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leftist coalition whose
leaders are linked to Marxist-led guerrillas announced Monday it
will participate in the March presidential elections.
   Leftist parties have boycotted elections since civil war began
in late 1979. They said their security could not be guaranteed and
that elections formed part of a U.S.-directed counterinsurgency
plan.
   In the past, the Christian Democratic government of President
Jose Napoleon Duarte has invited leftist political leaders to
participate in elections but asked the guerrillas to lay down their
arms.
   The Democratic Convergence, a coalition of three left-of-center
parties, said Monday it will choose its candidates in coming weeks.
   The coalition includes the National Revolutionary Movement, the
Popular Social Christian Movement and the Social Democratic Party.
   Guillermo Ungo, leader of the National Revolutionary Movement,
and Ruben Zamora, chief of the Popular Social Christian Movement,
are the president and vice-president, respectively, of the
Democratic Revolutionary Front.
   The front forms a civilian-military alliance with the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front, the guerrilla army battling the
U.S.-backed government.
   An estimated 65,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in the
civil war.
   The guerrillas condemned previous elections as farces, but
leftist civilian politicians recently said guerrilla leaders
understand their decision to take part in the March elections.
   ``Our objective in the electoral process is the promotion of a
political and negotiated solution to the armed conflict as an
indispensable condition for fulfilling the Salvadoran people's most
pressing demands,'' a communique issued by the Convergence said.
   ``The upcoming elections will not in themselves resolve the
fundamental problems of our society ... but we are convinced that
our participation will bind and mobilize people around the
objectives of social justice, democracy, national independence and
peace.''
   The election is likely to be a close contest between El
Salvador's two dominant parties, the incumbent Christian Democrats
and the conservative Republican Nationalist Alliance.
   The alliance, known as Arena, gained control of the legislature
and two-thirds of the country's municipal governments in elections
held in March.
   Duarte has been diagnosed as having terminal liver cancer.
</TEXT>
