<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WaterRestrictions     08-22 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Water Restrictions,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Carolina Town Orders Water Use Restrictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SILER CITY, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with a third straight summer of
low rainfall, officials ordered most of the town's 4,500 residents
and businesses to cut water use by 20 percent Monday.
   ``The gut of the problem is we haven't gotten any rain,'' City
Manager Ben Shivar told a news conference. ``If we had gotten the
kind of showers that fell this weekend in Sanford and Greensboro,
we would have substantially reduced our problem,'' Shivar said
referring to two other central North Carolina cities.
   The main reservoir supplying this town 50 miles west of Raleigh
is more than six feet below its normal level, reducing the
available water supply to about 44 percent of normal, Shivar said.
   If customers continue to use water at the current rate of about
2.2 million gallons a day without substantial rainfall, the city
could run out of water in about 41 days, Shivar said.
   Mayor Earl B. Fitts' order Monday mandates a water allocation
system requiring residents and most businesses to cut water use by
20 percent immediately. The order requires two large poultry
producers _ Townsend Foods and Mid-State Farms _ to reduce water
consumption by 30 percent.
   Shivar said the two poultry companies, which employ about 500
people, use about 42 percent of the city's water supply.
   Voluntary conservation measures have reduced daily consumption
to just less than 2.2 million gallons from about 2.47 million
gallons, Shivar said. Monday's order is designed to reduce daily
usage by an additional 300,000 gallons. Anyone found violating the
order a third time could be penalized with fines and termination of
service.
   Residents could face stricter restrictions in the coming weeks
unless consumers cooperate, Shivar said.
   ``We might not be able to avoid layoffs,'' he said. So far, no
businesses have had to cut back on production because of the water
crisis, he added.
</TEXT>
