<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     08-22 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0485</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Minister Denies U.S. Harassment Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter on
Monday denied charges that Panamanian forces are harassing U.S.
military personnel, calling the allegations an escalation of a
campaign to undermine the government.
   Ritter told a news conference U.S. officials who accused the
government of encouraging attacks on Americans were seeking ``an
excuse ... (for) new and more aggressive measures against Panama.''
   U.S. officials in Panama said Sunday that American personnel
reported at least 240 incidents of harassment by Panamanian
officials this year, ranging from extortion for traffic violations
to the blocking of mail.
   The Panama Defense Forces rejected the allegations Sunday night
and said in a statement that American troops caused problems for
Panamanian authorities, including fights, mistreatment of women and
shooting in public places.
   The Reagan administration has applied economic sanctions against
Panama in an effort to force the ouster of Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, commander of the Defense Forces and the country's de facto
ruler.
   Noriega is under U.S. indictment in Florida on drug trafficking
and money laundering charges, which he denies.
   Ritter said Monday American officials made the allegations to
make it appear that ``the (U.S.) aggressors become the victims.''
   He reiterated Panamanian charges that the United States was
seeking a pretext to annul the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties, under
which the United States is to hand over control of the canal to
Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   Col. Rogelio Alba, co-president of a bi-national committee
charged with the defense of the Panama Canal, said that U.S.
Southern Command officials ``have shown a lack of respect in all
things for us.''
   Alba said, ``We've gone out of the way to collaborate with them.
We've never interfered with them, and they're killing us with
hunger.'' _ referring to the U.S. economic sanctions that have
crippled Panama's economy.
   The New York Times on Sunday quoted U.S. Southern Command, State
Department and Defense Department officials as saying there have
been an increasing number of beatings, abductions, rape and
extortion of U.S. military personnel and their dependents.
   The story, under a Washington dateline, said the U.S. officials
viewed the incidents as a campaign by the Panamanian government to
pressure the United States to lift sanctions.
   But one Southern Command official said Sunday the increased
reports of harassment ``could be just an indication of individual
frustration and anger.''
   Washington imposed economic sanctions on Panama in March after
the Noriega ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle. Delvalle has
since been in hiding, but the United States continues to recognize
him as Panama's legitimate president.
   About 12,000 U.S. servicemen are stationed in Panama by treaty
to protect the Panama Canal. They are attached to the Southern
Command, which oversees all U.S. military operations south of the
U.S.-Mexico border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
