<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DietLabFire     08-22 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Diet Lab Fire,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smoke Causes Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REXBURG, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosion and fire at the
pharmaceutical laboratory associated with Diet Center stores Monday
sent clouds of smoke through this eastern Idaho town, forcing the
evacuation of a four-block-wide area.
   The blast occurred about 3 p.m. in the research and development
laboratories at Ferguson Pharmaceutical while employees were on a
break. No injuries were reported, said Ross Mayfield, operations
director for the state Bureau of Disaster Services.
   Residents and businesses within a two-block radius were
evacuated, along with pupils and employees at a nearby elementary
school, where classes were just ending.
   Most of the materials in the laboratory involved vitamins and
diet supplements manufactured for the company's 2,300 Diet Center
franchises in the United States and Canada, Mayfield said.
   Authorities warned residents, however, that the smoke could
contain toxic elements. Mayfield said this was because the fire
burned plastic containers, releasing hazardous gases.
   About 120 employees worked in the laboratories, said Roger
Ferguson, co-founder of the Diet Centers with his wife, Sybil. The
company had about a 60-day supply of stock in another building,
said his son, Mike Ferguson.
   The fire was expected to burn through the night, said Doug Call,
chief of the Idaho Falls Fire Department, which was called for
assistance.
   The cause of the blast remained undetermined late Monday.
</TEXT>
