<2ND_LINE>AM-Emergency Landing, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0737,0408</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Press Plane Accompanying Bush Makes Safe Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `It went...' with two grafs to UPDATE with
plane grounded, reporters taking another craft to Seattle; picks up
10th graf, `Key Air...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chartered jet carrying about 80 reporters
covering Republican presidential nominee George Bush was forced to
dump fuel Monday and return to O'Hare International Airport,
officials said.
   ``It's taxiing to the terminal. There were no reports of
injuries,'' said a supervisor at the O'Hare tower who would not be
identified by name.
   He said the Boeing 727 landed without incident at 2:48 p.m. CDT.
He was uncertain how far out of Chicago the aircraft was when it
developed problems.
   ``They took off and they had a bad flap indicator,'' said Mort
Edelstein, spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration.
   The reporters had covered the vice president's campaign stop in
Chicago, and were flying to Bush's next campaign stop at Spokane,
Wash., authorities said.
   Edelstein said the decision to dump fuel while the plane circled
over Lake Michigan preparing for an approach to O'Hare was routine.
   ``It's a precaution. When you make an emegency landing you don't
want to come in loaded, heavy with fuel,'' Edelstein said.
   The plane was chartered from Key Air, based in Rosslyn, Va.,
said Missy Compton, a spokeswoman in Bush's Washington campaign
office.
   ``It went back to Chicago. They have mechanics there in Chicago
who are going to work on the plane,'' she said.
   Key Air officials decided Monday evening to ground the plane,
and the reporters proceeded to Spokane on another aircraft,
Edelstein said.
   Key Air Vice President Scott Andrews said the flap problem was
not serious and that the plane could have flown to Spokane if the
captain had chosen to do so, though at a reduced altitude and speed.
   Andrews said the flaps on the plane's wings failed to go back to
their normal position after takeoff.
   The incident was the second malfunction in the plane in three
days, Andrews said.
   During Bush's trip to Ohio over the weekend, smoke entered the
jet's cabin as the aircraft landed at Port Columbus International
Airport. Airport officials said a hose came loose and allowed a
small amount of smoke to leak, but said the problem was minor. The
plane continued from Columbus to Cleveland on Saturday without
incident, officials said.
</TEXT>
