<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Paraguay-Youth Adv29   08-22 0666</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Paraguay-Youth, Adv 29,0684</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs Aug. 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Paraguayan Youth Seen as Turning Backs on Stroessner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH LOVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 34 years in power, President
Alfredo Stroessner's Colorado Party is losing the loyalty of young
people. Leaders say they are concerned but not alarmed.
   The trend is most evident in the universities, although no
statistics are available to show the exact numbers of youths
leaving or refusing to join the governing party.
   Student governments that formerly were staunchly pro-Stroessner
now are dominated by coalitions that challenge the government.
Students also are forming new groups.
   ``I'm a Colorado by tradition, not conviction, because you have
to be one to work as a public employee,'' said a 20-year-old law
student who gave her name only as Maria. She added that she was
fired from a government job for voting for an opposition slate of
candidates for her student government.
   ``There is no doubt that the Colorado Party has been losing
influence among the young these days,'' said sociologist Jose
Nicolas Morinigo.
   The Paraguayan Federation of University Students, which
Education Minister Carlos Ortiz Ramirez describes as ``one more
movement of irregular opposition to the government,'' was set up
last year and comprises more than a dozen member groups.
   The Colorado Party claims 1.4 million members, most of whom are
younger than 29 and know no other president than Stroessner, who
took power by coup in 1954 and has ruled ever since. He is now 75
years old.
   The party, after the armed forces, is the strongest institution
in this rural, landlocked nation of 3.8 million people. Membership
is required for all public employees, and a prerequisite for
benefits such as government scholarships.
   Desertions by youths and challenges by those who chart an
independent course from within pose a thorny problem that Colorado
officials acknowlege they must address.
   A priority next year is ``the recovery of the diverse student
centers that are circumstantially in the hands of the opposition,''
said Mario Abdo Benitez, the party's vice president and
Stroessner's longtime private secretary.
   ``We have made mistakes, but we are trying to set them right and
give a greater dynamism to our policies with the young,'' said
Martin Chiola, a Colorado congressman who is president of the
party's Committee on Student Affairs.
   Students along with the Catholic Church have called on the
government to allow more civil rights and political liberties.
   In May, when Pope John Paul II visited Paraguay, dozens of young
people at a rally held up their arms, shackled at the wrists with
handkerchiefs, to dramatize the lack of freedoms.
   In July, students boycotted classes at Catholic University to
protest the expulsion of the Rev. Juan Antonio de la Vega, a
Spanish Jesuit priest who had lectured on Liberation Theology, a
social reform movement among clergymen.
   Thousands of youths were among the estimated 20,000 people who
in early August marched silently through the streets of the capital
in a gesture of solidarity with the Catholic Church, to which most
Paraguayans at least nominally belong.
   The Rev. Dionisio Daeshague, who helped organize 14,000 youth
volunteers for the papal visit, said dissident or independent
student groups could be ``a time bomb for the government. All they
need is someone to light the wick.''
   Party leaders are concerned, but not alarmed. Militant
Stroessner supporters won control of the party at its convention
last year. While that alienated some members, it nevertheless
demonstrated that Stroessner's power base remains strong.
   ``Some of the youth call for democracy, but I don't know what
kind of democracy they want and demand because I consider this a
democracy,'' said Zoraida Ramirez, vice president of the
government-sanctioned Colorado University Student Association.
   ``We have peace, we have progress with the government of
President Stroessner,'' said Ms. Ramirez, a 24-year-old economics
student at National University. ``One has to leave the country to
fully appreciate the peace in which we live.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs Aug. 29</NOTE>
