<NOTE>For Release Wednesday, Aug. 31</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Wednesday, Aug. 31, the 244th day of 1988. There are
122 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   One hundred years ago, on Aug. 31, 1888, Mary Ann Nicholls, a
42-year-old prostitute, was found stabbed to death in London's East
End in what is generally regarded as the first of at least five
murders committed by the notorious serial killer who came to be
known as Jack the Ripper. Speculation about the identity of the
Ripper, who was not known to have been apprehended, continues to
this day.
   On this date:
   In 1688, preacher and novelist John Bunyan, author of ``The
Pilgrim's Progress,'' died in London.
   In 1881, the first U.S. tennis championships were played, in
Newport, R.I.
   In 1886, the first recorded major earthquake in U.S. history
rocked Charleston, S.C., killing up to 110 people.
   In 1887, inventor Thomas A. Edison received a patent for his
Kinetoscope, a device which produced moving pictures.
   In 1895, the first professional football game (in the sense that
one quarterback was paid) took place in Latrobe, Pa. (John
Brallier, who received $10, led a YMCA-sponsored team to a 12-0
victory over a team from the town of Jeanette.)
   In 1935, President Franklin D. Roosevelt signed an act
prohibiting the export of U.S. arms to belligerents.
   In 1941, ``The Great Gildersleeve,'' a spin-off of ``Fibber
McGee and Molly,'' made its debut on NBC radio with Harold Peary in
the title role.
   In 1954, Hurricane Carol hit the northeastern United States,
resulting in nearly 70 deaths and millions of dollars in damage.
   In 1962, the Caribbean nation of Trinidad and Tobago became
independent within the British Commonwealth.
   In 1965, the U.S. House of Representatives joined the Senate in
voting to establish the Department of Housing and Urban Development.
   In 1969, boxer Rocky Marciano died in the crash of a small
airplane in Iowa, one day short of his 46th birthday.
   In 1980, Poland's Solidarity labor movement was born as Deputy
Prime Minister Mieczyslaw Jagielski and labor leader Lech Walesa
signed an agreement in Gdansk, ending a 17-day-old strike.
   In 1985, a suspect in the Night Stalker killings that terrorized
Southern California was captured in East Los Angeles.
   In 1986, 82 people were killed when an Aeromexico jetliner and a
small private plane collided near Los Angeles International
Airport, dropping wreckage over Cerritos, Calif.
   In 1986, the Soviet passenger ship Admiral Nakhimov, collided
with a merchant vessel in the Black Sea, causing both vessels to
sink. According to Soviet accounts, up to 448 people died.
   Ten years ago: In a surprise move, Symbionese Liberation Army
founders William and Emily Harris pleaded guilty in an Alameda
County, Calif., courtroom to the 1974 kidnapping of newspaper
heiress Patricia Hearst.
   Five years ago: Slain Philippine opposition leader Benigno S.
Aquino Jr. was buried in his homeland, 10 days after he was shot
dead as he ended a self-imposed political exile.
   One year ago: The Justice Department challenged the
constitutionality of the 1978 Ethics in Government Act, which
provides for the appointment of independent counsels. (On June 29,
1988, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld the law.)
   Today's birthdays: Broadcast journalist Daniel Schorr is 72.
Comedian Buddy Hackett is 64. Actor James Coburn is 60. Baseball
Hall-of-Famer Frank Robinson is 53. Violinist Itzhak Perlman is 43.
Singer Van Morrison is 43. Actor Richard Gere is 39.
   Thought for today: ``With history being made all the time, every
day now seems to be the first anniversary of something awful.'' _
Anonymous.
</TEXT>
