<1ST_LINE>a i AM-TiberRenaissance ADV31   08-22 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tiber Renaissance, ADV31,0776</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv31</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Aug. 31, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Tiber Lovers Try to Turn the Tide for Rome's Polluted River</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smelly sewage notwithstanding, the Tiber is having a
renaissance.
   Once the river was the lifeline of Rome. From ancient times to
just a century ago, Romans bathed, fished and washed their clothes
in it.
   Rome's unplanned development boom after World War II, however,
proved too much for the river. In 20 years, the population swelled
from 1 million to more than 3 million.
   Anyone foolish enough to swim in the Tiber risks fatal infection
from the untreated sewage that pours into it daily. Today's Romans
don't have the habit a going down to the river _ a stroll there
means sidestepping broken bottles, rats and syringes discarded by
drug addicts.
   But this summer gave Tiber lovers hope the tide is turning their
way in the battle against pollution and neglect.
   With an eye on developing tourist attractions for 1990, when
Rome hosts the World Cup soccer games, the city offered free boat
rides during July. The response was so great that the promotion was
extended into September.
   Tickets sold out for sunset cruises to the romantic setting of a
play performed at the Roman amphitheater at Ostia Antica, the
Tiber's ancient port.
   Hot, breezeless nights found young Romans playing cards and
dancing on Tiberina Island.
   ``The fish will return, there will be pleasure boats. This isn't
the Thames, but there's reason to believe the Tiber can be made
livable for flora and flauna,'' said Aurelio S. Misiti, a sanitary
engineer and professor at Rome's La Sapienza University. His
department works closely with the city on Tiber projects.
   While dictator Benito Mussolini had declared the river
contaminated and banned swimming and transport in 1924, Misiti
noted, postwar governments didn't get around to prohibiting the
dumping of sewage into it until 1976.
   ``In 1974, Rome started building the first purification plant,''
Misiti said in an interview. ``Now there are four plants, but they
can only handle a bit less than half the discharge, and that's just
talking about urban waste, not industry's, which is supposed to be
handled by the factories themselves.'' The sewage treatment program
was supposed to have been completed years ago.
   Misiti said it should be finished by 1992 and ``after that the
Tiber should return to normal.''
   Just outside the city, fisherman pull in edible catch from the
river, which begins its 251-mile course in the Etruscan Apennines.
   Paola Ruggeri of the World Wildlife Fund says the city for the
most part doesn't enforce regulations forcing factories to purify
their wastes before spilling them into the Tiber.
   Since 1982, her group has rented from the city a stretch of
riverbank and intends to keep it as a green oasis.
   Willows, poplars, even a fig tree, lean out to the water, making
that stretch look more like Mark Twain's Mississippi than a river
channeled through a noisy, traffic-plagued international city.
   ``Every week volunteers come to clean it and every week we find
a mountain of garbage,'' Ms. Ruggeri said.
   Until about a century ago, the city spilled down to the river
banks, leaving Rome vulnerable to devastating floods, roughly every
couple of hundred years.
   After many suggestions, including those of Giuseppe Garibaldi,
the unification hero, the government began walling off the Tiber
and demolishing buildings at river-level. Now pedestrians and cars
move along, at bridge-deck level, with the Tiber's murky green
waters are out of sight below.
   Earlier this year, when the city planned its annual April 21
celebrations of the legendary founding of Rome by Romulus along the
left bank of the Tiber, it hosted an exhibit about excavations done
in the last 10 years, when the river became a distinct department
within the city's Superintendency of Archaeology.
   Tourists walking along the river can see the excavation of a
three-level storehouse for jars of oil, wine and fish sauce left
dockside by barges at the ancient port near what is now Testaccio,
a blue-collar workers' neighborhood.
   ``In the past, the city lived on its river. Rome was a kind of
Venice, a Copenhagen, a London or a Paris,'' said Claudio
Mocchegiani Carpano, head of the city's underwater archaeology
department.
   ``A thousand years from now, when they dig up artifacts from the
20th century, they'll find out that the Tiber just ran through Rome
and served as a sewer,'' Carpano said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Aug. 31</NOTE>
