<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1351EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-APN--St.Paul's ADV04   08-22 1124</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--St. Paul's, ADV04,1157</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 1 b&w
photo. ColorFoto subscribers get 1 35mm slide.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   
   EDITOR'S NOTE _ The baroque St. Paul's Cathedral, designed by
Sir Christopher Wren, is a beloved national monument in Britain. It
is also at the center of a heated debate over modern architecture,
since developers have a plan to rebuild much of the neighborhood
near the cathedral. Leading the opposition is Prince Charles, who
has emerged as a highly outspoken critic of today's buildings.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince Charles, Britain's best-known critic of
modern building, has put architects on the line in the one place
they cannot afford to blunder: opposite St. Paul's Cathedral.
   The domed cathedral in London, burial place of the nation's
heroes, survivor of the Nazi blitz, is now the focal point of a
heated debate about how cities should preserve their heritage while
coping with modern needs.
   The debate is symptomatic of a dilemma confronting all historic
cities. In the words of architecture professor Charles Jencks, ``In
most cities of the West there is a genteel blood bath going on
among those who have different tastes.''
   Nowhere is that battle more intense than at Paternoster Square
facing the north side of St. Paul's.
   Developer Tony Clegg, who owns most of the 7-acre site, plans to
tear down a clump of undistinguished 1960s office blocks and put up
more offices and shops.
   But Prince Charles, who got married in St. Paul's, hates Clegg's
plan. Although he has no architectural background, he has made the
subject one of his favorite hobbyhorses, and his opinions carry
weight.
   The baroque cathedral designed by Sir Christopher Wren is a
beloved national monument. So the developers consulted with the
Church of England, the Royal Fine Art Commission and other
interested bodies, and invited seven architects to compete for the
development.
   They also invited the heir to the throne to see the plans.
Charles disliked them all, telling a banquet in London's City
financial district last December: ``I was deeply depressed that
none of them had risen to the occasion.''
   ``Surely here, if anywhere, was the time and place to sacrifice
some profit, if need be, for generosity of vision, elegance and
dignity, for buildings which would raise our spirits and our faith
in commercial enterprise and prove that capitalism can have a human
face,'' the prince said.
   He likened much of the rebuilding of British cities since World
War II to a rape, and in his most controversial utterance,
suggested that modern London architecture was more unsightly than
the rubble left by the German bombers.
   Clegg conceded in an interview that ``there's been a lot of
criticism'' of the Arup Associates plan which his Mountleigh Group
chose.
   But he added that tastes change, noting that the existing plaza
and buildings, now despised, were much admired when they went up in
the 1960s,
   It is the prince's view that architecture should put people
first. ``Hurrah for the champion of ordinary people...Prince
Charles is acting as the conscience of the nation,'' wrote
architecture critic Gavin Stamp in The Daily Telegraph.
   The concrete shopping centers, dull office blocks and high-rise
public housing that typify many British cities were built hastily
to replace war rubble and solve the postwar housing shortage.
   Now, many are so hated that they are being dynamited by city
authorities. Today, many inner-city housing complexes consist of
cottages and gardens that mesh well with Charles'
small-is-beautiful philosophy.
   In Pittsburgh last March, Charles told a conference of
international architects that after 40 years of town-planning in
the United States and Britain, ``the results have been pretty
disastrous.''
   Charles went public on architecture in 1984, and has developed
his theme with mounting fervor, claiming to speak for ordinary
people whose views are ignored by the professionals.
   Although self-appointed as an arbiter of taste, 39-year-old
Charles is one of the most popular members of the royal fmily, and
his views get results.
   A projected extension to the National Gallery art museum in
Trafalgar Square was shelved after he called it a ``monstrous
carbuncle on the face of a well-loved friend.''
   Then he dismissed a 20-story tower design of the late Mies van
der Rohe, for a site near the Bank of England, as a ``giant glass
stump.'' It too was scrapped. This year his written complaint about
apartment blocks planned near his Kensington Palace residence led
to their alteration.
   Charles likes classical style buildings recalling 18th century
Georgian architecture, itself inspired by ancient Rome. He prefers
buildings on a human scale with ground-level shops and somewhere to
sit down.
   Many architects are aggrieved at being attacked by a man who has
no formal architectural training. A Paternoster plan which the
prince favors _ John Simpson's arcaded shops and low-level main
buildings with columned facades and sculpture _ has met a lukewarm
response.
   Architect Maxwell Hutchinson, tapped as the next president of
the Royal Institute of British Architects, accuses the prince of
abusing his privileged position.
   Writing in The Independent newspaper, Hutchinson denounced the
``fogeyish obsession'' with classical styles and wondered why the
work of contemporary British architects such as Richard Rogers, who
co-designed the futuristic pipes-and-glass Pompidou Center in
Paris, is more admired abroad than at home.
   But Jencks, writing in The Observer weekly, remarked that most
people now preferred ``to live in traditional houses at a village
level, and possibly in some other century.''
   Jencks also told a London audience that Charles had played a
crucial role in widening the debate. ``We are closer now than we
have been for 70 years to welcoming different schools and
philosophies of architecture,'' he said.
   Wren also had problems. His first two designs for a replacement
of the medieval cathedral, destroyed in the Great Fire of 1666,
were rejected.
   His cathedral, which attracts 3 million visitors a year, has
become a tough act for any architect to follow.
   Asked if he was worried by all the publicity, Clegg, 51, said:
``I think anything worthwhile is going to involve a whole lot of
argument and it will be worth it. Even without Prince Charles, lots
of people would have taken a strong interest in this site.''
   Clegg estimates his development will cost $700 million to $850
million. He says he will apply for planning permission in December,
start building in 1990 and hopes to complete the job by 1993.
   The rival plans were displayed for four weeks in the crypt of
St. Paul's and attracted 7,000 visitors, 700 of whom left written
comments which the developers say will be considered in the final
plan.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
