<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   08-22 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV00,0526</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Live at the Whisky a Go-Go'' (Elektra) _ X
   
   The songs are short, the arrangements smart and the band
rambunctious on ``Live at the Whisky a Go-Go.'' X squeezes 24 songs
into the two-record set. Just about everything rocks, and just
about everything clicks.
   Lead guitarist Tony Gilkyson is the star of the show. Many of
the songs, such as ``Another Perfect Day,'' are built around
Gilkyson's riffs. And his breaks combine finesse with wild abandon;
they're two parts rockabilly and one part machine gun.
   Singers John Doe and Exene Cervenka are in top form, too.
Neither has a particularly appealing voice, but they blend together
well and come up with some great harmonies, often when the band is
playing at top speed.
   For the uninitiated, only the absence of a lyric sheet keeps
``Live at the Whisky a Go-Go'' from being a perfect introduction to
X. It's impossible to understand what Cervenka and Doe are singing
most of the time, but the general theme seems to be that life is
not a beach.
   ``I wish it would snow in Fort Lauderdale, or at least rain and
hail,'' Cervenka sings on ``Skin-Deep Town.'' On ``The World's a
Mess,'' she contends just that: ``Go to hell and see if you like
it,'' she suggests. It's good to know there are still a few bands
out there with a bad attitude.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``No Friction'' (Gramavision) _ Fool Proof
   
   This well-intentioned set of ``back to the roots'' blues by a
group of jazz players from varied backrounds reinforces two
lessons: Good intentions alone rarely get you very far, and it's
not easy to blend musical styles.
   Fool Proof combines the talents of nine jazzmen brought together
by Gramavision Records President Jonathan Rose, who was dismayed
that many new jazz musicians were neglecting their blues roots.
   The result, ``No Friction,'' though well-played throughout, just
doesn't measure up as a good blues record. Too often, the jazz
chops sound like an intrusion on the blues arrangements. And
several of the songs lack emotional punch _ a fatal flaw in blues
territory.
   There are a few bright spots. There's a tough workout of the old
Al Green hit ``Love and Happiness,'' the only cover on the album;
``Red Car,'' composed by cornetist Butch Morris, is a good, jumping
tune; and saxophonist Dwight Andrews' ``Title Nine Blues'' has a
certain eerie charm, if you can be charmed by 7:19 of moody riffing
under a recitation of lines such as, ``Red blues ... brown blues
... I don't recall blues ...''
   Ultimately ``No Friction'' fails to satisfy. One gets the
feeling, though, that the musicians here will keep the spirit of
the project alive as they resume their own diverse work. Which
might say something good about good intentions after all.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
