<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Therapy ADV02-04   08-22 0711</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Therapy, ADV02-04,0745</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 02-04 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Music Is Their Healer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALLATIN, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Loney Hutchins gets his guitar out of the
case, sits at a table and begins singing a tune written by a lady
who's lucky to be alive:
   ``I could kiss your lips all night.
   ``Hold you in my arms with all my might.
   ``It's you who taught me
   ``The taste of love.''
   Across the table, Tammy Mitchem softly sings along with the
words she wrote. ``It's pretty good if I do say so myself,'' she
said.
   The 27-year-old woman from Gastonia, N.C., spent 2{ months in a
coma following a traffic accident in February 1987. While driving
to get horse feed, she was struck by a drunken driver in Bessemer
City, N.C.
   For the past 10 months she has participated in music therapy
under the direction of Hutchins, a singer-songwriter and former
associate of Johnny Cash.
   She is among about 25 people who once suffered severe head
injuries receiving individual and group music therapy from Hutchins
at Cedarbrook, a private treatment facility 40 miles northeast of
Nashville.
   ``These people could be vegetating without this facility,'' says
Hutchins.
   Patients start by listening to music, then graduate to singing
or composing. Some go on fieiew bear markets in a
favorable light.
   ``Remember, the only time you want stock prices to be at their
peak is the day you plan to sell. In the meantime, you should be
glad that the stock market periodically places its merchandise on
sale.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv Wednesday Aug. 24</NOTE>
</DOC>
