<HEAD>NASA Consortium Seeking Private Rocket Launcher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consortium is looking for a company to
build, launch and recover a rocket it hopes to launch next year for
a six-minute space flight with a half-dozen commercial experiments.
   The Consortium for Materials Development in Space will oversee
the launch of the rocket carrying experiments that require low
gravity. One is a study of making polyurethane foam in space, a
process that may someday be used to build structures in orbit or on
the moon, said Francis Wessling, associate director.
   The consortium, a cooperative venture by the University of
Alabama, industry and the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration, designethat they just can't do anything.
   ``Hopefully we will be able to explain this on the neurological
level, in terms of what the nerve cells themselves are doing. Then
we can look at developing drugs for it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 25</NOTE>
