<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stadd   08-22 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st add,0554</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armtek Corp., which has rejected a $550
million buyout offer from Mark IV Industries Inc., says it is
negotiating with a third party interested in buying the plastics
and chemicals company.
   The announcement Friday came one day after Mark IV sweetened its
offer for all of Armtek's stock to $44 a share from its original
$40-a-share bid.
   Armtek's board, which rejected Mark IV's original share as
inadequate, has not responded to the latest offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   GC&C Brands Ltd. has launched a new bid for Irish
Distillers Group PLC that values Ireland's leading whiskey
distiller at 253 million Irish punts, or about $354 million.
   The $5.60-a-share bid was made hours Friday, after GC&C received
regulatory clearance from Britain's Panel on Takeovers and Mergers
to proceed with a new bid for Irish Distillers, maker of Jameson's
and other whiskies.
   GC&C, a consortium-owned group, was restructured as a wholly
owned subsidiary of Grand Metropolitan PLC on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donnay SA, once the world's top maker
of tennis rackets, was declared bankrupt by a Belgian court after
failing to reach a deal with creditors to restructure its massive
debt.
   The family-run company is likely to become a takeover target,
and several potential acquirers are expected to come forward,
sources said Friday.
   Donnay climbed to the top rank among the world's tennis racket
makers when Bjorn Borg advertised its products a decade ago, but
the company began to suffer heavy losses after the Swedish champion
retired in 1981.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boise Cascade Corp. employees in three
Northwest states ended their 2-month-old strike against the
wood-products company after ratifying a new three-year contract.
   The pact was approved by a substantial margin of the estimated
2,000 union woodworkers eligible to vote, said Brad Witt, a
spokesman for the Western Council of Industrial Workers in Portland.
   The settlement was the second in the regional strike that began
June 6 and eventually spread to eight companies.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Government officials say national security does not
appear to be an issue in the proposed sale of steelmaking equipment
from a shuttered USX Corp. plant to the government of Iraq.
   But opponents claim that the sale of the Texas Works plant in
Baytown would threaten peace negotiations between Iraq and Iran and
is a deliberate move by the steelmaker to lessen competition.
   Republican Rep. Jack Fields said Friday he is concerned USX
would be exporting ``state-of-the-art armorizing technology ...
used for tanks and other military applications.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A late burst of computer-driven selling wiped out measly gains
in blue-chip stocks Friday and contributed to another mixed finish
on Wall Street, capping a sluggish week that traders would just as
soon forget. The Dow Jones industrial average, ended with an
11.03-point loss to 2,016.00, putting the index's decline for the
week at 21.52.
   The dollar finished mixed after being tipped lower by central
bank intervention that continued for a third straight day.
   Bond prices finished virtually unchanged.
   Crop futures finished lower; livestock and meat futures were
mixed; precious metals declined; energy futures rallied; and
stock-index futures advanced.
</TEXT>
