<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-22 0371</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher In Trading, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose swiftly in European trading this
morning, recovering last week's losses. Gold prices were lower in
quiet trading.
   Foreign exchange dealers said there was no central bank
intervention in early trading but they predicted another round of
concerted intervention this week to curb the dollar's rise.
   Traders in Italy said the market wasn't being led by hard
economic facts or news, but by statements from public officials and
a gut feeling that the Reagan administration wants a strong dollar
to help the presidential candidacy of George Bush.
   ``This is a market led by declarations. (U.S. Secretary of
Commerce William) Verity says one thing, the White House another,
and the market reacts accordingly,'' said a senior dealer in Milan.
   Verity's statement last week that a lower dollar is needed if
the U.S. is to right its massive trade imbalance had triggered a
fall in the U.S. currency.
   One dealer at a U.S. bank in Frankfurt said the dollar's
recovery and current strength raised the chances that the Deutsche
Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank, will raise its discount
rate at a meeting on Thursday.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.48 yen to a closing 133.88 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 133.85 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's
rates, included: 1.9137 West German marks, up from 1.8925; 1.6092
Swiss francs, up from 1.5915; 6.4835 French francs, up from 6.4125;
2.1615 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1390; 1,416.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,405.50; and 1.2277 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2271.
   In London, the British pound fell to $1.6860 from $1.7025 bid
late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $432.25 a troy ounce, up
from $432.00 bid late Friday. But at midmorning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a lower recommended price of
$429.70.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.50, down from $432.50 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.61 to close at $432.01
compared to Saturday's $433.62.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.63 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.68.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
