<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-22 0160</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Slip, Dollar Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices fell on the Tokyo Stock Exchange today as
some investors feared higher interest rates worldwide, traders
said. The dollar closed higher.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which gained
80.06 points Friday, lost 130.24 points or 0.46 percent to close at
28,079.18. Trading was moderate on the exchange's first section,
with volume at 600 million shares.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 133.88 yen,
up 0.48 yen from Friday's close, after staying in a narrow range
between 133.80 yen and 133.95 yen.
   Dealers said the yen-dollar exchange rate appeared to be stuck
within the 133-134 yen range.
   ``This is because investors are likely to sell the dollar if the
U.S. currency touches the 134-yen level, and are likely to sell the
currency if it approaches the 133-yen level,'' said an exchange
dealer at a major bank in Tokyo, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
