<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0757EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LukensContract     08-22 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lukens Contract,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steelworkers Ratify 3-Year Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COATESVILLE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although some complained about the lack
of a salary hike, United Steelworkers members at Lukens Steel Co.
approved a three-year contract that includes $2,400 in bonuses and
a new profit sharing program.
   Negotiators for Local 1165 and Lukens reached a tentative
agreement Thursday, just hours before the 1,400 USW members planned
to start manning picke lines. On Saturday, members voted 617-451 to
approve the contract.
   ``A lot of guys don't like it,'' steelworker Jack Entrekin said
after the agreement was explained to members. ``Of course, how they
talk and how they vote are two different things.''
   A number of union members were upset at the apparent trade-off
of profit sharing for a straight hourly raise because Lukens has
earned substantial profits in the past year, officials said.
   Last year's earnings of $46.6 million were more than double the
previous year's figure.
   ``I voted against it,'' said Edward Stanley, who has worked at
the mill since 1965. ``Slavery days are over.''
   In addition to the bonuses and profit sharing, the agreement
calls for better medical and insurance benefits, according to union
officials.
   The first profit-sharing plan for hourly employees would pay
steelworkers an extra 89 cents an hour based on company earnings
for the first six months of 1988, union officials said.
   Lukens steelworkers earn an average of $30,000 a year, according
to the company.
   John Washington, a crane operator, said he wanted to see an
across-the-board raise.
   ``We don't know what the steel industry is going to do,''
Washington said. ``The bottom could drop out tomorrow.''
   Harry Haines, president of Local 1165, said Lukens strongly
opposed a straight hourly wage increase because it automatically
would raise the company's costs for benefits and overtime.
   He shared the feelings of some union members who turned thumbs
down while walking in the rain to vote at the union hall Saturday.
   ``We told them we couldn't endorse it,'' Haines said. ``It was
our best effort, but not the company's.''
   Haines said the agreement provides for a $1,000 signing bonus,
to be paid in September. Workers also will receive bonuses of $800
and $600 in the second and third years of the contract.
   The bonuses are guaranteed, although payments in the final two
years would be deducted from any profit-sharing the workers earn.
   W.R. Wilson, chairman and president of Lukens Inc., the steel
company's parent firm, said it was his ``expectation and hope that
the steelworkers will do very well under the profit-sharing plan.''
   The union had worked under an extended contract since September
1986 but canceled the extension last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
