<DOCNO> AP880822-0252 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 0940EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Wickes     08-22 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wickes,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wickes Agrees To $598 Million Management-Led Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wickes Cos. plans to sell itself in
a deal valued at nearly $2.6 billion to a management group headed
by chairman Sanford Sigoloff, who led the retailing giant out of
bankruptcy three years ago.
   The $12 per-share offer announced Sunday is nearly $3 higher
than Wickes' closing stock price of $9.37{ Friday on the New York
Stock Exchange. It appeared to reflect Sigoloff's frustration at
failing to boost the company's stock price and profits through a
restructuring-and-acquisition strategy.
   Based in Santa Monica, Wickes is one of the largest suppliers to
the automobile industry, the world's biggest producer of wall
coverings and major retailer of home improvement products.
   W-II Holdings Corp., a firm Sigoloff established with members of
his management team, will offer to purchase nearly 40 million of
Wickes' 49.8 million shares, as well as assume its debt of $2.06
billion. The deal values Wickes at nearly $2.6 billion.
   But Sigoloff said in a statement that the agreement was
structured in such a way that higher offers from other potential
bidders were still possible.
   ``While we believe that our offer is fair, both management and
the board want to ensure that the company's shareholders obtain the
best price for their shares,'' Sigoloff said in a prepared
statement.
   The offer was publicized in conjunction with an announcement
that Wickes lost $12.4 million for the second quarter ending July
30, compared with earnings of $18.9 million a year earlier.
   The major participants in W-II Holdings will be institutional
investors, including the Wall Street firm Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., which will arrange much of the financing, Wickes spokesman
Michael Sitrick said.
   In 1982, Wickes became what was then the largest U.S. company to
file for bankruptcy protection, blaming the move on an excessive
debt load, deteriorating relationships with creditors and declining
profits.
   About three years later, the giant retailer was back on its feet
after selling 13 of its 32 divisions and winning creditor approval
for a plan allowing Wickes to emerge from bankruptcy court.
   The force behind the comeback was Sigoloff, who earned the
nickname ``Ming the Merciless'' for the tough-minded business moves
and hard-nosed cost cutting.
   With a reputation for working up to 16 hours a day, Sigoloff got
a break when Wickes' creditors allowed him to pay off $1.21 billion
in debt with $289 million in cash, $524 million in debt securities
and an 82{ percent share of the reorganized company.
   Part of the company's post-bankruptcy struggle has been blamed
on Sigoloff's strategy of issuing more debt to raise cash for other
acquisitions, some of which ended in costly failure.
   In April 1986, for example, Wickes bid more than $1.2 billion
for the National Gypsum Co., a Dallas-based building supplier. The
bid collapsed when National Gypsum was acquired by its management.
   Wickes also failed in a $2.1 billion hostile bid for the
Owens-Corning Fiberglas Corp., and a $1.7 billion bid for Lear
Siegler Inc., an aerospace and automotive equipment concern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
