<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     08-22 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0306</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were narrowly mixed today after
pulling back last week.
   The Dow Jones Average of 30 Industrials, which fell 21.52 last
week, was up 1.07 at 2,017.07 after 30 minutes of trading.
   But declining issues held a narrow lead over gainers among
issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 392 up, 436 down
and 486 unchanged in the early going.
   Big Board volume came to 20.49 million shares as of 10 a.m. on
Wall Street.
   Trading volume has been sluggish as investors have looked for
evidence about the direction of the economy and prospects for
inflation and interest rates.
   The economic indicators have been generally strong, but that has
inspired concerns about a resurgence of inflation.
   Interest rates have been rising in the wake of the Federal
Reserve's boost in the discount rate earlier this month.
   The Fed said in boosting its lending rate for member financial
institutions to 6.5 percent from 6 percent that it wanted to head
off inflation.
   But rising rates have raised some concerns that the central bank
could be pushing the economy toward a recession.
   Among the actively traded issues today, Philadelphia Electric
was up [ at 18, Kansas City Power and Light was up [ at 29} and
Exxon was down [ at 45|.
   The NYSE index was off 0.01 at 147.53. At the American Stock
Exchange, the composite market index was off 0.34 at 294.69.
   On Friday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 11.03 points to
2,016.00.
   In composite NYSE trading, gaining issues outnumbered declines
by about 4-to-3, with 794 up, 624 down and 522 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 122.37 million shares, against 139.82
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
