<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-China-Trade     08-22 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-China-Trade,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan, China to Sign Investment Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita will leave
Friday for a six-day visit to China where he will sign a treaty on
investment protection that has been in the works for seven years,
officials said.
   Takeshita also will hold separate meetings with China's four top
leaders on his first visit as prime minister to Japan's giant
communist neighbor.
   ``We place special significance on this visit, on the 10th
anniversary of the signing of the Japan-China treaty of peace and
friendship,'' a senior Foreign Ministry official said Monday.
``Takeshita will review the last 10 years and discuss the future
with his Chinese counterparts.''
   The Japanese premier is to hold his main talks with Chinese
Premier Li Peng on the first day of his visit, which begins in
Beijing. He also will meet separately with President Yang Shangkun,
Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang and senior leader Deng Xiaoping.
   The visit comes at a time of relative calm in relations between
the two countries, once wartime adversaries.
   Takeshita's visit will ``further economic cooperation, and the
prime minister will confirm Japan's policy to support China's
modernization course,'' said a Japanese diplomat, who spoke on
condition he not be named.
   The investment protection accord was reached after the Beijing
government was persuaded to grant ``national status'' to Japanese
companies investing in China, the Foreign Ministry official said.
Such status means Japanese investors will be allowed the same tax
and other benefits accorded to Chinese enterprises.
   Takeshita will pledge a third round of Japanese yen credits to
begin in 1990 in an amount still to be decided, the official said.
   Foreign Ministry sources have suggested that the ceiling for the
loan package will be about 800 billion yen, or around $6 billion.
The current ceiling on Japanese loans to China is 470 billion yen,
or some $3.5 billion. The loans are for hydroelectric power and
other major development projects.
   Trade between the two countries has moved into China's favor in
the last three years. In 1985 Japan's surplus with China was $5
billion, but after the first six months of this year China is in
the black by $500 million in a bilateral trade worth $8.6 billion.
   China is Japan's fifth-largest trading partner while Japan is
China's no. 2 trading partner.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
