<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Brokers,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pru-Bache, DLJ Report Record First-Half Profits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. and Donaldson,
Lufkin & Jenrette Inc. both reported record first-half earnings,
which were boosted partly by merger and acquisition and merchant
banking fees, the securities firms said Monday.
   The record performances came despite a slump in many sectors of
the securities business that pushed profits at several other firms
sharply lower.
   Prudential-Bache had profits of $92 million after taxes in the
first six months, compared with $3 million in the year-ago period.
Earnings in the 1987 period were reduced by more than $30 million
as a result of the discontinuation of the firm's international
trade finance subisidiary, a spokesman said.
   In the merchant banking department, Hachette SA's purchase of
Diamandis Communications Inc. contributed more than $20 million to
Prudential-Bache's first-half profit, a spokesman said.
   Prudential-Bache officials noted that beefing up investment
banking operations at the largely retail-oriented brokerage firm is
paying off.
   The company is a unit of Prudential Insurance Co. of America,
based in Newark, N.J.
   Donaldson Lufkin, part of Equitable Life Assurance Society of
the U.S., had profits of $33 million before taxes, compared with
$17 million a year earlier.
   John S. Chalsty, the firm's chief executive officer, attributed
the gains in part to merchant banking activity. He also noted that
the firm managed to avoid trading losses.
   Neither Prudential Insurance nor Equitable, both mutual
insurance companies, report the earnings of their brokerage units
publicly.
</TEXT>
