<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-Recall     08-22 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Recall,0300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler's Canadian Branch Won't Recall Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Canadian government cannot make Chrysler Corp.
recall 120,000 cars that may violate pollution laws even though the
company recalled 492,000 cars for a similar reason in the United
States, officials said.
   Chrysler cars built between 1986 and early 1987 with 2.2-litre
and 2.5-litre engines were recalled in the United States in April
1987 because a flawed fuel injector caused some cars to emit black
smoke, which violated American pollution laws.
   But Canadian authorities cannot force a similar recall because,
until September 1987, Canadian emission laws were far less
stringent than those in the United States, according to Chrysler's
Canadian subsidiary, which has refused a request by Transport
Canada to recall the cars.
   ``We met with Chrysler in July,'' says David Gourley of the
department's energy emissions branch. ``But they said there was no
reason to recall the cars because they met Canadian standards at
the time (the cars were sold).''
   A Chrysler Canada Ltd. spokesman said Friday the company can't
afford to recall old cars to comply with new laws.
   ``Where would you draw the line on something like that, 1902?''
the spokesman asked.
   Most Chrysler K-cars, including Plymouth Reliants and Dodge
Aries, were among the models recalled in the United States.
   Canadian emission-control laws for passenger cars were changed
in September to meet standards the United States has used since
1981.
   Chrysler extended its fuel-injector warranty on the questioned
models to 80,000 kilometres from 20,000 kilometres in February.
   In the meantime, Gourley says the only way to force Chrysler to
recall the cars is to take the automaker to court, where his branch
would need ``a smoking gun...a smoking Chrysler'' to win its case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
