<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Sharply Lower On Wet Weather</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean, corn and oat futures plunged their
permitted daily limits early in today's session on the Chicago
Board of Trade in reaction to heavy overnight rainfall overnight in
western and central Iowa.
   Wheat futures also were sharply lower.
   Rain was headed east into the central Corn Belt, where a
summer-long drought has wreaked severe damage on the corn and
soybean crops.
   But analysts said the rain was coming too late to greatly
benefit the crops; corn plants passed their most vulnerable period
in mid-July and most of the soybean crop is past the critical
pod-setting stage.
   ``This rain should not really do that much damage to prices; we
might see a rally,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader in Chicago
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   Corn and oat futures are limited to daily moves of 10 cents a
bushel. The wheat limit is 15 cents and the soybeans are limited to
moves of 30 cents a bushel except for the August soybean contract,
which has no limit pending its expiration today.
   In early trading, wheat was 8 cents to 10\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.81{ a bushel; corn was 2}
cents to 9} cents lower with September at $2.77{ a bushel; oats
were 6 cents to 10 cents lower with September at $2.49 a bushel;
soybeans were 11 cents to 36{ cents lower with August at $8.33 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly lower in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .08 cent to .85 cent lower with October at
71.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .45 cent to 1.15 cents
lower with August at 81.65 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent to .83
cent lower with October at 40.70 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .47 cent to .77 cent lower with August at 36.50 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settle mixed on Friday.
</TEXT>
