<1ST_LINE>r f AM-NameThatBank     08-22 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Name That Bank,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper Begins Bank Name Contest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank trivia buffs have a chance to cash
in on their knowledge in a record year for mergers, closings and
consolidations.
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram began a contest Monday challenging
readers to match Texas institutions' old and new names.
   The newspaper, which advertised the contest in its business
section, said the grand prize is not a blank check, but it is
``reported to be more valuable than a certificate of stock from
River Plaza National Bank (or just about any other bank, for that
matter). We'll provide details later.''
   The contest was dubbed the First American Texas National Bank
contest and survey.
   Many bank names are combinations of First, National, American,
Texas, and of course, Bank. The contest is a challenge because many
Texas institutions use arrangements of those and other words.
   Also, contestants must pick a new name for the latest impending
north Texas bank merger, involving the company that owns Texas
American Bank-Fort Worth and National Bancshares Corp. of Texas in
San Antonio.
   The union will create another bank identity, but it is uncertain
whether the new institution will be renamed, said Anne Quinn, Texas
American marketing vice president.
</TEXT>
