<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-22 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Sharply Lower To Limit Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of soybeans, corn and oats
plummeted their permitted daily limits Monday on the Chicago Board
of Trade in reaction to heavy showers in Iowa and slack foreign
demand for U.S. grain and soybean products.
   Wheat futures also closed sharply lower.
   Rain was moving east into the central Corn Belt, where a
summer-long drought has inflicted severe damage on the corn and
soybean crops. But analysts said the rain was coming too late to
greatly benefit the crops; corn plants passed their most vulnerable
period in mid-July and most of the soybean crop is past the
critical pod-setting stage.
   ``The rain was the catalyst'' for the sell-off, said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``But the thing behind it all is that demand is still not very
good,'' he said. ``We need an increase in demand to get this market
moving and we're just not getting it.''
   Mickey Luth, a soybean analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
in Chicago, agreed. ``The market's waiting for the demand to
develop, and with no players, it moves lower,'' he said.
   Corn and oat futures were limited to daily moves of 10 cents a
bushel. The wheat limit was 15 cents and soybeans were limited to
moves of 30 cents a bushel except for the expiring August soybean
contract, which had no limit.
   Wheat settled 7} cents to 11{ cents lower with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.81 a bushel; corn was 3} cents to 10
cents lower with September at $2.77\ a bushel; oats were 9{ cents
to 10 cents lower with September at $2.49 a bushel; and soybeans
were 23{ cents to 32{ cents lower with August at $8.37 a bushel.
</TEXT>
