<2ND_LINE>AM-Wickes, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0188,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Management Buyout Offer Invites Higher Bids</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 13th graf pvs, In announcing ..., to CORRECT to 1987
sted 1977</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A management group's offer to take
Wickes Cos. Inc. private in a $598 million leveraged buyout has
brought numerous inquiries from other potential buyers, the
company's investment banker said Monday.
   The $12-a-share tender offer, made late Sunday by a management
group led by Wickes Chairman Sanford Sigoloff, included a 60-day
wait before the group would begin buying Wickes stock to give other
bidders a chance to emerge.
   Numerous potential buyers called Monday, said Michael
Tennenbaum, senior managing director at Bear Stearns & Co. Inc.,
which was retained to advise Wickes management on the offer.
Tennenbaum wouldn't reveal names, but said some callers were
interested in buying the company intact and others sought
information on some of its parts.
   ``Our phones have been ringing off the hook,'' Tennenbaum said.
``People who have a prima facie financial capacity to do this
transaction are calling in impressive numbers.''
   Wickes' stock closed at $13.25 a share Monday on the New York
Stock Exchange, up $3.87 a share from Friday's close.
   A buyer of Wickes would have to assume $2.1 billion in debt. The
company's main lines of business are industrial products, including
auto fabrics and aircraft and missile parts; home improvement and
furnishings, including Wickes Furniture and Builders Emporium
do-it-yourself stores in Southern California; and a group that
makes wallpaper and carpet.
   Sigoloff, who led Wickes out of bankruptcy proceedings 3{ years
ago, said the management group financed by Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. wouldn't begin buying shares until Oct. 20, and didn't make it
a condition of the deal that the company refuse other bids.
   ``While we believe that our offer is fair, both management and
the board want to ensure that the company's shareholders obtain the
best price for their shares,'' Sigoloff said in a news release
announcing the leveraged buyout offer.
   The 60-day delay in purchasing shares was intended ``to ensure
that ample opportunity is afforded to determine whether it is
possible to achieve a higher price for our stockholders,'' he said.
   Sigoloff refused an interview request Monday, and a company
spokesman declined to expand on Sunday's statement.
   The group is offering $12 a share for up to 83 percent of
Wickes' 49.8 million outstanding shares. If the buyout is
consummated, each share that isn't purchased would be exchanged for
a share of a new class of preferred stock valued at $12 a share.
   The offer is contingent on 50 percent of outstanding shares
being offered for sale, and on obtaining financing, the company
said.
   In announcing the buyout offer, Wickes said it lost $12.4
million in the second quarter, in contrast to its profit of $18.9
million in the second quarter of 1987. Second-quarter sales were
$937.9 million, up from $865 million a year earlier.
   Sigoloff and others in management run little risk in making the
offer, said Leslie W. Childress, an analyst who follows the company
for Harper, McLean & Co. in Seattle.
   ``They win either way,'' Childress said. ``They either are
successful and get it at $12 a share ... or somebody comes in and
offers a bit more and they win anyway.''
   Some analysts suggested the heavy debt burden made it unlikely
the price would rise much beyond the $12 offer. Others suggested
potential buyers might be interested in various of Wickes' diverse
businesses rather than in running the company as presently
organized.
   ``What you have in Wickes are leadership niches in three major
markets,'' said Gerald S. May of PaineWebber in New York. He valued
the company at $12 to $15 a share.
   Sigoloff brought the company out of bankruptcy in January 1985
to embark on a buying spree that included the acquisition of
consumer and industrial products lines from Gulf and Western Corp.,
home improvement businesses from W.R. Grace & Co. and Collins &
Aikman Corp., a New York manufacturer of auto interiors, fabrics
and wallpaper.
   Wickes made unsuccessful bids for National Gypsum of Dallas,
Owens-Corning Fiberglass Corp. of Toledo, Ohio, and Lear Siegler
Inc., a Southern California aerospace and auto equipment
manufacturer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
