<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-22 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0621</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher; Gold Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mostly higher Monday in
skittish domestic trading after rising sharply overseas in the face
of concerted central-bank intervention.
   Gold prices were mixed. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a late bid price for gold of $433.20 a troy ounce, up from
$431.25 late Friday.
   The dollar gained over the weekend in the Far East and continued
to move higher when trading shifted to Europe. Dealers said there
was no fundamental reason for the dollar's strength except that the
market simply is bullish toward the currency.
   ``The dollar is the flavor of the month, and people are going
for it,'' said Keith Dipple, chief dealer at Banque Francaise de
Commerce Exterieure.
   A host of European central banks joined the Federal Reserve in
selling dollars when the currency was trading at about 1.9150 West
German marks, but dealers said the dollar slipped only temporarily
and then resumed its rise.
   The dollar closed higher in Europe and managed to finish mostly
higher in domestic dealings despite a heavy bout of profit-taking
and late central-bank intervention.
   ``It was really wild on the downside,'' said Frank Watson, vice
president at Swiss Bank Corp., commenting on the tumble the dollar
took when the Fed intervened.
   Despite the intervention, the dollar ``is still well in
demand,'' said Ronald Holzer, chief dealer at Harris Trust and
Savings Bank in Chicago.
   He noted that investors ``are getting more and more complacent
about intervention _ they are more willing to hold onto dollars''
when the central banks sell the currency.
   Traders noted that the market was very thin. ``There's a lack of
liquidity,'' Watson said. ``That accentuates the dollar's moves.''
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 0.48 yen to a closing 133.88 yen. Later in London,
it was quoted higher at 134.05 yen. In New York the dollar closed
at 133.63 yen, down from 133.69 yen on Friday.
   The pound fell sharply against the dollar. One dealer cited
disappointment that an expected increase in British interest rates
didn't materialize.
   In London it cost $1.6767 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.7025
late Friday. In New York it cost $1.6860 to buy one pound, less
expensive than late Friday's $1.6987.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday,
included: 1.9086 West German marks, up from 1.8965; 1.6075 Swiss
francs, up from 1.5954; 6.4680 French francs, up from 6.4193;
1,412.00 Italian lire, up from 1,405.00, and 1.2285 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2301.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday: 1.9190
West German marks, up from 1.8925; 1.6105 Swiss francs, up from
1.5915; 6.5050 French francs, up from 6.4125; 2.1605 Dutch
guilders, up from 2.1390; 1,417.00 Italian lire, up from 1,405.50,
and 1.2291 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2271.
   Gold for current delivery on the New York Commodity Exchange
rose to $433.60 a troy ounce from $431.70 late Friday.
   Gold held steady in London, finishing at a late bid price of
$432 a troy ounce, unchanged from Friday's late bid. In Zurich,
gold fell to a closing bid of $431 an ounce, compared with $432.50
late Friday. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.61 to close at a
bid $432.01 an ounce, compared with Saturday's $433.62.
   Silver prices also were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver for
current delivery rose to $6.730 a troy ounce, from $6.657 late
Friday. Silver bullion prices fell in London, where the metal was
trading at a late bid price of $6.64 an ounce, compared with
Friday's $6.68.
</TEXT>
