<2ND_LINE>AM-Chevron Chief, 1st Ld-Writethru,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevron's New Chief Sees Oil Prices Under $20</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CLARIFY that Derr made remarks at news
conference; picks up 3rd graf pvs bg'ng, ``Ultimately oil ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new chief of Chevron Corp. said Monday
he is basing his plans for the nation's fourth-largest energy
company on oil prices below $20 a barrel.
   Kenneth T. Derr, 52, elected chief executive officer last Friday
by the company's board of directors, also told a news conference he
expects oil prices to continue to move in a volatile pattern.
   ``Ultimately oil prices are going to increase significantly,''
said Derr, who takes over from George M. Keller on Jan. 1. Chevron
will ``continue with an (oil) exploration program and projects that
will be important to us,'' he added.
   The selection of Derr, who has been one of Chevron's two vice
chairmen for nearly three years, was widely expected. It follows
the company's report that it earned $520 million in the second
quarter, up 45 percent from its profits in the year-earlier quarter.
   Derr's most challenging assignment at the company was his
supervision of the merger with Gulf Corp. following Chevron's $13.3
billion acquisition of Gulf in 1984.
   Keller, 64, will take mandatory retirement at 65 after more than
seven years at the helm of Chevron.
   Derr's appointment isn't expected to bring major changes at the
international oil giant, obsevers said.
   In response to a question, Derr noted the fierce opposition by
environmentalists to oil drilling offshore Northern California. He
gave a strong hint, however, of what Chevron's attitude on the
question will be.
   ``I think the country is facing serious problems in the future
in terms of its energy supplies, '' he said. ``(Oil) imports are up
to 40 percent (of total U.S. consumption) today; they'll be over 50
percent in the next couple of years, and who knows from there?
   ``I think it's important that the country adopts policies that
allow for maximum development of U.S. energy reserves,'' he added.
</TEXT>
