<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Broadly Lower, Dow Industrials At Nearly Three-Month Low</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout. CORRECTS Amex change
in last graf to decline of 2.02 sted 2.002.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest-rate worries drove the stock market
broadly lower on Monday, pushing the closing Dow Jones Industrial
Average below 2,000 for the first time in nearly three months.
   ``This is very nervous trading,'' said Jack Baker, head of block
trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``This isn't the kind of
market that's going to bring people off the sidelines.''
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which lost 21.52 points
last week, gave up another 25.78 to close at 1,990.22.
   That was the lowest closing level for the market's best-known
indicator since it finished at 1,956.44 on May 27, the day before
the three-day Memorial Day holiday. When traders returned May 31,
the Dow climbed 74.68 points and the industrial average finished
above 2,000 every day since then.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of nearly 3 to 1
among issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange, with 385 up,
1,107 down and 466 unchanged. The NYSE index fell 1.60 to 145.94.
   The pace of trading was sluggish, however. Volume on the floor
of the NYSE amounted to 122.25 million shares, down from 122.37
million shares on Friday. Nationwide, consolidated volume in
NYSE-listed issues, including trading at regional exchanges and on
the over-the-counter market, totaled 144.90 million shares.
   As the market opened, stock prices pushed marginally higher, but
quickly reversed course when a decline in bond prices drove
fixed-income yields higher.
   Analysts said the yields available in the bond and money markets
are keeping many investors out of the stock market. That
inclination was even more pronounced on the eve of the first of a
flurry of economic reports due to be released this week, analysts
said.
   The government plans to report Tuesday on consumer prices for
July. Later in the week, it planned to revise its estimate of
second-quarter economic growth, among other things.
   The economy has been growing at such a strong pace that the
Federal Reserve boosted its rate on loans to member banks by a half
percentage point to 6.5 percent earlier this month in a bid to head
off inflation.
   Shearson's Baker said traders were worried that Tuesday's
consumer price report would show a big jump that would encourage
the central bank to push rates even higher. That would make
Treasury issues even more attractive to big institutional investors
compared with the uncertain returns on stocks.
   On Monday, prices of the widely-followed 30-year Treasury bond
fell $5 for every $1,000 in face value, pushing its yield to 9.45
percent from 9.39 percent on Friday.
   Alfred E. Goldman, director of technical market analysis for the
brokerage A.G. Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis, said yields on
shorter term issues are also attractive. He noted that 5-year
Treasury issues are yielding about 9 percent, for instance, while
the Dow Jones industrials have lost more than 160 points since
early July.
   ``As long as stocks are going down, these will provide some very
stiff competition for the investors dollar ... The institutional
investor who has substantial cash reserves is saying, `Why bother?
I'll take a safe haven until the economic uncertainties clarify
themselves','' Goldman said.
   Wickes was among the most actively-traded issues on the NYSE,
jumping 3~ to 13\. A management-led group proposed Sunday to take
the company private in a leveraged buyout at $12 a share in cash
and stock.
   There was also some interest in utility stocks that have either
recently passed or are approaching deadlines for investors to
qualify for dividends. Philadelphia Electric was the most active
issue, down [ at 17}, while Kansas City Power & Light rose \ to 29~.
   Among actively traded blue chips, American Telephone & Telegraph
fell { to 24\, Ford tumbled 1} to 46~ and International Business
Machines fell 2 to 110}.
   Several airline stocks fell. AMR, the parent of American
Airlines, was off 1 at 42\, and UAL, parent of United Airlines,
fell 2| to 88|.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, fell $26.896 billion, or 1.03 percent, to
$2.576 trillion.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index fell 3.95 to 294.49, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index was off 3.26 to 256.98.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 2.02
to 293.01. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 373.73, down 3.69.
</TEXT>
