<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Miners-Suit 2ndLd-Writethru f0226 08-22 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miners-Suit, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0226,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Miners Sue Union</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS two grafs of background</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PIKEVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of miners Monday filed a $1
billion federal lawsuit against the United Mine Workers of America
and its leadership, claiming the union prevented it from recovering
wages lost during a 3{-year strike.
   The lawsuit contended the union did not represent the miners
properly and discriminated against them because they did not take
part in selective picketing.
   Named in the suit filed in U.S. District Court included Rich
Trumka, UMW president; Cecil Roberts, vice president; and John
Banovick, secretary-treasurer. Each was accused of conspiring to
keep the 406 plaintiffs from collecting benefits to which they
should have been entitled.
   Jerry Hammond, a spokesman for the so-called ``Forgotten 400,''
said the lawsuit stemmed from an agreement reached in May between
the UMW and the A.T. Massey Coal Co. and its subsidiaries to end
selective strikes launched against two eastern Kentucky mines in
1984.
   The agreement, requiring payment of $4.47 million to the union,
also settled a lawsuit challenging Massey's decision to turn the
mines into non-union operations.
   About 700 miners, including Hammond, worked at the two mines
until February 1983 when all but a maintenance crew were laid off.
   The remaining miners workers lost their jobs Sept. 30, 1984, the
day before the two mines were sold to Sidney Coal Co., a subsidiary
of Ora Mae Coal Co., an operation owned by Massey.
   After the agreement was announced, Roberts said the $4.47
million for lost wages and benefits would be divided among about
250 miners, who had been on selective strikes, with each receiving
about $18,000.
   Hammond, of Red Jacket, W.Va., said the lawsuit contends that
the UMW breached its duty of fair representation by limiting the
number of members who would receive payments.
   Hammond and other plaintiffs also contend they have been
excluded from union meetings, thus violating the organization's
constitution.
   The lawsuit asks for a jury trial, plus $500 million in
compensatory and $500 million in punitive damages.
   In Washington, union spokesman Joseph Corcoran said late Monday
that the union's legal department had not yet seen the lawsuit. But
Corcoran said, ``The union is very confident that that settlement
will be upheld in any court.''
   Trumka pushed for the union's use of selective strikes, and on
Oct. 1, 1984 Massey became the first target after the company
refused to sign the union's national coal wage contract. Signing
would have given Massey's laid-off employees companywide
re-employment rights.
   The union finally called off the sometimes violent strike in
December 1985 when Massey agreed to settlement of an unfair labor
practice charge, but selective strikes against the two subsidiaries
continued until May.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-HuttonSettlement     08-22 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hutton Settlement,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rockwood and Hutton Settle Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOMERSET, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rockwood Insurance Co. has agreed to pay
more than $1 million to settle lawsuits involving E.F. Hutton Group
in a complex mortgage insurance case, Rockwood officials announced
Monday.
   Robert E. Lauterbach, a member of Rockwood's board and chairman
of its executive committee, said the settlement included a payment
of $550,000 on Monday plus $200,000 annually for three years
beginning in 1989. The agreement also provided for both parties to
mutually release all outstanding liabilities.
   ``The payments are a modest settlement to get rid of all the
litigation,'' Lauterbach said. ``We felt it was worthwhile to
settle it and get it behind us. We consider this an extremely
satisfactory settlement.''
   In 1985, Hutton _ which was acquired earlier this year by
Shearson Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. _ announced plans to sue
First American Mortgage Co. of Maryland in connection with Hutton's
purchase of about $64 million in mortgage loans from First
American. A major portion of the loans was delinquent, and Hutton
claimed the loans were insured fully by Rockwood.
   Subsidiary E.F. Hutton Mortgage Corp. sued Rockwood Insurance
Co. in 1986, seeking recovery under the surety bond issued by the
company.
   The suit demanded Rockwood pay Hutton the amount of the
outstanding balances of all delinquent loans, which then totaled
more than $32 million and with more delinquencies could have
increased to the full amount of the loans.
   Rockwood sued E.F. Hutton Mortgage Corp., alleging
non-compliance and violations of the surety bond and asking the
court to declare the bond void and unenforceable.
   Rockwood Insurance and Rockwood Holding Co. also filed a
separate complaint seeking damages from E.F. Hutton & Co. and its
parent, E.F. Hutton Group, in connection with the transactions
between Hutton Mortgage, First American Mortgage and Rockwood
Insurance.
   In May, a federal judge dismissed Hutton's motions to have
Rockwood's complaints dismissed and Rockwood's motion to dismiss
the Hutton complaint.
   Lauterbach said that since the litigation the company has
stopped writing financial insurance, such as the mortgage insurance
that was at issue in the Hutton litigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880822-0289 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-22-88 2246EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Venezuela-LatinDebt     08-22 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Venezuela-Latin Debt,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela President Blasts Foreign Creditor Banks at International
Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuelan President Jaime Lusinchi
leveled harsh criticism at foreign commercial banks Monday,
blasting them for what he called their ``speculative'' treatment of
Latin American debtors.
   ``Either we are loyal to our peoples and we look after their
well-being, or we yield with those who impose conditions on us and
violate our rights, and who only feel egoism, opulence and
insatiable avarice,'' Lusinchi told conference delegates from 23
Spanish and Portuguese-speaking nations of America and Europe.
   ``The speculative criteria that predominates in big financial
centers is incompatible with the interest of all people on earth,''
Lusinchi said.
   The president spoke during the opening ceremony of the Sixth
IberoAmerican Conference held to organize the planned 1992
celebrations of the 500th anniversary of the discovery of America.
   Lusinchi's remarks come as Venezuela is seeking about $2.5
billion in new loans from foreign financial institutions to help
cover a balance of payments deficit.
   Commercial banks widely are expected to seek economic austerity
measures as a condition for new lending to Venezuela.
   Lusinchi labeled as ``absurd'' Latin America's current economic
situation, in which countries from Mexico to Argentina are
struggling to pay foreign debts of over $400 billion. Venezuela,
which has a $34 billion foreign debt, is the region's
fourth-largest debtor.
   ``This is a threat to our most elemental rights, against our
democratic stability, and against our societies that want
well-being and freedom,'' he said.
   Lusinchi earlier this month sent a financial mission to the
United States and Europe to seek new debt financing.
   Venezuelan officials claim commercial bank creditors have
reneged on a promise included in a 1987 partial debt refinancing to
provide Venezuela with new funds and help it regain access to
international financial markets.
   But despite recent rumors that Venezuela might declare a
unilateral debt payment moratorium, Lusinchi and other top
administration officials have said any suspension of payments would
occur only if the financial mission failed and only in concert with
commercial banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
